outlooksByWeek.1: When Cook is healthy and on the field, he's an exciting player to watch -- and a great option for your fantasy lineup. However, through two seasons it's clear that "healthy and on the field" might be more rare than we'd hope for the Florida State product. He's only played in 15 games over two seasons. He seems to be ready to go for Week 1, however, which means he'll get a shot as the team's primary back against an Atlanta defense which ranked among the top 10 most generous in terms of both yards and touchdowns allowed last season. Start him with confidence as an RB1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Cook looked strong in Week 1, leading the Vikings in both carries and yards while scoring a pair of touchdowns -- and catching a couple of passes, as well. He'll look to do more of the same against the Packers in Week 2, although that is a considerably worse matchup than the one against the Falcons to open the season. Green Bay looked solid on defense against the Bears in Week 1, so don't expect another huge game from Cook. Do lock him in as an RB2 regardless.
outlooksByWeek.3: Volume is king in fantasy football, and among running backs, Cook is the king of volume. No other back seems to be as integral to his team's offense, as the Vikings look to Cook in all situations. Only Marlon Mack has more carries, but Cook averages 1.5 more yards-per-attempt than the Colts running back. Cook even received 20 carries in a game that his team trailed 21-0 at one point, in Week 2 against the Packers. There's no reason to doubt the FSU product in Week 3, not even against a Raiders defense that has been surprisingly stingy against the run.
outlooksByWeek.4: No team favors the run over the pass quite like the Vikings, and that's been great news for Cook so far in 2019. His 57 attempts rank fourth in the NFL while his 375 yards are first overall. He's gone over 100 yards and scored a rushing touchdown in each of the first three games -- and he has also seen a few targets in the passing game. He's competing with Christian McCaffrey and Austin Ekeler for the top spot on the scoring charts -- and winning so far, according to ESPN-standard scoring. Week 4 will be a difficult one as the Vikings travel to Chicago to take on the Bears, but that's no reason to bench the Florida State product. Lower your expectationS slightly, but Cook remains an RB1.

player.seasonOutlook: Now two seasons into his NFL career, Cook has made it through only 13 games healthy. Though durability is obviously a concern, volume and efficiency are not. During those 13 weeks, Cook handled 61 percent of the team's designed runs (14.2 per game) and 14 percent of the targets (4.7 per game). He's averaging 4.7 YPC (2.1 YAC) on 207 career attempts. Cook has yet to emerge as a consistent fantasy threat, but did post the seventh-most fantasy points at the position after Week 12 last season, which aligned both with his return to full health and Minnesota's move to a run-first offense. Minnesota is expected to operate a run-heavy scheme in 2019, and Cook has minimal competition for touches. He's a breakout candidate and strong RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: We've yet to see Chubb thrive as a receiving threat but, atop an otherwise thin depth chart, he could finally feast on all downs in what is an inviting enough matchup. The Titans, after all, were a bottom-half rush defense last season and yielded more than two yards after contact per rush to tailbacks.
outlooksByWeek.2: The Titans held Chubb in check for much of Week 1, but the workload—20 total touches—was inspired. The Jets rank 16th in defending running backs on the ground since the start of last season and have allowed the eighth-most yards after contact per rush, an area in which Chubb thrives. Few backs can be trusted to handle 20 touches each week for a capable offense the Browns'. Chubb is a strong RB1 option for Monday night.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Browns host the Rams on Sunday and, despite a strong defensive reputation, the Rams have allowed the eighth-most rushing yards to tailbacks since the start of last season—including a generous 4.9 per carry over that time. One of just six players averaging at least 20 touches this season, Chubb's uptick in receiving involvement since last season vaults him into the position's coveted bell-cow tier.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Georgia product netted the second-most carries of his career on his way to a season-high 96 rushing yards for the Browns. The Ravens have allowed the seventh-fewest fantasy points to enemy backfields this year, but LeSean McCoy's success in Week 3 against Baltimore is a good sign for Chubb's upside this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Chubb opened his NFL career buried behind both Carlos Hyde and Duke Johnson, but it didn't take long for the 2018 second-round pick to force his way into a massive role. Once he took over as the lead back in Week 7, Chubb handled 80 percent of the Browns' designed runs and 10 percent of the targets, and only seven backs scored more fantasy points. For the entire season, Chubb averaged 5.2 YPC (10th-highest at the position), including 2.41 after contact (seventh-best), and he averaged 0.53 fantasy points per snap, which was fourth-highest among backs. Chubb will open 2019 as Cleveland's clear feature back, though a limited role as a receiver and the return of Kareem Hunt around midseason limit his upside a bit. Chubb is best viewed as a strong RB2 in Cleveland's improved offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ertz was justifiably one of the top tight ends drafted in fantasy leagues, following a 2018 season with a (by far) career-high 1,163 yards and 116 receptions ,while tying his career-best with eight touchdowns. Though Washington held him to a 15-yard performance in Week 17 last year, he torched them for nine catches and 83 yards in Week 13. A near lock to approach double-digit targets most weeks, Ertz remains among the top fantasy options at his position for the 2019 opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ertz didn't find the end zone in Week 1 but still had a serviceable TE fantasy day, which is the minimum you'd want from such a high pick. The Falcons didn't give up a catch to any Vikings tight end in Week 1, but don't let that deter you from parking Ertz in fantasy TE1 territory.
outlooksByWeek.3: Ertz, who caught eight passes in Week 2, may be even busier than usual in Week 3 if at least one of Alshon Jeffery (calf), DeSean Jackson (groin) and Dallas Goedert (calf) is forced to be inactive. Regardless of how this injury picture shakes out, Ertz remains a top-flight fantasy TE1 against the Lions.
outlooksByWeek.4: Ertz had 64 yards in Week 3 (catching 4-of-7 targets) with Alshon Jeffery (calf) and DeSean Jackson (groin) out. The quick turnaround to Thursday's game at Green Bay probably will have Jackson out again, but Jeffery has a chance to suit up. That could take some defensive attention off Ertz, who remains a strong fantasy TE1 in Week 4, despite Green Bay's strong fantasy defense versus tight ends (5.7 points-per-game, the fourth-lowest mark).

player.seasonOutlook: Ertz set the all-time tight end record with 116 receptions last season and was fantasy's No. 2 scorer at the position. Incredibly, Ertz has improved his fantasy point total each of his seasons in the NFL and has now posted four consecutive top-nine finishes. He paced all tight ends in snaps (949), routes (550) and targets (156), while ranking top-four in receiving yards (1,163), touchdowns (eight) and end-zone targets (nine) last season. After struggling in the area during his first four seasons, Ertz has scored exactly eight touchdowns in back-to-back seasons. The 28-year-old is an elite, high-floor fantasy option who could defer some targets to DeSean Jackson and Dallas Goedert and still post a top-three fantasy season. He'll cost you a third-round pick this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Touchdown regression is almost surely coming for Williams after his 10-score performance last season. Countering this could be an uptick in overall usage and production. The Colts were stingy against wideouts last season, but a blend of red zone and big-play potential supports WR3 value for Williams.
outlooksByWeek.2: Williams wasn't very busy in Week 1 in seeing just four targets, but he was also a key focus of the Colts' defense. A stronger Week 2 showing could be in the books if the Lions use top corner Darius Slay to shadow Keenan Allen. Somewhat of a boom-or-bust player dependent on big plays around the red zone, Williams remains in the starting mix among receivers heading into Motown.
outlooksByWeek.3: Questionable with a knee injury heading in, Williams gamely handled 25 routes in Week 2 and delivered an impressive 83 yards in the loss to the Lions. The Texans don't pose a great threat to Williams' production potential given their struggles in coverage in the secondary, thus Williams is a worthy WR3 or flex option this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Limited to just 15 targets on the season so far, Williams has yet to meet expectations in 2019. The good news is a matchup with Miami looms, setting up this big-play maven with a choice opportunity to deliver vertical plays against a Dolphins defense allowing 16.7 yards per reception to wideouts.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams managed a top 35 fantasy campaign last season despite handling more than six targets in only two games. Touchdowns were the difference-maker for the 2017 first-round pick, as he scored 10 times on 66 targets. That 15.2 percent hit rate was tops at the position and is far from sustainable. Williams racked up 12 end zone targets (13th most), but his 6.2 OTD suggests he was over his head. The good news is that Williams' efficiency was otherwise good. He caught 65 percent of his targets despite a 14.6 aDOT (10th highest) and ranked 11th in both YPR (15.4) and YPT (10.1). Williams caught a first down on a position-best 44 percent of his targets. Tyrell Williams' departure sets up Williams with a larger role in his second season. He's an obvious breakout candidate and WR3 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Heading for a starting role against the Colts this week with Melvin Gordon still holding out for a new contract, Ekeler is likely to split rushing duties nearly evenly with Justin Jackson but most valuably should dominate passing work. A solid RB2 option with Gordon not playing, Ekeler is in a strong spot to return value against a Colts team that allowed the seventh-most receiving yards to backs last year.
outlooksByWeek.2: An awesome opener for Ekeler saw him become the first Chargers player with 150 yards from scrimmage and three touchdowns in a season opener. With receiving and red zone duties secured while Melvin Gordon holds out, Ekeler is in a strong spot to replicate the solid scrimmage showing David Johnson enjoyed against the Lions last week. Given his awesome receiving role, Ekeler is knocking on the RB1 door in PPR formats for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: A costly fumble this past week hurt the Chargers' chances in Detroit, but overall Ekeler remains an awesome fantasy option and a plus playmaker for the Chargers. The Texans have struggled against gifted receiving backs since the start of last season, setting up Ekeler with another RB1 projection.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Dolphins have allowed a league-high 535 rushing yards to tailbacks on the season to go with four rushing scores. Ekeler is on pace for a historically great receiving campaign and has seemingly consolidated goal-line duties, as well. With a choice matchup in Miami, Ekeler is firmly in the must-start tier of tailbacks.

player.seasonOutlook: Granted, it has been in a situational role behind Melvin Gordon, but Ekeler has been one of the league's most efficient backs since he entered the league as an undrafted free agent in 2017. Ekeler is averaging 5.3 YPC (2.4 YAC) on 153 carries and 7.9 YPT on 86 targets in 30 career games. He ranked fourth in YAC last season and has finished top-six in YPR and YPT in both seasons. He has also ranked top-eight in fantasy points per snap both seasons. The 24-year-old will be on the early-season RB1 radar with Gordon continuing his lengthy holdout and could flirt with standalone value once Gordon does report. Ekeler is a good mid-round target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite not starting until Week 10 of his rookie season, Jackson compiled an incredible 695 yards on the ground—the ninth-most by a quarterback in a season since 2001. His sophomore campaign begins against an exploitable Miami defense that allowed the seventh-most rushing yards per attempt and the eighth-most points per drive in 2018. Jackson can deliver QB1 numbers in the opener despite being drafted as a backup option in most leagues.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jackson's five-score opus saw him become the first player in Ravens history with a perfect passer rating in a game and the first with one in a season opener in NFL history. Jackson provided amazing statistical results with just six rushing yards against Miami in the opener, meaning his fantasy ceiling is somehow even higher once he lets loose on the ground. The visiting Cardinals posted the fourth-highest blitz rate in the league in Week 1, suggesting Jackson might have to evacuate the pocket a bit more in Week 2, adding to his already-intriguing fantasy potential. He's a breakout starting option.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jackson leads ESPN leagues in fantasy points through two games thanks to following up Week 1's five-score opus with just the second game in NFL history with at least 250 passing yards and 120 rushing yards. This unique dual-threat has rare upside for this meeting with a Chiefs team that has allowed the sixth-most points per drive to opponents since the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jackson is now 8-2 in his career as a starter in the regular season, with both losses at the Chiefs by a combined eight points. Big-play production in the Ravens' passing game this season has complemented Jackson's already elite rushing ability. Jackson is second only to Matthew Stafford with 22 pass attempts at least 20 yards downfield. Such verticality helps his fantasy forecast against an aggressive, but exploitable, Cleveland defense at home in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Jackson took "dual threat" quarterback to a new level during his rookie season, setting an NFL single-season quarterback record with 147 carries despite starting only seven regular-season games. Jackson averaged a massive 17.0 carries per game and ranked seventh in the entire NFL with 556 rushing yards during his seven starts. Jackson did, however, struggle as a passer. He completed 58 percent of his passes (fourth worst) and was off target on 22 percent of his throws (second worst). The Baltimore offense averaged 1.9 touchdowns per game during Jackson's starts, which would have ranked seventh worst over the full season. Jackson's legs provide him with QB1 upside, but a lack of passing volume and efficiency, coupled with inherent durability concerns makes him more of a QB2 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fitzgerald remains the top receiver in Arizona and, with rookie QB Kyler Murray, under center, the offense could see a bit of a spark compared to last year's lackluster performance. The veteran wideout has seen volume with every passer the Cardinals have put on the field throughout his career, so expect more of the same against Detroit. The Lions allowed the fifth-most yards-per-catch last season (7.9), so this is as good a matchup as any.
outlooksByWeek.2: Who are you calling "old?" The 36-year-old Pitt product looked like the same player we've seen for years, hauling in 8-of-13 targets for 113 yards and a score to kick off his 16th season in the NFL. Kyler Murray is certainly comfortable throwing to the experienced receiver, and Fitzgerald is just as comfortable finding ways to get open for the rookie. He's facing a very tough Ravens defense that limited DeVante Parker of the Dolphins to only three catches for 75 yards in Week 1, so consider him more of a flex pick than a WR2, given the difficulty of the matchup.
outlooksByWeek.3: The veteran Fitzgerald was always going to be a go-to option in the passing game for a rookie quarterback, and that has indeed proven to be the case through two weeks. He has seen 24 targets, 13 of which he's caught for a total of 217 yards. He's among the league leaders in targets and figures to keep getting a healthy dose of looks in the passing game against the Panthers in Week 3. Carolina allowed a big game to Chris Godwin in Week 2,  but are otherwise a pretty solid pass defense. Consider Fitzgerald as a borderline WR2 who makes for a great flex if you have better options ahead of him.
outlooksByWeek.4: While the Chargers' Keenan Allen is on another planet and in first place in targets in the NFL, the veteran Fitzgerald is right in the mix at the top of the league in the opportunity metric of choice for receivers. He's turned those opportunities into fantasy points on a routine basis, scoring in double-digits every week and finding the end zone twice. This week, his Cardinals will face a Seattle defense which allowed John Ross to have a breakout game in Week 1, but has otherwise kept wide receivers quiet this season. That's no reason to downgrade Fitzgerald out of your lineup, however, as he's squarely in the WR2 discussion.

player.seasonOutlook: A future Hall of Famer, Fitzgerald will return for his 16th NFL season. The 2004 first-round pick posted three-consecutive seasons with at least 107 receptions and 1,023 yards prior to regressing in 2018, when he posted a 69/734/6 line and finished 25th in fantasy points. In addition, he managed only two top-20 fantasy weeks. Quarterback play was an obvious issue, helping Fitzgerald to a 6.6 YPT, which was ninth-worst at the position and his worst mark in the category since 2012. It's possible Kliff Kingsbury's modern offense can help Fitzgerald to a rebound season, but it's hard to see a ton of upside for a 36-year-old receiver, especially after Arizona drafted three wide receivers. Fitzgerald is best-viewed as a flex option.

Tucker was fantasy's No. 2 scoring kicker last season and has now finished no lower than 11th during any of his seven NFL seasons. His 10 top-10 fantasy weeks last season led the NFL. Baltimore's kicker remains one of the best in the business. He connected on 35 of 39 field goal attempts last season (89.7 percent) and has made 38 of 54 attempts (70.4 percent) from 50-plus yards during his career. The 29-year-old is an elite fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: This was a best-case landing spot for McCoy, if not a troubling addition for fantasy investors in other parts of this backfield. McCoy isn't likely to consume a ton of touches right away for Andy Reid, especially against a solid front seven. "Shady's" season-long prospects appear brighter than this initial matchup indicates.
outlooksByWeek.2: McCoy was second worst among qualifying rushers last season with just 3.2 yards per carry, so netting 8.1 per attempt on 10 tries in Week 1 is a promising turn. This is still clearly a committee approach for Kansas City, but it's possible McCoy can ascend into a bigger role if he continues to prove efficient. For this meeting in Oakland, McCoy is a somewhat risky flex given it's mostly a gamble on a short touchdown.
outlooksByWeek.3: As the team's closing back this past week, McCoy led the team with 14 total touches but tallied just 23 scrimmage yards in the process. The usage is much more encouraging than the production for McCoy, but even a nice role on the Chiefs isn't enough to offset this difficult matchup with a Baltimore defense that has held opposing backs to just 28 rushing yards on 1.56 yards per attempt this season, the stingiest defensive rates in the NFL currently.
outlooksByWeek.4: Fresh from producing his first game since 2017 with a rushing and receiving score, McCoy could return to sharing meaningful touches with Damien Williams this week. The matchup is at least inviting, as the Lions have allowed the 10th-most rushing yards to tailbacks this season.

player.seasonOutlook: McCoy appeared in 14 games in 2018, but it still felt like a lost season for the veteran back. McCoy carried the ball 161 times (his lowest total since 2009) and was targeted on 43 occasions (his lowest since 2014). McCoy struggled to a career-low 3.19 YPC (third-worst at the position) and finished dead last in YAC (0.96) for the second consecutive season. McCoy's best weekly finish was 13th, and he failed to finish as a top-20 fantasy back for the first time since 2009. McCoy has rushed for six or fewer touchdowns four of the past five seasons. He's entering his age-31 season in a much better offense, as he'll compete with Damien Williams and Darwin Thompson for lead back roles in Kansas City. The Chiefs' elite offense makes McCoy a fine mid-round target.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Dolphins allowed the ninth-most touchdowns and third-most yards per catch to receivers last season, yet it’s unclear if Brown is ready for top billing in the Baltimore passing game given the rookie played sparingly in the preseason. It's best to see how this passing offense performs in Miami before starting Brown.
outlooksByWeek.2: All Brown did for the Ravens in Week 1 was become the first player in NFL history with multiple 40-yard receiving scores in his first game. The Cardinals are missing their top cover corner to suspension and saw an offseason shuffle at safety, so this matchup is an inviting spot for "Hollywood" to follow up on his historic debut.
outlooksByWeek.3: Brown's brilliant start to his career continued in Week 2, when he led the Ravens with 13 targets and a healthy 11.0 air yards per target in the process. Brown is emerging as a trusted fantasy play; he's the main target for Lamar Jackson heading into a game that has the highest point total on the Week 3 slate.
outlooksByWeek.4: Brown led the Ravens in targets at Arrowhead in Week 3 and leads the team for the season with a robust target-per-route rate of 34%. He's the clear top option in an emergent passing attack, and Cleveland has been middle-of-the-pack defending wide outs this season. The attention Brown gets from Lamar Jackson plus his unique vertical skill set make for another solid week as a flex option.

player.seasonOutlook: The Ravens selected Brown with the No. 25 pick in April's draft. The former Oklahoma Sooner is extremely small (5-foot-9, 166 pounds), but he is superfast with the ability to get behind the defense and make plays with the ball in his hands. Drops (eight last season) and durability (he suffered a Lisfranc injury prior to the draft) are red flags, but Brown has the skill set of DeSean Jackson and John Brown, which allows him plenty of upside. The biggest concern here is that Brown's short-term fantasy value will be hindered by Baltimore's extremely run-heavy offense and Lamar Jackson's shaky accuracy. Brown is only worth a late flier in 2019 fantasy drafts because he has a good chance to lead the team in targets as a rookie.

outlooksByWeek.1: A gifted vertical receiver drafted to pair with Pat Mahomes' strong arm, it will likely take months, if not longer, for Hardman to develop into a weekly fantasy threat. The Jaguars, meanwhile, surrendered just the fourth-fewest yards to receivers last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Rare 4.33 speed and what should be a sizable uptick in attention means Hardman is suddenly on the radar as a streaming option. Tyreek Hill's injury vaults Hardman into a starting outside role. We didn't see the rookie earn a target last week, but a soft defensive opponent and an expected uptick in work results in Hardman as a fun flier to consider.
outlooksByWeek.3: It was Demarcus Robinson who enjoyed gobs of air yardage and success with Pat Mahomes in Week 2 with Tyreek Hill absent, but in this somewhat equal-opportunity big-play offense, there's always room for Hardman to deliver flex-worthy results in a single play. The Ravens' back seven is uniquely equipped to handle Hardman's speed, so the floor is decidedly low for the rookie.
outlooksByWeek.4: With 14.4 air yards per target the past two weeks, Hardman's awesome per-catch rate of 26.3 yards appears somewhat sustainable. Afforded just a handful of targets each week, Hardman's prospects this week are somewhat boom-or-bust against Detroit's exploitable secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: The Chiefs selected Hardman in the second round of April's draft to complement Tyreek Hill, who has a similar skill set. Hardman is undersized at 5-foot-10, 187 pounds, but the Georgia product is extremely explosive and versatile. Hardman has terrific speed (4.33 40-yard dash) and toughness (17 bench reps) and dominates with the ball in his hands (8.7 RAC in 2018). He has struggled with drops (eight on 91 career targets) and fumbles (eight on 39 touches last season). Hardman figures to be utilized as a short-area RAC target, lid lifter and a returner. He's positioned for situational rookie season role in a high-scoring, Patrick Mahomes-led offense, which makes him a fine bench stash in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fourth in line for work behind several proven vets on the depth chart, Dorsett doesn't claim any fantasy value for this prime-time meeting with the Steelers.
outlooksByWeek.2: Dorsett delivered his first career multi-score game and also set a career high in yardage. As can be the case sometimes with one-week wonders, this could be Dorsett's strongest showing of the season, especially with more talent joining the receiving depth chart this week. Even in the wake of a great opener, leaving Dorsett on the wire might be the best play.
outlooksByWeek.3: Now the fourth receiver on the team and likely the sixth or seventh priority in the game plan once we factor in the backfield, Dorsett's awesome Week 1 isn't going to help you this week against the Jets.
outlooksByWeek.4: Second on the team in routes and third in targets this past Sunday, Dorsett tallied a solid line in the win over the Jets. We'll likely never see him match Week 1's awesome breakout performance, but Dorsett is at least in the streaming discussion in deep leagues against a Bills secondary that has been generous to receivers thus far.

player.seasonOutlook: Dorsett is back with the Patriots after managing only 60 targets in 31 games since joining the team. Dorsett was a full-time player during Julian Edelman's four-game suspension last season, but was limited to a 16/165/2 line and the 45th-most fantasy points among wideouts during the span. He was a non-factor for a majority of the rest of the season and failed to finish as a Top 75 fantasy receiver for the fourth time in four NFL seasons. The 2015 first-round pick spent his early career as a downfield target, but was used more in the short area in 2018 (10.3 aDOT). He's undersized at 5-foot-10, 185 pounds and offers little near the goal line (six career touchdowns). Dorsett has little value behind Julian Edelman, Josh Gordon and likely Demaryius Thomas.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite lacking top-end pass-rushing talent, this Ravens defense features Earl Thomas leading a gifted group of ball-hawks. The unit is in a choice spot against Ryan Fitzpatrick, who had the highest interception rate in the NFL last season (4.9). It should have fantasy managers salivating.
outlooksByWeek.2: Another choice matchup awaits the Ravens' aggressive, ball-hawking defense. The Cardinals found their offensive groove late against the Lions in Week 1, but Kyler Murray struggled early and often as a passer, which helps support a strong projection for this D/ST in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: As productive as Baltimore's D/ST has been, a matchup with the Chiefs' video game offense at Arrowhead isn't an inviting one for fantasy managers. This game's point total already has risen to 55 at some books, which means this is expected to be a high-scoring matchup without strong defensive performances.
outlooksByWeek.4: The upside sell for this group begins with Baltimore's strong pass rush; the Ravens have pressured passers on 35.6% of dropbacks, the fourth-highest clip this season. The Browns, meanwhile, have allowed pressure on 35.3% of Baker Mayfield's dropbacks this year. Cleveland's offense is talented at the skill positions, but a porous offensive line could help this D/ST produce a solid showing.

player.seasonOutlook: Baltimore's D/ST has been a fantasy powerhouse for a long time, posting four top-seven campaigns the past five seasons and seven in the past 11 seasons. In 2018, the Ravens allowed a league-low 4,687 yards, and their 287 points allowed ranked second-best. On the other hand, the unit ranked 22nd in forced turnovers and was outside the top 10 in sacks for the fourth consecutive season. The worst news is that Baltimore lost its Nos. 1, 2, 5 and 7 snap-getters from 2018 (Eric Weddle, C.J. Mosley, Terrell Suggs, Za'Darius Smith). Earl Thomas was a strong addition, but this unit has more holes than we're used to. Expect a step back to more of a streaming option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Frequently the No. 1 overall pick in 2019 drafts, Barkley will remain a fantasy lineup fixture regardless of the matchup. The Cowboys were one of few defenses to at least contain him in 2018, though he still topped 100 scrimmage yards in both of those matchups. With his excellent work in the receiving game, Barkley will all but guarantee 20-plus touches each week. We have him ranked near the top of his position for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Barkley rattled off 139 scrimmage yards but only touched the ball 15 times in a failed Week 1 comeback attempt. He'll next face the Bills, who held Jets running backs in check in Week 1, though Le'Veon Bell did manage to find the end zone. Matchups rarely matter for Barkley, who again should be considered a surefire fantasy RB1 in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Barkley saw more work in Week 2 after his surprisingly low touch count in Week 1. Despite questions surrounding New York's offense, the star running back remains a constant. Daniel Jones takes over at quarterback, which could open things up for Barkley to see slightly less defensive attention. Then again, stacked boxes have not stopped him often to begin with. Fire him into fantasy lineups as a high-end RB1 against the Buccaneers in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Barkley suffered a high-ankle sprain in Week 3 and is expected to miss at least one month. Pick up Wayne Gallman, who's expected to be his top replacement during his absence. Stash Barkley in all leagues as he'll return to being an elite play almost immediately upon activation -- though that may not happen until after the Giants' Week 11 bye.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley was the second overall pick in the 2018 NFL draft and it's fair to say he'll be the first overall pick in most 2019 fantasy drafts. Barkley was a workhorse as a rookie, racking up 261 carries (second-most among running backs) and 119 targets (third-most), while pacing the position in routes (458), scrimmage yards (2,028) and fantasy points (386). Barkley finished worse than 13th at the position in fantasy points in only two weeks. He was on the field for 83 percent of the Giants' snaps, handled 75 percent of the designed runs and took on 21 percent of the targets. That workhorse usage isn't expected to change in what could be an even run-heavier offense in 2019. Barkley is the top asset in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brown has been with the Rams for four seasons and has seen an uptick in playing time over the past two campaigns. That said, he's still only handling a couple of touches-per-game as a reserve running back. Plus, Los Angeles added Darrell Henderson via the NFL Draft this spring. Brown is a true backup for the Rams and he's not an option for fantasy lineups in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: That sound you hear is fantasy managers everywhere scrambling to their waiver wires to pick up Brown. The fifth-year back out of Texas outsnapped rookie Darrell Henderson 21-2 and handled five red-zone carries. Todd Gurley II is still the lead back in Los Angeles, but Brown made an impossible to ignore case to be the No. 2. It's a role made even more appealing while watching Gurley appear to be limited due to conitnued injury concerns. Add him if you can and see how he performs in Week 2 against a good Saints defense. Consider using him in future weeks if his role remains consistent.
outlooksByWeek.3: Brown is an elite handcuff, but his fantasy value when Todd Gurley II is healthy just isn't enough to merit a weekly start. His Week 1 performance -- scoring a pair of touchdowns on 11 carries -- was an outlier and shouldn't be the expectation for a back likely to play on only 20-to-30 snaps per week. Keep him on the bench for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Brown is secure in his role as the No. 2 back in Los Angeles, clearly surpassing trendy "preseason player to watch" Darrell Henderson as Todd Gurley's handcuff and backup. While his Week 1 touchdowns were nice, it's clear that Brown is strictly the reserve here. This is not a timeshare. With that in mind, keep him rostered if you have Gurley, but don't start him in Week 4 against a tough Buccaneers run defense.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Latavius Murray moving on, the Vikings added Mattison in the NFL Draft to provide backup to Dalvin Cook. Being next in line behind the oft-injured Cook isn't a bad place to be from a fantasy perspective, but heading into Week 1 it appears the starter is healthy and ready to go. Keep Mattison as a handcuff on your bench rather than in your starting lineup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Mattison is the obvious No. 2 to Dalvin Cook in Minnesota, but on Sunday we learned that said role doesn't offer a ton of upside. Cook handled over two-thirds of the total snaps and 21 of the team's 32 carries. Mattison got nine of the remaining 11, which is an encouraging sign for his handcuff status. However, he's not going to hold fantasy appeal in Week 2 against a tougher Packers defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: If you're looking for Dalvin Cook's handcuff, you're in the right place. Mattison has had 13 carries -- 10 more than Ameer Abdullah -- and has done very well when given the chance to carry the ball for Minnesota. He doesn't hold much stand-alone value at this time, so you shouldn't consider him for your Week 3 lineups. Still, pick him up whether or not you roster Cook, just in case something happens to the FSU product.
outlooksByWeek.4: There may be no more valuable handcuff in fantasy, but that's all Mattison is at this point. He's seeing only around a dozen snaps-per-game and should be kept on the bench as insurance for superstar Dalvin Cook.

player.seasonOutlook: Looking to fill a need after the offseason departure of Latavius Murray, Minnesota selected Mattison with the No. 102 pick in April's draft. Mattison is a big, between-the-tackles back at 5-foot-11, 221 pounds, but also has good receiving and blocking chops. Mattison, who handled a whopping 302 carries at Boise State last season, lacks speed (4.67 YPC) and quickness, but has the size and skill set to settle in as a reliable backup. That's the role he'll play in 2019 as Dalvin Cook's handcuff.

outlooksByWeek.1: McCaffrey was a fantasy monster in 2018, falling 35 scrimmage yards short of 2,000 and piling up 13 touchdowns. There shouldn't be a matchup that scares his fantasy managers. Against the Rams in Week 1, he should be busy once again, even if Cam Newton (foot) plays hobbled. Keep McCaffrey near the top of the RB rankings for the opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: McCaffrey was too tough to bring down in Week 1, compiling 209 scrimmage yards with two scores. One of the top picks in most fantasy drafts this year, McCaffrey should continue his busy schedule in Week 2 against the Buccaneers, against whom he averaged 159 scrimmage yards across two meetings last year. He's still a surefire fantasy RB1.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Buccaneers surprisingly tamed McCaffrey in Week 2, and if Panthers QB Cam Newton (foot) has to miss Week 3, that'll certainly be the case again. Fortunately, the Cardinals' light defensive front may be easy for him to run against anyway. McCaffrey won't be a star this week without Newton, but his workload should keep his value close to that of a fantasy RB1 regardless of who is under center.
outlooksByWeek.4: McCaffrey again dominated backfield work for Carolina, tearing through Arizona's small defensive front and letting Kyle Allen play an effective game under center in Week 3. Cam Newton's (foot) absence seemed to allow the offense to breathe a bit and, though Allen will start again in Week 4 against the Texans, fantasy players should continue riding McCaffrey as a top-end RB1.

player.seasonOutlook: If not for being rested during a meaningless Week 17 game, McCaffrey would've led all backs in fantasy points last season. The Stanford product took his game to a new level in 2018, playing an almost unheard of 97 percent of Carolina's snaps through Week 16. He finished 10th among backs in rushing attempts (219) and was first in targets (124), receptions (107) and receiving yards (867). McCaffrey had at least five receiving touchdowns for the second year in a row. He improved his yards per carry from 3.7 to 5.0 and his catch rate from 73 percent to 86 percent. The 23-year-old does it all and is well worth the early-first-round fantasy investment.

outlooksByWeek.1: Can JuJu set the target record this season? These are fun type of questions that become reasonable after posting over 1,400 yards at age 22. The Patriots allowed 18 touchdowns to receivers last season, above league average, setting up Smith-Schuster as a surefire WR1 for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Context can matter when considering small samples. For instance, Smith-Schuster's debut as the team's top receiver was seemingly modest, but he was shadowed the entire game by one of the league's top cover talents and still netted six catches, passing Mike Wallace for most receptions by a Steeler within his first three career seasons. The Seahawks were gashed regularly by multiple Bengals receivers in Week 1, setting up Smith-Schuster -- who appears good to go after suffering a toe injury -- for a strong second showing.
outlooksByWeek.3: Lost in the shuffle of losing Ben Roethlisberger to injury this past week was the fact Smith-Schuster passed Randy Moss as the youngest player (22 years, 297 days) in NFL history to reach 2,500 career receiving yards. There are legitimate questions about Mason Rudolph's ability to sustain WR1 value for Smith-Schuster going forward, but he's still projected to be in the elite mix this week at the position given a choice matchup with an exploitable crew of corners for the 49ers.
outlooksByWeek.4: A huge touchdown play salvaged his fantasy value in Week 3 and signaled his ninth career game with at least 75 yards and a score in his career. The Bengals have surrendered 14.9 yards per catch to receivers, setting up Smith-Schuster for a strong showing if he can get past their safeties in this one.

player.seasonOutlook: Smith-Schuster is the new main man in Pittsburgh after the Steelers shipped Antonio Brown to Oakland. Smith-Schuster should be able to handle it considering he's fresh off arguably the best second season for a second-year wide receiver in league history. Smith-Schuster paced all wide receivers in pass routes (662) and finished no lower than seventh in targets (167), receptions (111) and receiving yards (1,383). Smith-Schuster has scored seven touchdowns during each of his two NFL seasons, though his 8.3 OTD and 13 end zone targets in 2018 suggest he was a bit unlucky in that department. Smith-Schuster's targets might not rise significantly in 2019, but that's only because he was already a huge part of the offense. Incredibly still only 22, Smith-Schuster's best days still could be ahead of him. He's a solid WR1 with upside to lead the position in fantasy points.

outlooksByWeek.1: With the helmet drama in the past, Brown's next mission is dueling with top cover corner Chris Harris Jr. on Monday evening. As was the case in Pittsburgh, sometimes the sheer volume of targets sent Brown's way can fuel fantasy fun. With an expectation for a dominant market share of the Oakland offense, Brown can likely overcome the tough matchup.
outlooksByWeek.2: So that happened. Antonio Brown is on the Patriots and the rest of the NFL just has to deal with it, beginning with the lowly Dolphins. Likely ready to plug-and-play with Tom Brady right away against a secondary that is suspect past Xavien Howard, Brown is already back in the WR1 discussion after a tumultuous summer.
outlooksByWeek.3: Targeted on a whopping eight of his 14 routes in Week 2, it was clear early on that the team wanted to get Brown integrated into offense with heavy usage. Brown delivered a touchdown in his first game with Tom Brady and could thrive with more routes and targets against a Jets secondary that has proven suspect against receivers.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown missed Week 17 last season or else he might have finished as fantasy's No. 1 scoring wide receiver for the fifth consecutive season. Both a high-floor and high-ceiling asset, Brown has posted a minimum of 159 targets, 101 receptions, eight touchdowns and 11 end zone targets during each of the past six seasons. The last season in which he didn't finish as a top 5 fantasy wide receiver was 2012. Brown's touchdowns figure to take a dive this season after he found the end zone a career-high 15 times last season despite a 9.6 OTD. In the five previous seasons, Brown averaged 10.4 scores per season (9.0 OTD) and he figures to be in that range in 2019 once he finds a home. The 31-year-old receiver is now in New England and, while he figures to see a dip in targets, he'll get enough in a Patriots' high-scoring offense that another Top 10 fantasy campaign is possible. Consider him a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tom Brady could look Edelman's way early and often in Sunday's marquee matchup with the Steelers. Pittsburgh allowed the 13th-most yards to receivers last season and could struggle to contain Edelman underneath in space. As the top target in a Brady offense, Edelman is a high-end WR2 for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Edelman became the fifth Patriots player to ever compile 500 catches with the franchise thanks to another textbook six-catch showing. There is now clearly increased competition for targets now that Antonio Brown is in the fold, but the guess would be the pie is big enough to satiate the top targets in this offense, especially facing a suspect Miami defense that saw the Ravens play catch in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.3: We'll see Edelman's target share naturally dip in the weeks ahead now that Antonio Brown and Josh Gordon are members of the depth chart. This doesn't mean Edelman still isn't a high-floor flex option in PPR formats facing a soft Jets pass defense, because he is, but rather the ceiling is a bit lower now that there are so many talented peers to contend with.
outlooksByWeek.4: The seven catches Edelman netted in the first half of Week 3 are tied for the most of his career in a single half. Unfortunately, Edelman left the game in the second quarter with a rib injury, but tests after the game revealed no fractures. Assuming he's good to go for this division matchup, Edelman is a high-floor option in PPR formats facing a Bills team that has allowed the third-most receptions to receivers.

player.seasonOutlook: Edelman was suspended for the first four games of the 2018 season but still managed a 74/850/6 line during 12 regular-season games. Tom Brady's top target was limited to one top 10 fantasy week but finished only one of 12 outings worse than 30th, making him the second-safest bet for a top-30 week behind only Davante Adams. Edelman is averaging a massive 9.4 targets per game over the past five seasons and reached eight targets in nine of 12 games in 2018. Durability is the notable drawback as he has missed 45 of 160 possible regular-season games (28 percent) since joining the team in 2009. Edelman is now 33, but following Rob Gronkowski's retirement, he's ticketed for a gigantic offensive role. Consider him a strong WR2 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: A new left tackle and additional speed on the outside of the offense help Watson's case as the best fantasy play at the position for this first week of the 2019 season. Watson is the rare quarterback capable of rushing for 100 yards one week while throwing five touchdowns the next. In Week 1, Watson is in the Superdome to face a Saints defense that allowed the most yards to receivers last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: The hurry to get a competent line together for Watson late this offseason didn't result in better protection for the star signal-caller. He was sacked six times in New Orleans in Week 1. Then again, it didn't harm Watson's fantasy production, as the unique dual-threat talent produced four total scores with strong yardage results. The Jaguars come to town, fresh from surrendering 40 points to the Chiefs, with Watson poised as a top option once again in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Watson failed to throw a touchdown for just the third game in his career but did deliver his ninth career rushing score, breaking a tie with David Carr for the most rushing scores by a Houston quarterback. The offensive line continues to struggle—Watson has been sacked 10 times this season, including four in Week 2—which could be an issue against a dangerous Chargers pass rush. Then again, the point total for this game is approaching 50 and, with Watson as the centerpiece of the Houston offense, there's still an awesome ceiling in place.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Panthers are allowing just 13.5 fantasy points per game to opposing passers this season, eighth fewest in the league. Even with a tough matchup ahead, we're talking about Watson, who just became the first Texans quarterback since 2014 with at least 350 passing yards, three scores and zero interceptions in a game. On the fast field in Houston, Watson remains a must-start option under center.

player.seasonOutlook: Watson picked up where he left off during an injury-shortened rookie season with a terrific sophomore campaign. The Clemson product was fantasy's No. 4 QB and his 10 top-10 fantasy weeks ranked third. Despite dealing with overwhelming pressure due to a weak offensive line (league-high 62 sacks), Watson ranked top 12 in passing yards (4,165) and touchdowns (26). He added 551 yards and five scores on 99 carries, all of which ranked third at the position. Watson is only 23 years old, adds value with his arm and legs, and will have a better and healthier supporting cast in 2019. He's a strong QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: The leader among running backs in receiving yardage since he entered the league in 2015, Johnson will be busy in his debut with the Texans in a game bound that should prove rewarding for fantasy managers. The Saints were stingy against the run last season but exploitable against the pass. Johnson has solid flex value for this trip to New Orleans.
outlooksByWeek.2: Johnson's debut with the Texans was ultimately positive given he tallied 90 scrimmage yards on his 13 touches. Johnson will need to see more work in the passing phase to really erupt as a fantasy weapon, especially with Carlos Hyde likely to consume a heavy does of carries. The Jaguars have allowed just the seventh-fewest receiving yards to tailbacks since the start of last season. Given his talents as a receiver, Johnson enters Week 2 as a solid flex option.
outlooksByWeek.3: With a robust target rate of 20% per route run, Johnson brings some upside to the field in PPR formats against the Chargers this week. Aiding Johnson's cause as a flex option in PPR leagues is the fact the Chargers have allowed 1,030 receiving yards to tailbacks over the past 18 games, the most in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.4: Johnson, who had just four touches in Week 3, is not living up to the lofty expectations placed on him entering the season. Still the better fantasy option than Carlos Hyde, Johnson isn't a solid option in Week 4 against Carolina's speedy linebackers and strong defensive line.

player.seasonOutlook: Johnson has emerged as one of the league's best receiving backs since he was drafted in the third round of the 2015 draft. He ranks third at the position in targets (297), third in receptions (235), first in receiving yards (2170) and 11th in touchdown catches (eight) the past four seasons. Despite the success, Johnson had career lows in carries (40) and targets (62) last season. Fantasy's No. 11 scoring back in 2017 plummeted to a career-worst 37th in 2018. A bounceback figures to be in the cards in 2019 as Johnson was traded to Houston where he'll play a major role following Lamar Miller's torn ACL. Johnson figures to be limited a bit as a rusher, but will certainly be very busy as Houston's primary receiving back. He's in the RB2 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: The former Jaguar had a breakout season in 2015 which seemed to predict a career as a top-tier NFL receiver, but Robinson has struggled to stay healthy and consistent ever since. He saw a healthy share of targets last season and found the end zone four times, but fantasy managers can't help but expect a bit more out of the Penn State product. He'll face the Packers in Week 1, a team that held him in check last year, but on volume and role alone he's worthy of a spot as your WR3 or flex.
outlooksByWeek.2: Robinson was the star of the show for the Bears in Week 1, hauling in 7-of-13 targets for 102 yards in what was an otherwise disappointing day for the Chicago offense. That's healthy volume and efficiency in what was a poor day for his team, so there's reason for optimism in what should be an easier matchup with the Broncos in Week 2. Denver allowed Tyerll Williams to break out for 105 yards and a touchdown in Week 1. Consider Robinson as a solid WR2 for the week ahead.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Bears' offense has yet to kick into gear this season, with a pair of tough matchups out of the gate. That all changes in Week 3, as  Chicago heads to Washington, a team that offers less resistance to the pass game. DeSean Jackson hauled in a pair of touchdowns in Week 1 -- two of the six passing scores allowed by the Washington defense across two games. Robinson is the receiver with by far the most targets on the Chicago offense, so he stands to benefit from what should be a breakout game for the entire Bears offense. He's a borderline WR2 and definitely worthy of a spot in your flex.
outlooksByWeek.4: While quarterback Mitchell Trubisky had a breakout game in Week 3, Robinson couldn't say the same about his lackluster 60 yards. With all three of Chicago's TD passes going to Taylor Gabriel, the Penn State product was left with a disappointing fantasy point total. Still, he saw seven targets and is now up to 27 on the season through three games. Plus, he's absolutely the best receiver on the Bears. He'll face a tough test as Chicago hosts Minnesota in Week 4, however, so downgrade him to more of a flex pick.

player.seasonOutlook: It's fair to say Robinson's first season with Chicago was a bit of a disappointment. The former Jaguar missed three games because of injury and was held to one weekly finish fantasy better than 19th. Robinson was held to four touchdowns, though he did enjoy a healthy 23 percent target share. The latter supplies some promise as Robinson is still only 25 and enters 2019 with a full season under his belt after missing all but three snaps in 2017 because of a torn ACL. Robinson ranked seventh at the position in targets (297) and fourth in touchdowns (20) during the 2015-16 seasons. Robinson is a fringe top 25 fantasy receiver.

outlooksByWeek.1: The matchup isn't ideal for Njoku; the Titans have talented cover safeties, which helped them limit tight ends to seventh-fewest yards in 2018. That said, Njoku is still a primary target in a strong passing game. He's still in the TE1 tier.
outlooksByWeek.2: Third on the Browns in routes and targets in Week 1, Njoku did have two drops, which have been a career-long issue. Assuming he's still the third option in the passing game, Njoku is a fringe starting fantasy option facing a Jets defense that has allowed the second-fewest yards to tight ends since the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.3: A bad fall midway into Monday's game against the Jets saw Njoku leave the contest with a concussion. Njoku is now in the league's protocol. We'll learn more as the week progresses, but Njoku's managers will want to have another option handy. If he's available, Njoku is in a good spot against a Rams defense that has allowed the seventh-most yards to tight ends since the start of last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Njoku entered the NFL extremely young, at 20 years old, and is now entering the all-important third NFL season. The 2017 first-round pick's snaps and targets increased substantially last season, which helped him to a ninth-place finish in fantasy points (he was 10th during Freddie Kitchen's eight games as offensive coordinator). A dangerous threat down the seam, Njoku has ranked top 11 at the position in aDOT in each of his two pro seasons. Last season's 16 percent target share figures to decrease slightly with Beckham in the fold, but it's possible Njoku overcomes that with an extra touchdown or two (he has exactly four in each of his two seasons). The 23-year-old is a fringe TE1 with upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones is stuck between presumed starter Peyton Barber and preseason star Dare Ogunbowale for backfield work, and his struggles in pass protection won't do him any favors. He's best considered a desperation flex play against the 49ers in Week 1, and it looks like he'll be stuck in a committee for some time.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jones took the spotlight as Jameis Winston struggled in Week 1. Jones may lead Tampa Bay's backfield after his 93-yard day from scrimmage, but he'll still have to give up some work to both Peyton Barber and Dare Ogunbowale. The Panthers allowed 150 yards and two touchdowns to Rams backup Malcolm Brown, so Tampa Bay could have some room to generate a surprise fantasy day. Jones looks like a high-end fantasy flex for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jones logged just four touches in a sloppy Week 2 win as the Buccaneers rode Peyton Barber. They simply didn't need Jones' receiving services in this one. Against the Giants, Barber should be the lead back again, though New York has allowed three ground scores to running backs so far, which may leave Jones room to contribute in garbage time. He's an OK dice roll at the flex spot for Week 3 fantasy lineups.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jones took the backfield lead during a high-scoring Week 3 clash with the Giants and could be poised to outwork Peyton Barber again in Week 4, when the Buccaneers probably will need to keep a frantic pace to try and match the Rams. Jones is a solid flex play due to his big-play ability. He's averaged at least 5.7 YPC in two of his three games so far this year.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones was one of the youngest players selected in the 2018 draft, and maybe that's the excuse for what was an ugly rookie season. The second-round pick struggled right out of the gate and ended up managing only 88 snaps in nine games. He registered 44 yards on 23 carries (1.9 YPC, 1.3 YAC) and 33 yards on nine targets (3.7 YPT). Jones is undersized at 5-foot-11, 205 pounds, which might limit his early-down and goal-line opportunities, but the depth chart is wide open in Tampa Bay. He's a post-hype sleeper with tons of raw talent and upside as a receiver. Throw a dart in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Veteran savvy and locker room leadership don't show up in the box score, which certainly curbs Gore's appeal for this meeting with the solid front-seven of the Jets. At this stage, Gore is likely third in fantasy value among the Bills' trio of tailbacks.
outlooksByWeek.2: Sure, Gore led the Bills with 11 touches in a Week 1 win over the Jets, but he was held to just 1.82 yards per rush and ran just one route. Even as the Giants present an inviting matchup—New York allowed the fourth-most rushing scores (15) to tailbacks last season—Gore's uninspired role and lack of playmaking ability mean he's not a starting fantasy option.
outlooksByWeek.3: In a solid showing against the lowly Giants' defense, Gore became just the fifth running back at least 36-years old with a rushing score in the Super Bowl era. The Bengals, third worst in rushing defense, actually have been worse than the Giants in defefening opposing backfields over the past 18 games..
outlooksByWeek.4: In a vintage performance, Gore rumbled for 89 yards from scrimmage for the Bills in Week 3. The lanes might not be as wide this week facing a stingy New England front seven that has ceded just 2.24 yards per attempt to tailbacks, the lowest clip in the NFL. Gore is outside of the flex tier thanks to increased competition for touches from Devin Singletary against a tough defensive foe.

player.seasonOutlook: Gore joins the Bills as a complement to rookie Devin Singletary after a bizarre 2018 season in Miami, during which he averaged a healthy 4.6 YPC (2.3 YAC), but failed to rush for a single touchdown. Gore finished 46th at the position in fantasy points, which is the first time he has finished a season worse than 21st since 2006. He also missed a game for the first time since 2010. Now 36 years old, Gore won't see enough volume to allow consistent fantasy production. Even if Singletary were to miss time, Gore would share touches with TJ Yeldon. There's little fantasy appeal here.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fuller is one of the league's most prolific scoring threats on vertical targets, but he has had durability issues. Healthy heading into the new season, Fuller projects as a worthy big-play option against a New Orleans defense that yielded the most yards in the league to wideouts in 2018.
outlooksByWeek.2: A crowded and competitive depth chart at receiver left Fuller with just four targets in Week 1. These weren't just any targets, however, as Fuller's average target travelled 35.7 air yards, leading him to 69 yards on his two catches. We'd like to see more opportunities for this gifted deep threat, but he has almost sole claim of the Texans' valuable vertical work. In additon, the Chiefs beat the Jaguars deep several times this past week. Fuller is a high-ceiling, low-floor flex candidate.
outlooksByWeek.3: An awesome vertical threat averaging a team-high 23.8 air yards per target through two weeks, the counter to Fuller's big-play upside is that he has a catch on just 9% of his routes this year.
outlooksByWeek.4: Fuller leads the Texans in routes run but, with just 5.6 targets per game, he's only had a reception on 10.8% of his routes (team average is 12.8). This puts pressure on him to hit on big plays when he does connect with Deshaun Watson. It makes sense, then, that Fuller has a team-best 18 air yards per target. The Panthers were susceptible to the big play last season, and Fuller is the quintessential boom-or-bust deep threat.

player.seasonOutlook: Fuller has certainly flashed the upside that made him a first-round draft pick back in 2016, but he has yet to finish a season as a top-60 fantasy wide receiver. Durability has been the obvious issue, as Fuller has missed at least two games during each of his three seasons, including six in 2017 and nine in 2018. Last season, Fuller handled career-high 21 percent target share and sat 14th at the position in fantasy points prior to suffering a season-ending injury in Week 8. The downfield playmaker has scored 11 touchdowns in 17 games during the past two seasons. Fuller is still only 25 years old and has big upside if he can stay on the field, but with DeAndre Hopkins, Keke Coutee and now Kenny Stills in the mix, he may not be worth the cost for fantasy drafters. Consider him a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: It wasn't that long ago that the "start or sit" decision for the Seahawks D/ST was as simple as it gets. However, this unit is no longer a must-start, as the "Legion of Boom" is no more and the team just doesn't quite make as many splash plays as they once did. Offseason departures of players like Earl Thomas and Frank Clark make the unit a bit more uneappealing, but a matchup with the Bengals shouldn't scare anyone away. Consider this unit a mid-range starting D/ST for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: The Seattle defense made its fair share of big plays in Week 1, recovering fumbles and sacking the quarterback to post a decent fantasy score. However, they aren't the same defense they once were and will face a tough test against the Steelers in Week 2. You can probably find a better option on waivers.
outlooksByWeek.3: With Drew Brees under center, the outlook for the Seattle defense would have noted that Brees is efficient and careful with the ball, leaving little in terms of big play potential. However, with the Saints veteran quarterback now sidelined, the Seahawks D/ST currently offers a lot more Week 3 upside than it would have seemed just seven days ago. While they're not up to "Legion of Boom" standards, the Seahawks have made a few big plays on defense this season and merit consideration as a middle-of-the-pack starting D/ST.
outlooksByWeek.4: After Week 1, it looked like the Seahawks might be an interesting pick as a D/ST. However, they've registered only one sack in the two weeks since that five-sack outburst against the Bengals, and have forced only a pair of turnovers in that time. They don't offer the big-play appeal needed to be a trustworthy defense. They also face a Cardinals offense that can put up points, even if it's in a slightly inefficient manner. Seattle's D/ST is one to consider, but you can probably find a better option.

player.seasonOutlook: The Seattle D/ST finished 14th in fantasy points last season, which marks its first finish worse than ninth since 2010. Seattle ranked 18th in interceptions (12), 24th in tackles for loss (82) and 25th in yards per play (5.92). The unit was 10th in forced turnovers (26) and 11th in points allowed (347), though a league-high 14 fumble recoveries will be hard to repeat. Earl Thomas, Frank Clark and Justin Coleman were big offseason losses, though Jadeveon Clowney and Ziggy Ansah will help offset those moves. This is a defense with good coaching but very shaky personnel in some areas, especially cornerback. Add and start the Seattle D/ST only when the unit is at home and the matchup is good. That will be the case in Week 1 against the Bengals.

outlooksByWeek.1: We won't truly know how this committee approach with Drake and Kalen Ballage will play out until kickoff on Sunday against Baltimore's stingy rush defense. Drake is likely to consume the majority of passing usage out of the backfield, an element that could prove rewarding for a team that could trail early and often as sizable home underdogs.
outlooksByWeek.2: Game script removed the rushing phase from the menu for Miami in Week 1, but it would have been nice to see Drake prove more effective and busy as a receiving threat in a blowout loss. The Patriots stymied the Steelers' backfield in Week 1, thus Drake makes for a somewhat risky flex option given Miami's position as a heavy home dog.
outlooksByWeek.3: We've yet to see Drake's big-play prowess emerge this season and this is due in part to the fact he's getting just 8.5 touches per game for the league's worst offense. Drake has shown some promise as a receiver this season, but he doesn't earn enough total touches to help offset a tough matchup with Dallas' speedy linebackers.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Dolphins tried to stick with the running game in Week 3, giving Drake 12 carries -- more than in the first two weeks combined. Sadly, he struggled to find space, gaining only 38 yards, though he did chip in with 34 more through the air. He's the lead back who plays on almost double the snaps of the next runner on the Miami depth chart, Kalen Ballage, but that doesn't guarantee fantasy appeal. After allowing a Week 1 breakout performance to Marlon Mack, the Chargers have kept running backs under wraps since. This isn't a favorable spot for Drake, who is a flex option at best.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite playing second fiddle to Frank Gore in the rushing department, Drake posted career-high marks in touches (173), scrimmage yards (1012) and touchdowns (nine) last season. Only 13 backs scored more fantasy points. Most of Drake's damage was done as a receiver, as he ranked 13th at the position in targets (71), 14th in receiving yards (425) and ninth in aDOT (2.1). He registered only one carry inside the opponent's 5-yard line and posted a 3.9 OTD (which wasn't far off his 3.5 OTD when he scored four touchdowns in 2017). That suggests a dip in touchdowns is coming, though his role figures to expand with Gore no longer on the roster. Drake is a serviceable RB3/flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dissly made a big impression last season with a breakout performance in Weeks 1 and 2, racking up 10 catches and 147 yards plus two touchdowns. However, a knee injury would sideline him just two weeks later and erase the rest of his season. He seems to be cleared to play and ready for Week 1 but, with so much uncertainty, he's best left on benches for now.
outlooksByWeek.2: Dissly entered Week 1 as the clear starter at the TE position, but suffered an injury during Sunday's game. Before he left the contest, he did haul in a pass, but his upside in fantasy isn't that great to begin with. Even if he is good to go for Week 2, you can look elsewhere at this position.
outlooksByWeek.3: Dissly left Week 1's matchup with the Bengals with a knee injury, which was certainly a disappointment for those who took a chance on him in fantasy lineups. He returned in Week 2 and showed no ill effects, scoring a pair of touchdowns that likely failed to impact most fantasy matchups. He did see five targets against the Steelers -- a healthy amount for a tight end, outside of elite options like Travis Kelce -- so he's a name to keep on the radar. He just doesn't have a secure role that we can trust as a TE1. Consider him as a streaming option and a bench player for now.
outlooksByWeek.4: While his touchdown may have come at the end of a game on a meaningless play, it still counts for fantasy. Dissly now has three scores in three games and appears to be a trusted target near the end zone for Russell Wilson. He also received a healthy seven targets in Week 4 and now faces a premium matchup with Arizona. The Cardinals have allowed huge performances out of TEs T.J. Hockenson, Mark Andrews and Greg Olsen so far this season. Dissly has good odds to make it four in a row.

player.seasonOutlook: Dissly took the fantasy landscape by storm last season, as the relatively unheralded rookie tight end exploded for a 6-147-2 line and the third-most fantasy points at the position through Week 2. Dissly predictably came back to earth a bit in Week 3 before suffering a season-ending knee injury in Week 4. The 2018 fourth-round pick was targeted 13 times through three weeks (third most on the team), though he ran a route on only 53 percent of the team's pass plays. Dissly figures to take on a larger role in his second season, which makes him a fine late flier, but Seattle's run-heavy offense will limit his upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: There is some risk with Michel as an RB2 option this week given how isolated he was to rushing duties last season, placing the onus on the Georgia product to net touchdowns to return value. This said, the Patriots have produced the most goal-to-go opportunities for their running backs over the past three seasons, with Michel in a good spot as the team's lead early-down force heading into Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: It appears averaging less than a yard per carry is a bad thing, as Michel's fantasy managers found out this past Sunday. We know Michel won't factor as a receiver very often, so he's going to need to prove dangerous as a rusher, particularly in the red zone, to deliver value. This said, the Dolphins allowed Mark Ingram to run for 49 yards on his first touch with the Ravens compiling over 200 yards on the ground in the process. If there were ever an ideal game script for Michel's skill set, this could be it.
outlooksByWeek.3: In this week's edition of causation versus correlation, we find the Patriots are now undefeated (including playoffs) in the nine games he's scored a rushing touchdown in his career. We've yet to see Michel break out as a rusher this year, but it was nice to see him accrue 18 touches in Miami. A matchup with the Jets could see Michel enjoy additional rushing work given the potential for game script to prove run heavy into the second half.
outlooksByWeek.4: Third on the backfield in snaps in Week 3 and struggling to find lanes at just 2.4 yards per carry this year, Michel's fantasy stock is on the descent. The Bills have surrendered the 11th-fewest rushing yards to tailbacks this season and Michel has essentially no role in the receiving phase, thus he's a risky flex option on the road this Sunday.

player.seasonOutlook: Michel appeared in 13 regular-season games as a rookie and handled a generous 16.1 carries per game. That helped the 2018 first-round pick to a top-15 finish in both carries (209) and rushing yards (931). Michel also racked up 12 carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line (seventh-most), which helped him accrue six rushing touchdowns. New England called run on an enormous 76 percent of Michel's snaps, which meant he was limited to 11 targets. That crushed his fantasy production, as he managed only five top-20 (two top-10) fantasy weeks. It's possible the 24-year-old plays a more versatile role in 2019, but his target share figures to increase only slightly with James White, Rex Burkhead and rookie Damien Harris in the mix. Michel is a back-end RB2 who should be upgraded in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Thompson will continue to occupy his role as Washington's top pass-catching back but must now deal with Derrius Guice along with Adrian Peterson. His upside is capped a bit more strongly, but PPR fantasy players will still roster him with some comfort as a low-end bench piece. He could fly as an Ezekiel Elliott or Melvin Gordon replacement for Week 1, and more strongly so in leagues that reward receptions. Washington may need his services frequently against the talented Eagles, after all.
outlooksByWeek.2: Thompson touched the rock 10 times in Week 1 to total 78 scrimmage yards during a disappointing loss to Philadelphia. Expect him to be busy again versus Dallas, especially now that Derrius Guice (knee) will miss at least one week. Adrian Peterson will be activated, but Thompson coexisted with the veteran on many occasions last year -- and Thompson remains the better bet in passing-down work. He's a decent flex in most fantasy formats against the Cowboys, who should force Washington to pass often.
outlooksByWeek.3: As expected, Thompson did most of his damage versus Dallas through the air in Week 2. With Derrius Guice (knee) out through at least Washington's Week 10 bye, Thompson will continue splitting work in the backfield with Adrian Peterson. Against the sturdy Bears defense in Week 3, Thompson will probably see plenty of work on screen passes, which cements his flex value -- more strongly so in PPR games.
outlooksByWeek.4: Thompson was used heavily in Week 3 versus the Bears, as he's deployed frequently when the team is trailing and needs to pass. Thompson has had four-plus catches and at least 48 receiving yards in each of his first three games. He will continue sharing snaps with both Adrian Peterson and Wendell Smallwood, who are set to handle most of the between-the-tackles work. Against the Giants, he's worthy of flex trust in fantasy lineups for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Thompson has emerged as one of the league's better receiving backs in recent years, but injuries have derailed his chances for a full-on breakout. The 28-year-old back has missed exactly six games each of the past two seasons. Thompson's best season came in 2017, when he put up 804 scrimmage yards and six touchdowns on 103 touches in 10 games. Thompson has never cleared 68 carries in a season (though he has benefited from light boxes), but he's averaging an impressive 4.96 YPC in his career. Interestingly, he paced the position in YPR (13.1) and YPT (9.8) in 2017 but finished sixth-worst (6.4) and fifth-worst (4.9), respectively, last season. Thompson will continue to be limited to passing situations behind Adrian Peterson and Derrius Guice, which severely limits his fantasy upside. He's worth a look in deep PPR leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even with increased competition for targets with several capable peers in the passing game, Hopkins remains Houston's most prolific playmaker and should feast in a prime-time matchup with a Saints team that surrendered the most yards to receivers last season. It helps Hopkins' case that this contest claims the highest point total of the opening slate.
outlooksByWeek.2: Hopkins delivered his ninth career multi-score showing in Week 1, leaving him one shy of tying Andre Johnson for most in Texans history. Just as impressively, Hopkins tallied a team-high 13 targets and should again dominate that market against Jacksonville's Jalen Ramsey in Week 2. Even with that tough matchup, you can start Hopkins with confidence.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jalen Ramsey was effective in shadowing Hopkins in Week 2, limiting him to just 40 receiving yards, a mark he dipped below just once all of last season. With a potential shootout on deck with the Chargers in Los Angeles, a defense that was just gashed by T.Y. Hilton and Kenny Golladay in consecutive weeks, Hopkins is due for a bounce-back performance for the Texans in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: With nearly a third of the Texans' total targets through three games and the same share of yardage production, Hopkins once again claims a uniquely high weekly floor. The Panthers are ranked 15th in fantasy points allowed to receivers. Hopkins is a top option at his position for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Hopkins has been the No. 2 scoring fantasy wide receiver during each of the past two seasons and has finished in the top 4 three of the past four seasons. Hopkins has been a workhorse, ranking no lower than sixth in targets, receptions, yardage, touchdowns and end zone targets during each of the past two seasons. He has topped the position in OTD both seasons. Finally attached to a quality quarterback for a full season, Hopkins caught a career-high 70 percent of his targets in 2018. Hopkins has managed a massive 35 percent target share over the past two seasons. That could drop some with Kenny Stills, Will Fuller V and Keke Coutee in the mix, but Hopkins will still rank at or near the top of the position in the category. The sure-handed 27-year-old remains an elite fantasy asset.

outlooksByWeek.1: One knock against Mixon's prospects is the potential for the Bengals to trail big as sizable road dogs in this game—potentially affording Gio Bernard additional exposure as a receiver. Working in Mixon's favor? Seattle allowed almost three yards before contact per rush, among the most generous in the league. Unless Seattle has solved its rush defense issues, Mixon is set up for a strong opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: The collective sigh you heard on Monday? It came from Mixon's fantasy managers after an MRI confirmed the ankle injury that knocked him out of Week 1 isn't considered serious. If he's available for Week 2 against the 49ers, Mixon is in a strong spot to produce given San Francisco just yielded a strong day from scrimmage to the Bucs' Ronald Jones.
outlooksByWeek.3: Mixon's managers are vexed. He's averaging 11 touches and 22 scrimmage yards after two good matchups. The hope is Mixon can handle a heavy workload another week removed from a tweaking his knee in the opener. He'll need volume to deliver strong RB2 results against Buffalo's solid front seven.
outlooksByWeek.4: After a slow start to the season, Mixon tallied an impressive 95 yards from scrimmage for the Bengals in Week 3. Next up is a Steelers defense allowing 128.3 rushing yards per game to tailbacks, third most in the league, setting up Mixon for another solid day from scrimmage in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Mixon appeared in 14 games last season and handled a generous 16.9 carries and 3.9 targets per game. His rushing efficiency took a giant step forward from that of his rookie season, as the 2017 second-round pick boosted his yards per carry from 3.5 to 4.9 and his YAC from 1.7 to 1.9. Mixon quietly ended up fourth at the position in rushing yards (1,168), sixth in both touches (280) and scrimmage yards (1,464), and 10th in fantasy points (243). The Bengals' offensive line remains a problem area, but 22-year-old Mixon is a workhorse back positioned well for another step forward in his third season. Consider him a fringe RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones is one of the most interesting running backs in the league, as he posts incredible numbers on a per-carry basis, but doesn't seem to get a big boost in volume as a result. Still, he managed to score nine times one year ago and is healthy and ready to go as the Packers' starter in 2019. However, he faces a very tough test against a Bears team that allowed the fewest fantasy points-per-game last season, so he's more of an RB2/RB3 than a borderline RB1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jones is definitely the lead back for the Packers, but in Week 1 it hardly mattered given how poor the Packers offense performed against the stalwart Bears defense. It's hard to expect much more in Week 2 against the Vikings, a team that ranked among the 10 toughest matchups for running backs a season ago. Minnesota also held Devonta Freeman to only 31 total yards in Week 1. As such, Jones is at the fringe of the RB2 discussion and is probably more safely considered a flex pick.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jones is on the heavy end of a timeshare with Jamaal Williams, but it's fairly close in terms of snaps played. When it comes to carries, however, Jones has a massive lead, and that's led to him outgaining Williams on the ground by almost 130 yards over two weeks. Since the Broncos are very tough against the pass, Green Bay may look to establish the run in Week 3. That worked fairly well for the Raiders in Week 1, as Josh Jacobs picked up 85 yards and two scores, and again in Week 2 when David Mongtomgery scored and racked up 62 yards. Jones should see a healthy number of carries and can be expected to do fairly well despite going up against a talented defense. Lock him in as a high-end RB2.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Packers backfield is a curious one from a fantasy perspective, as Jones played on fewer snaps than Jamaal Williams in Week 3 after out-snapping him in both Weeks 1 and 2. Yet, he still found the end zone twice and saw 10 carries in his limited playing time -- albeit with a low 1.9 YPC. Still, this backfield is an even split and Jones offers upside as a regular player in a backfield with one of the league's best quarterbacks. All that said, Week 4 brings a very tough test against an Eagles defense which has allowed the fifth-fewest RB fantasy points per game. Downgrade Jones to a borderline RB2 and more of a RB3/flex play.

player.seasonOutlook: For the second consecutive season, Jones was one of the league's more efficient running backs in 2018, but a limited role and missed games precluded the 2017 fifth-round pick from consistent fantasy production. Jones has missed four games in each of the past two seasons but has averaged a healthy 5.5 YPC during both campaigns.
