Despite playing only 51 percent of the snaps, Jones posted a trio of top-10 fantasy weeks and ranked 13th at the position in fantasy points during the 11 weeks in which he wasn't out or injured last season. With a new coaching staff in place, Jones is the favorite to lead a committee with Jamaal Williams this season. Jones will be positioned for around 200 carries and a modest receiving role, which should allow for solid RB2 numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Following up an historic season is never easy, but if anyone is up to the challenge, it's Mahomes. The Chiefs take their offensive circus to a Jacksonville to face a strong defense due for some positive regression this season. Even with a formidable opponent in place, Mahomes remains a surefire QB1 given the Madden-like numbers that surfaced last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Already up to five career games with at least 350 passing yards and three scores (the most in the league since 2018), Mahomes continues to destroy defenses into his second year as a starter. Since the start of last season, the Raiders have allowed the most points per drive and the most yards per play to opponents, with Mahomes once again poised with the top projection of the slate.
outlooksByWeek.3: With four passing scores in the second quarter against Oakland, Mahomes set the franchise record for touchdowns in a quarter. The Ravens have been solid on defense but did allow Kyler Murray to enjoy a strong passing performance in Week 3, while Mahomes is clearly already matchup-proof and the rare must-start signal-caller for fantasy purposes.
outlooksByWeek.4: Through 20 career games, Mahomes has the most passing scores, yards, 300-yard games, and the highest completion percentage in league history and just became the first player in the last 40 seasons with 250 passing yards and two passing scores in the first half of three straight games. The Lions have produced a strong pressure on opposing passers this season, but Mahomes is probably matchup-proof at this point.

player.seasonOutlook: If you took a shot on Mahomes late in your 2018 fantasy draft, congratulations, you probably won your league. Mahomes exploded onto the fantasy scene with 12 top-10 fantasy weeks en route to finishing as the top-scoring QB by 62 points over second-place Matt Ryan. Mahomes paced the league in passing touchdowns (50) and was second in passing yards (5,097), while adding 272 yards and two scores rushing. Entering his third season, Mahomes looks like the next great NFL quarterback -- and should be the top QB off the board in all drafts -- but history suggests we should expect a substantial statistical dip. Daunte Culpepper was the last to repeat as the No. 1 fantasy quarterback, and that was way back in 2003-04.

outlooksByWeek.1: Godwin was arguably one of the most-hyped fantasy sleepers this draft season. If Mike Evans (quadriceps) is limited or inactive for Week 1 against the 49ers, his ceiling will skyrocket. The favorable matchup already puts him as a solid WR2 for the opener. He could be a big gainer in Bruce Arians' offense if Jameis Winston can master it quickly.
outlooksByWeek.2: Godwin found the end zone on a 3-catch, 53-yard day in Week 1. Jameis Winston has struggled with the offense, and Mike Evans (illness) wasn't himself, so maybe when the Tampa Bay offense looks more dangerous, he'll take a step back. Godwin nevertheless remains a breakout candidate for 2019. Against the Panthers in Week 2, count him as a high-end fantasy WR3.
outlooksByWeek.3: Godwin seems to be the big winner in the Buccaneers' new offense, scoring twice and averaging 7.5 targets and 87 receiving yards over the first two games. Against the Giants' wobbly defense, which has allowed a league-high 550 WR receiving yards, he should once again take the spotlight. Rank him as a strong WR2 for fantasy purposes in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Godwin commanded just four targets in Week 3 as Jameis Winston and Mike Evans connected for three scores. Godwin hadn't seen fewer than six targets in the two previous games and could be leaned upon a bit more against the Rams, who've allowed the sixth-fewest fantasy WR points-per-game. Godwin is a strong fantasy WR3, with a WR2 ceiling during what could be a comeback effort in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Godwin was limited to 57 percent of the Buccaneers' pass plays last season but still managed a 59/842/7 line and 27th-place finish in fantasy points. The 2017 third-round pick ranked 52nd at the position in routes, but was 25th in receiving yards and 13th in touchdowns thanks to a solid 9.0 YPT and 14 end zone targets (sixth most). Godwin has three drops on 150 career targets and has ranked top 5 in first down rate each of his two NFL seasons. New coach Bruce Arians, whose wide receivers ranked fifth in fantasy points during his five seasons as Arizona's head coach, says he believes Godwin could push for 100 catches in 2019. That might be a stretch, but Godwin is well positioned for a run at a top 20 fantasy season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mack flirted with three-down usage at times in the preseason, but Nyheim Hines still looms as the backfield's top receiving threat, casting doubt over Mack's ascension as an every-down force. Using last season's as precedent, expect Mack to lead the team in rushes, including around the goal line. The Chargers allowed the 11th-fewest yards to tailbacks last season, keeping Mack in the RB2 tier.
outlooksByWeek.2: Mack rumbled for 119 yards in the third quarter, the most by a Colts player in a single quarter since the franchise moved to Indianapolis in 1984. The Colts' Week 2 opponent, the Titans, held down Nick Chubb in Week 1, but Cleveland's back still had a respectable fantasy showing. With a heavy early-down workload, Mack is a strong RB2 candidate for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Leading the league in carries, Mack is one of two backs averaging at least 20 rushes through two games. His 45 total rushes this season are the most by an Indianapolis running back since Edgerrin James registered 50 in his team's first two games in 2005. The Falcons have allowed a generous 107 yards rushing per game this season, and Mack is poised for another strong day on the ground.
outlooksByWeek.4: One of the rare feature backs left in the league, Mack is averaging a robust 21.7 touches per game and has consumed a strong share of the Colts' receiving workload that evaded his profile last season. The Raiders present a great matchup for Mack. They've ceded the seventh-most rushing yards to tailbacks on the season.

player.seasonOutlook: If you blinked, you may have missed it, but Mack scored 10 touchdowns in 12 games during the 2018 season. The 2017 fourth-round pick seemingly struggled as a rookie, averaging 3.85 YPC, but his 2.25 YAC suggested a second-year leap. That was indeed the case, as Mack's YPC jumped to 4.66 and allowed him 908 yards on 195 carries. Mack appears to be an effective NFL rusher, but he has yet to make much of an impact as a receiver. He was held to 26 targets and posted an ugly 65 percent catch rate (second-worst among backs) last season. Andrew Luck's retirement and limited receiving work caps his fantasy ceiling, but Mack will get enough volume to allow fringe RB2 numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Howard's elite blocking ability and big-play upside will keep him on the field as often as possible. He looks like one of the position's biggest breakout candidates for 2019, considering he scored five times in 10 games while averaging 11.8 yards-per-target and 16.6 yards-per-catch before his 2018 season ended abruptly due to ankle and foot injuries. He's a steady TE1 for Week 1 against the 49ers.
outlooksByWeek.2: Howard managed just 32 receiving yards in the Buccaneers' opener, though he's going to be on the field as often as possible thanks to his well-rounded profile. Still, Jameis Winston's early struggles make him a risky play. On the bright side, he probably still belongs in TE1 fantasy territory for Week 2 against the Panthers, who allowed a touchdown to the Rams' Tyler Higbee in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Howard played on 60 snaps in Week 2 but didn't record a catch, showing the rough grasp Jameis Winston has had on this new offense -- or possibly showing how the new scheme may limit him. Still, Howard's electric talent as a receiver will keep him on the fantasy landscape. Against a Giants defense that has allowed two TE touchdowns thus far, Howard will once again force us to start him in most setups. Yep, roll him out again as a fantasy TE1 and hope for the best.
outlooksByWeek.4: Howard has played on at least 75.3% of snaps in each of the first three games but enjoyed a season-best 66 yards in Week 3. His talent for blocking and receiving has him on the field as often as possible, though the Rams, Tampa Bay's Week 4 opponents, have allowed just 7.1 TE fantasy points-per-game, ranking them among the 10 toughest matchups. Still, Howard's big workload keeps him on the border of fantasy TE1 territory, with elite upside.

player.seasonOutlook: Howard finished 2018 as the No. 14 scoring tight end, which is impressive when you consider he missed six games due to injury. Howard, who ranked sixth prior to the injury, accomplished the feat with low volume (4.7 targets per game) and elite efficiency (Howard has led the position in both YPT and YPR in both of his two NFL seasons). Howard has also scored touchdowns at an unsustainable rate (11 career TDs, 5.9 career OTD). The 24-year-old is clearly a rising star, but durability (eight missed games) and the presence of new coach Bruce Arians (his tight ends ranked 31st in fantasy points during five seasons in Arizona) are red flags. But Howard has played too well to be discounted. He has elite upside but will cost you a sixth round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Murray inherits the Mark Ingram role in the New Orleans offense, that of complementing Alvin Kamara with red-zone potential and bruiser work. Still, he's not as great a receiver as Ingram, so he may not be trusted in as many situations. On the other hand, that keeps Murray in the fantasy flex tier most weeks, as the Saints have become a run-first club and have room to make two backs fantasy-relevant. Feel free to flex him in the opener versus Houston.
outlooksByWeek.2: Murray snuck into the end zone in the first half in Week 1 but touched the ball just six times, showing he's still the No. 2 back behind Alvin Kamara. Still, inheriting Mark Ingram's role will result in many productive fantasy performances. Leave him in flex consideration for a Week 2 matchup with the Rams that should put plenty of points on the scoreboard.
outlooksByWeek.3: Drew Brees' Week 2 exit due to a thumb injury threw off the entire Saints offense, and Murray fell flat against stacked boxes and minimal work during a comeback attempt. With Teddy Bridgewater and Taysom Hill likely splitting work under center as Brees misses 6-to-8 weeks, the New Orleans offense could stall significantly. Murray's role may be in further jeopardy of losing carries if the Saints are playing from behind more often. He's still a "cross your fingers that he scores a TD" flex play against the Seahawks, but Seattle is a tough environment for any visitor -- let alone one with shaky QB play.
outlooksByWeek.4: Murray was in on just 20.7% of the Saints' Week 3 snaps, even with Teddy Bridgewater taking over under center for Drew Brees (thumb). The bruising back wasn't needed much as Alvin Kamara was heavily used. That may again be the case against the Cowboys, but mainly because this may be a time when the Saints play from behind. Still, the Cowboys rank middle of the pack with 23.2 RB fantasy points-per-game allowed, making Murray a capable flex choice for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray signed on with the Saints to replace Mark Ingram as a complement to lead back Alvin Kamara. Murray has been the poster boy for mediocrity, having finished each of the past four seasons with a yards per carry mark no higher than 4.13 and no lower than 3.90. Murray has been between 103 and 264 receiving yards each of the past three seasons. The area where Murray has stood out is the touchdown department. Since 2015, he ranks second in the NFL in rushing touchdowns (32), fourth in rushing OTD (27.7) and fifth in carries inside the 5-yard line (40). Murray is a sneaky flex in touchdown-only leagues, but his real appeal is as arguably the most valuable handcuff in fantasy. If Kamara goes down, Murray will be in the RB1 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Samuel earned rave reviews for his camp work and, while his target load may be erratic thanks to Christian McCaffrey, D.J. Moore and Greg Olsen all requiring attention, Samuel's playmaking ability after the catch could be a major asset to QB Cam Newton. Against the Rams, Samuel is a worthwhile fantasy flex choice, considering the Panthers will probably need to keep pace with this big-play offense. If reports say Newton's foot injury is an issue heading into the game -- or it keeps him out entirely -- dock Samuel appropriately.
outlooksByWeek.2: Samuel was targeted four times but came away with just 32 yards in Week 1. With Greg Olsen's back injury and a short turn-around before Week 2's Thursday game versus Tampa Bay, Samuel could gain more offensive attention. He's a solid flex play in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Samuel was targeted a whopping 13 times in Week 2 but caught just five of those passes. QB Cam Newton (foot) may miss Week 3, but Carolina probably will continue to find ways to give the playmaking wideout touches, perhaps even in the form of more handoffs. Regardless of Newton's status, consider Samuel as a solid fantasy flex against a Cardinals defense that'll be without CB Patrick Peterson (suspension).
outlooksByWeek.4: Samuel didn't miss a beat, despite Kyle Allen's debut in replacing Cam Newton (foot) for Week 3. Samuel scored his first touchdown of the season in the contest. The Texans have allowed the fifth-highest fantasy WR points-per-game to wideouts, which keeps Samuel firmly in the fantasy flex tier -- with the upside of a strong WR3 for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Samuel has missed 10 games and registered a grand total of 54 receptions since being selected in the second round of the 2017 draft. The versatile receiver has struggled with efficiency, having hauled in 59 percent of his targets while posting a 6.6 YPT and 3.0 RAC. Samuel did make some noise in the touchdown department last season, scoring seven times on 47 touches, though his 4.4 OTD suggests he was over his head. Samuel played at least 60 percent of Carolina's snaps in five games last season and was fantasy's No. 32 WR those weeks. There's third-year breakout potential here, so Samuel is fine mid-to-late-round option.

outlooksByWeek.1: From early-round riser last summer to forgettable committee back in his second season, Freeman has the chance to prove he's a worthy backfield partner to playmaking peer Phillip Lindsay. Likely without a sizable share of the passing market, Freeman will need to prove efficient on the ground against an Oakland defense that was amongst the worst in football last season. Ultimately, Freeman's uninspiring spot in the backfield committee keeps him out of the flex tier this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Denver's Week 2 opponent, Chicago, has allowed the fourth-fewest yards per carry (3.62) to tailbacks since the start of last season, presenting real risk for Freeman's fantasy profile given he's somewhat dependent on rushing efficiency. Without much value as a receiving threat, Freeman is a low-floor option for this Week 2 meeting with the stout Bears.
outlooksByWeek.3: Now a true peer of Phillip Lindsay in the Broncos' passing phase, Freeman joins his backfield mate in the flex tier of running backs. He'll face a Green Back defense that has been defended the pass well but has allowed 6.1 yards per carry to backs, the second-highest clip in the league.
outlooksByWeek.4: A shoulder injury saw Freeman head to the locker room for a spell early in Week 3, but he returned to action in the second quarter and gamely compiled 73 scrimmage yards on 19 touches. The Broncos are doing their best to feed both Freeman and Phillip Lindsay equally. Freeman is a flex option against a solid Jacksonville front in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: A third-round pick last season, Freeman looked well on his way to a terrific rookie campaign following an impressive preseason. Instead, fellow rookie Phillip Lindsay stole the spotlight, and Freeman was left running against stacked boxes (7.1 box defenders per carry was fourth-highest) in a situational role most of the season. Freeman averaged a pedestrian 4.0 YPC, but his 2.2 YAC ranked 14th at the position. Freeman struggled as a receiver, adding only 14 catches for 72 yards (3.4 YPT) on 21 targets. Lindsay's late-season struggles and Denver's new coaching staff are expeced to lead to a larger role for Freeman, but Lindsay won't completely disappear, and Freeman's receiving woes can't be ignored. There's post-hype appeal here, but Freeman should be on benches to begin 2019.

outlooksByWeek.1: Though the Saints are directing a run-first offense, Brees will often pop big numbers in the right matchup. Remember, he still threw for 32 touchdowns last year. The 39-year-old will host a Texans defense that just traded away pass-rusher Jadeveon Clowney, which should improve his chances of making plays. Plus, he should enjoy the addition of TE Jared Cook. Brees is safely ranked as a low-end QB1 in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Brees looked like his vintage fantasy No. 1 QB self in Week 1 while staging a late comeback win against the Texans, averaging 8.6 yards-per-attempt, which outpaces any of his single-season rates. Will he keep this going against the Rams? On the road, Brees typically breeds more distrust. Being outdoors docks him a bit, but the veteran should hover around fantasy QB1 territory for the mere fact that this should be a high-scoring affair.
outlooksByWeek.3: Brees is getting a second opinion, but the initial diagnosis of his thumb injury sustained in Week 2 says the veteran will miss 6-to-8 weeks. Fantasy managers may struggle to roster him in leagues that don't have IR spots, but he did look like his old elite self in Week 1, so it's probably worth stashing him wherever possible.
outlooksByWeek.4: Brees (thumb) is expected to miss at least another month. Teddy Bridgewater took over in Week 3. Stash Brees if possible.

player.seasonOutlook: Brees has remained one of the league's best passers in recent seasons, but his fantasy production has dropped off considerably since New Orleans improved defensively. Granted he sat out Week 17 last season, but Brees was limited to six top-10 fantasy weeks and finished outside the top seven for the season for the second year in a row. In 2018, Brees finished outside the top 10 in pass attempts, completions and yards for the first time since at least 2009. Brees, who has finished third or better in completion percentage nine of the past 10 seasons, has enough talent to post another top-10 season, but a more-balanced offense and fewer late-game deficits has capped his ceiling a bit.

outlooksByWeek.1: The rapid return of Emmanuel Sanders has likely slowed Sutton's ascent as the team's top downfield target, yet there is still reasonable interest in using the young wideout as a flex option against an Oakland team that allowed 14 yards per reception to receivers last season, second most in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Sutton delivered his first career 100-yard game in a prime-time loss to the Raiders in Week 1. A greater challenge comes in Week 2; the Bears have allowed the fewest points per drive to opponents since the start of last season and have been solid in defending outside threats like Sutton. Given the sub-optimal matchup, Sutton is a fringe flex play.
outlooksByWeek.3: A strong Chicago defense quieted Sutton a bit this past week, but we can look to positive opportunity rates (such as leading the team with 11.5 air yards per target in Week 2) as reason to trust this second-year talent as a high-ceiling option heading into Lambeau.
outlooksByWeek.4: The lone productive receiver for the Broncos in Week 3, Sutton led the team in air yardage and actual yardage in another solid showing. The Jaguars present a stronger challenge given their tandem of top coverage corners, yet Sutton's solid usage pattern supports flex value for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Sutton was scooped up in the second round of the 2018 draft and played a fairly substantial role as a rookie. He was on the field for 82 percent of Denver's snaps and handled 5.2 targets per game (16 percent share). Sutton was held to two top-30 fantasy weeks and underwhelmed in a full-time role down the stretch, but a 42/704/4 is solid line for a rookie, especially one who posted a 14.2 aDOT (12th highest) and dealt with 28 percent of balls thrown his way registering as off target (10th highest). Joe Flacco's presence figures to limit his upside, but it's possible Sutton passes out Emmanuel Sanders for No. 1 duties at some point this season. He's an intriguing breakout candidate and worth a mid-to-late-round flier.

After pacing all kickers in fantasy points in 2017, Zuerlein missed five games in 2018, but still managed an 11th-place finish. Zuerlein was the top-scoring kicker when active and his nine top-10 weeks were two more than the next-closest kicker during those weeks. Incredibly, Zuerlein has produced 10-plus fantasy points in 18 of 27 games during Sean McVay's two seasons as head coach. The primary reason for the success has been volume. The Rams attempted 2.65 field goals per game (second most) in 2017 and 2.68 per game (most) in 2018, which are two of the five highest totals the NFL has seen during the past decade. Zuerlein has made 91.5 percent of his field goals over the past two seasons (fourth best). He is the clear No. 1 fantasy kicker option in 2019.

outlooksByWeek.1: A productive big-play threat for the Chargers over the years, Williams could set career highs in snaps and targets now that he's the clear No. 2 for the Raiders. Vertical threats like Williams can prove frustrating for fantasy purposes, especially against a solid Denver defense, thus he's not in the starting mix at the position just yet.
outlooksByWeek.2: Awesome usage led to awesome results in Week 1 for Williams, who netted WR1-like attention from Derek Carr. Williams not only led the Raiders in routes and yards, he impressively averaged 17.6 air yards per target, signalling a high-value vertical role for Oakland. The Chiefs are among the best matchups for a receiver, thus Williams is now a solid WR2 prospect ahead of Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: A hip pointer could slow Williams a bit, but he still profiles as a solid WR3 or flex heading into a matchup with a Vikings defense that struggled to contain the Packers' playmakers last week. There is some risk present given Minnesota's longer sample of good pass defense, but Williams' awesome share of this offense fuels strong expectations.
outlooksByWeek.4: A quiet Week 3 saw Williams barely targeted for much of the contest, but it's still worth noting he's leading the team in routes run by nearly 20 on the season and should resume a stronger workload this week against a Colts defense allowing the 11th-most fantasy points to receivers. Given an expected uptick in targets this week, Williams is back in the WR3 mix.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams heads to Oakland where - following the release of Antonio Brown - he'll take over as the team's No. 1 wideout. Williams was a full-time player, but primarily worked as a situational target throughout his four seasons with the Chargers. A Week 1 Keenan Allen injury forced Williams into No. 1 receiver duties back in 2016 and he delivered with a 69/1059/7 line and an 18th-place finish in fantasy points. That was, by far, Williams' most productive season and he's otherwise failed to eclipse five scores or post a fantasy finish better than 45th. Williams' resume suggests he won't be a high-volume target (he has been limited to a 13 percent target share each of the past two seasons), but his propensity for big plays (career 16.3 YPR) provides optimism that he can push for WR2 numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: A hamstring injury kept Ross out of the preseason, making it difficult to determine just how much of a role Ross will play for a depleted Cincinnati passing attack. The Seahawks were stingy against opposing receivers last season, resulting in Ross being a fade this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ross became the first Bengal with multiple 30-yard touchdowns in the same game since T.J. Houshmandzadeh in 2007. That included a 55-yard touchdown catch with seven seconds remaining in second quarter against the Seahawks in Week 1. He had never had that many yards in an entire game in his career.
outlooksByWeek.3: Just as we all expected, Ross is the No. 2 fantasy receiver through the first two weeks of the season. A team-leading 87 routes and a stellar 147 yards after contact have supported this surprising breakout. A blend of opportunity and play-making skills make Ross a fine flex option even against Buffalo's solid pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.4: An ugly Week 3 saw Ross secure just two of six targets, but he's still tied for the team lead in routes run and was close to a few big plays in the loss to Buffalo. He's poised for a potential bounce-back performance against the Steelers, who have allowed the seventh-most fantasy points to receivers this year.

player.seasonOutlook: Ross made his name with a record 4.22-second 40-yard dash at the 2017 NFL combine, but his career is off to a rough start. Ross battled through injuries and fumbled on his only touch as a rookie before posting a bizarre 21/210/7 line on 58 targets in 2018. The 2017 ninth overall pick caught 36 percent of his targets and averaged 3.6 YPT, both of which were worst at the position. Granted, a league-high 36 percent of balls thrown his way were off target, but Ross averaged only 10.0 YPR despite a 13.9 aDOT (15th highest). He scored seven touchdowns, but his 4.8 OTD suggests that's unsustainable. Durability is a major concern for the 23-year-old, as he already has missed 16 games with various injuries. He could still turn the corner, but he's no more than a dynasty stash.

outlooksByWeek.1: Carolina will often be a decent matchup play for fantasy purposes, but the Rams come to town in the 2019 opener. Leave the Panthers D/ST on waiver wires in Week 1 in what could be an embarrasing affair for the unit.
outlooksByWeek.2: Carolina had one interception and one sack in Week 1 against the talented Rams offense. They'll host the Buccaneers on Thursday night. Jameis Winston tossed three interceptions in his opener, and that penchant for turnovers makes Carolina a decent one-week rental for fantasy D/ST value.
outlooksByWeek.3: Carolina had three sacks and a safety in Week 2 but this D/ST stands to have a worse fate in Week 3 at the Cardinals' promising Kyler Murray-led offense. The problems may be compounded if Panthers QB Cam Newton (foot) has to miss the game, which would limit the offense's ability to retain possession. If Newton plays, this D/ST could do as a last resort. If he's out, defintiely shift to another option.
outlooksByWeek.4: QB Kyle Allen's presence actually elevated the Panthers offense, which in turn helped the defense get chances to record fantasy points with takeaways and QB takedowns. In fact, Carolina pestered Cardinals rookie QB Kyler Murray in Week 3, sacking him a whopping eight times and reeling in two interceptions. Traveling to face Deshaun Watson, DeAndre Hopkins and the Texans, however, lowers the ceiling -- except maybe in the sacks column. If your league doesn't penalize too much for points allowed, Carolina could remain a useful D/ST starter in Week 4.  However, this D/ST could end up hurt by a potentially high-scoring indoor affair.

outlooksByWeek.1: The class of the tight end position, Kelce consumes WR1-like usage on what is the league's top offense. The Jaguars allowed the 11th-fewest yards to tight ends last season and will likely bracket Kelce whenever possible in coverage, but none of that should get in the way of Kelce delivering TE1 results.
outlooksByWeek.2: Kelce earned a target on nearly 35% of his routes in Week 1, a robust rate that only again confirms what a special piece of the Chiefs' offense he's become. The Raiders have allowed 1,089 yards and nine touchdowns to tight ends in the past 17 games, all well above league average allowance. Start and enjoy.
outlooksByWeek.3: If the Ravens' defense has struggled over the past year in defending one position, it's tight end; Baltimore has allowed 1,023 yards to the position over the past 18 games, 12th-most in the league. Kelce continues to earn awesome opportunity rates even if he's yet to break out with a huge game, signaling he's due for a strong line.
outlooksByWeek.4: Quietly averaging nearly 17 yards per catch thanks to an awesome 11.3 air yards per target, Kelce is on path for yet another elite statistical campaign. The Lions have yielded the 10th-fewest yards to tight ends this season, but they've also yet to face Kelce.

player.seasonOutlook: Kelce set career-high marks in pass routes (530), targets (149), receptions (103), receiving yards (1,336) and touchdowns (10) last season. As incredible as that achievement is, he did this after already leading all tight ends in fantasy points each of the previous two seasons. Since missing his rookie season with a knee injury, Kelce has finished a season no lower than eighth at the position in receptions, no lower than sixth in receiving yards, no lower than 12th in touchdowns and no lower than ninth in yards per target. The three-time No. 1 fantasy tight end handled 26 percent of Kansas City's targets last season and should be in that range again in 2019. The 29-year-old is your top option at the position and worth a look in the second round of your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: With five catches or at least 70 yards in 14 games last season, Allen has emerged as one of the most consistent weekly PPR performers in fantasy football. The Colts allowed the second-fewest yards to receivers last season and claim a talented secondary, but arguably lack the top cover talent requisite to slow down Allen. Given what should be a heavy workload at home this week, Allen remains firmly in the WR1 class.
outlooksByWeek.2: Allen was close to an even bigger opener as he almost had a second touchdown in the contest, but managers will gladly take his unique blend of volume (10 targets) and efficiency (eight receptions). Allen could net strong coverage from the Lions' talented corners, but as the top target of Philip Rivers with such a strong and longstanding rapport, it's best to trust the larger sample of success for Allen this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Leading the NFL in air yardage through two weeks, Allen's 221 actual yards are the sixth-most through two games by a Charger and the most since Tony Martin's 230 in 1995.  The Texans struggle at outside cornerback, setting up Allen for another strong WR1 performance.
outlooksByWeek.4: Allen has produced the most fantasy points among skill players in ESPN PPR formats this season in part thanks to delivering his 10th career game with 10 receptions this past Sunday. The Dolphins have some talent at cornerback, but have still proven uniquely susceptible to big receiving plays. Allen is in a great spot to meet and even exceed his projection this week.

player.seasonOutlook: After missing 26 games (including at least one each season) during his first four NFL seasons, Allen has appeared in all 32 of the Chargers games during the past two regular seasons. In fact, he has been on the field for 91 percent of the team's pass plays and has handled a hefty 28 percent target share. Allen has finished no lower than 13th at the position in targets, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points during each of the past two seasons. If there's a concern area, it's touchdowns, as Allen hasn't scored more than six in a season since his rookie campaign in 2013. Allen's 5.4 OTD last season suggests he was fortunate to even reach six scores. Allen is in his prime at age 27 and one of the game's most effective receivers. Philip Rivers' top target is a safe back-end WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Normally, it would be tricky for a team to juggle talented pass-catchers like Woods, Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp with a workhorse back like Todd Gurley II, but this Rams team is as fantasy-friendly as it gets. Woods had a breakout campaign for Los Angeles last season and is all set to repeat his efforts in 2019. That begins in Week 1 when he'll take on the mediocre Panthers pass defense (fifth-most touchdowns allowed through the air), making him a solid WR2 pick.
outlooksByWeek.2: Woods led the Rams in targets, catches and yards in Week 1 --  an encouraging sign for a receiver who is one of three talented players at his position. He didn't make any splash plays, but he was targeted downfield and will have bigger games down the road this season. You drafted Woods for a reason, so keep him locked in as a WR2 this week against the Saints.
outlooksByWeek.3: Woods has yet to produce any big plays this season like teammates Cooper Kupp and Brandin Cooks have, but his time will almost certainly come. This offense is always going to have its ups and downs for various players as the ball is spread around between three amazing wideouts and a talented running back. So far, Woods has been on the wrong side of most of the offensive production. Don't lose hope. The Browns are an appealing matchup in Week 3, so start Woods as a WR2 and don't worry about him moving forward.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Rams have an impressive wide receiver trio, but Woods currently appears to be third in line among that group. He lacks the explosive plays of Brandin Cooks and the volume of Cooper Kupp, but only barely in both regards. He could find a big play at any moment in this talented offense, and he's only eight targets behind Kupp through three games. Don't panic! Continue to start him as a high-end WR3/flex pick this week against a Buccaneers team that struggled against rookie Daniel Jones in Week 3.

player.seasonOutlook: Fantasy's reigning No. 11 scoring wide receiver, the sure-handed Woods has averaged a healthy 24 percent target share during his two seasons with the Rams. During the seven full games Woods, Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp played together last season, Woods paced the team with a 24 percent share (7.9 per game) and ranked 11th in fantasy points. Woods ranked second among all receivers in snaps (996) and was top 10 in touches (105) and scrimmage yards (1376). The concerns with Woods are touchdowns (he has never cleared six touchdown receptions or eight end zone targets in a season) and durability (he has missed at least two games in four of six NFL seasons). Nonetheless, he's the No. 1 receiver in Sean McVay's high-scoring offense and thus a solid WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Long viewed as a breakout candidate as the second in line in the Atlanta backfield behind Devonta Freeman, Coleman will get his shot at a full-time role in San Francisco. In limited playing time, Coleman has proven to be a point-scorer from a fantasy perspective, finding the end zone regularly as both a runner and receiver with the Falcons. Against a Tampa Bay defense that ranked among the most-favorable matchups for running backs last season, consider Coleman to be a RB3/flex candidate with some intruiging upside, thanks to his change of scenery.
outlooksByWeek.2: Coleman had a couple of positive moments in Week 1, but would leave with an ankle injury that could sideline him for a few weeks.

player.seasonOutlook: Coleman signed on with the 49ers following four seasons with the Falcons. The 2015 third-round pick has yet to clear 167 carries or 32 receptions in a single season but has delivered strong efficiency (4.4 YPC and 11.0 YPR in 56 career games) and touchdown production (29 scores). In fact, Coleman is one of only five players who have scored eight or more offensive touchdowns each of the past three seasons. He found pay dirt 11 times in 2016, when current 49ers coach Kyle Shanahan was the Falcons' OC. Coleman will certainly play a role in the 49ers' backfield, but he is expected to work in a timeshare with Matt Breida. Coleman is safest as a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jeffery was pretty much himself in 2018, only over just 13 games. He still posted his highest yardage (843) since 2014 and has 15 touchdowns across his past two seasons, so he has a useful place on many fantasy squads. His ceiling in this crowded Eagles pass-catching picture, however, remains questionable. Against the Redskins, however, he's ranked as a fantasy WR3. He logged 5-59-1 against them in Week 17 last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jeffery both caught and ran for a score in Week 1, taking a backseat to DeSean Jackson's 2-TD aerial show in his return. Jeffery held his own, though, coming through on his typical WR3 fantasy value. He may have to deal with Desmond Trufant in Week 2, but Jeffery succeeded with Josh Norman looming over him for much of the opener. Keep Jeffery in fantasy WR3 territory.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jeffery (calf) could miss the next two game since Week 4's schedule has the Eagles playing on Thursday. He failed to register any Week 2 stats because he left the game early. His fantasy shareholders must begin prepping for a possible absence. In-house, they have WR Nelson Agholor (the best pickup). Other choices include Mack Hollins and rookie JJ Arcega-Whiteside, but their consistency questions might not make them the best avenues.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jeffery (calf) didn't suit up for Week 3 and is questionable for the quick turnaround game on Thursday against the Packers. If he does play, expect less than his typical high-end WR3 fantasy ceiling, especially because the Packers have been one of the stingiest fantasy defenses against receivers (23.6 points-per-game, the second-lowest mark).

player.seasonOutlook: Jeffery has posted a pair of solid fantasy seasons since joining the Eagles, but he has done it two different ways. In 2017, a massive 28 percent of balls thrown his direction were off target, which led to an ugly 48 percent catch rate. He still posted a 57/789/9 line and finished 21st in fantasy points. In 2018, Jeffery missed three games and was targeted closer to the line of scrimmage more often, which allowed a healthy 71 percent catch rate and 65/840/6 line. Jeffery was fantasy's No. 17 WR after returning in Week 4. The rangy receiver has reached double digits in end zone targets during each of the past six seasons and is the top perimeter option in a strong Eagles' offense. The 29-year-old is a solid WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: A sizable role in arguably the NFL's top offense signals real upside for Watkins. The "if" always comes next with Watkins, who hasn't been able to stay on the field for much of his career. That said, Watkins enters the season healthy and should be afforded some worthy vertical looks as the Jaguars roll coverage over the Tyreek Hill.
outlooksByWeek.2: Watkins set career-highs with 198 receiving yards and three scores, both good for the most by Chiefs player in a season-opener in franchise history. With Tyreek Hill sidelined and Watkins flush with valuable looks from Patrick Mahomes, he's suddenly reentered the WR1 tier for this trip to face a suspect Oakland secondary.
outlooksByWeek.3: Watkins was dealt with a team-high 13 targets in Week 2 and now sits 12th in the league in air yardage. With awesome opportunity rates in the league's best offense, Watkins is in a good spot to overcome a tough matchup with the Ravens' secondary.
outlooksByWeek.4: Even as his lines have been somewhat quiet since Week 1's amazing output, Watkins remains the team's leader in routes run and targets the past two weeks. This signals some big plays are going to resurface for Watkins and Patrick Mahomes. The Lions have some capable coverage talent at cornerback, but Watkins' strong share of the Chiefs' offense merits trust from fantasy managers.

player.seasonOutlook: Watkins hasn't posted a top 40 fantasy season since 2015, but injuries have been a big culprit. The 2014 first-round pick averaged a 21 percent target share (6.9 per game) during the 10 games he played in full last season. Believe it or not, he trailed Tyreek Hill (73) by only four targets during those weeks. Eight of the 10 games came during the regular season and Watkins was fantasy's No. 16 scoring wideout those weeks. Watkins posted a healthy 9.4 YPT despite a career-low 8.4 aDOT. Bizarrely, he was limited to one end zone target, which explains his three touchdowns. Watkins' durability is an obvious concern (he has missed at least three games during three of the past four seasons) but he plays a big role in arguably the league's best offense, which makes him a WR3 with WR2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Metcalf is big, strong, and fast -- characteristics fantasy managers typically like in a wide receiver. However, he's also young, unproven, and has been dealing with some nagging injuries -- things no one wants to hear heading into a rookie's first pro game. The Bengals offer up a fantastic matchup for the Seattle passing game, as they allowed the most passing yards in the league a year ago. That means a healthy, starting Metcalf is a wild-card flex play for those willing to take a bit of a risk. If not, he's still definitely a player to keep on your bench to see what sort of role he earns.
outlooksByWeek.2: Metcalf is an exciting prospect who got a few chances to show what he can do in his pro debut. He saw three times as many targets as any other Seattle receiver or tight end in Week 1 and finished with a team-high 89 yards receiving. He even flashed his big-play potential with a 42-yard grab. It was a great start for the rookie and we can expect more of the same in Week 2 against a Steelers defense that allowed three touchdowns to receivers in Week 1. He's a flex option in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.3: Metcalf is quickly becoming a must-start player in Seattle's offense, as he's nearly doubled the yards-per-catch of fellow wideout Tyler Lockett through two weeks. He also found the end zone for his first NFL touchdown in Week 2. Tight ends and running backs are involved in the Seattle passing game, but when Russell Wilson is looking down the field, Metcalf is one of only two options he'll consider on a regular basis.  The Ole Miss product and Lockett have combined for 27 targets while no other wideout has more than three. Against a Saints team that has allowed quite a few big plays in the passing game already this season, that makes Metcalf an appealing, high-upside flex option.
outlooksByWeek.4: In Week 1, it seemed like Metcalf might have already carved out a bigger role than Tyler Lockett in the Seattle offense, but those tides have turned quickly. The rookie out of Ole Miss is seeing a respectable 6-7 targets each week, but it's Lockett who has quickly risen back to the top of the receiving charts in Seattle. Metcalf is a great red-zone target and is producing decent numbers when he catches the ball, so against an Arizona team that's allowed the eight-most passing yards so far this season, he's someone to consider for your flex spot.

player.seasonOutlook: The Seahawks selected Metcalf with the final pick of the second round of April's draft. Metcalf is huge (6-foot-3, 228 pounds) with terrific explosiveness, speed and downfield play-making ability. The former Ole Miss star is young (he turns 22 in December) and raw, the latter of which can somewhat be attributed to injury woes. Metcalf showed off his speed and size at the combine with a 4.33 40-yard dash and 27 bench reps, though he did raise major red flags by struggling in quickness events. Metcalf has the upside to become one of the league's next premiere vertical receivers, especially with Russell Wilson on the other end of the battery, but he figures to be more boom/bust than a consistent producer as a situational deep threat in Seattle's super-run-heavy offense in 2019.

outlooksByWeek.1: In his lone start against the Jets as a rookie, Allen failed to throw a touchdown and turned the ball over three times. A debacle? Hardly. Allen ran for 101 yards and a score. We can expect a Gregg Williams defense to prove blitz-heavy, meaning the dual-threat quaterback could be on the move, but there still is clearly risk in trusting Allen as a passer on the road in Week 1. He's firmly in the QB2 tier.
outlooksByWeek.2: Four turnovers weakened Allen's fantasy output for the Bills in Week 1, but another strong day on the ground helped salvage his outing. If you can stomach the negative plays, Allen is primed for a positive Week 2 showing against the Giants, who surrendered the seventh-most points per drive to opponents and allowed the seventh-most rushing yards to quarterbacks.
outlooksByWeek.3: Another game, another rushing score for Buffalo's second-year signal-caller, who now leads quarterbacks in rushing touchdowns since the start of last season with 10. We're also seeing solid passing results emerge for Allen; he's averaged 253.5 through two weeks and next hosts a Bengals defense that has allowed 11 yards per attempt to opposing arms this season. Only the Dolphins (11.9) have allowed more. Given the floor his rushing production helps support, Allen is a viable starting option at home this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Bills are 3-0 for the first time since 2011 thanks to Josh Allen orchestrating two game-winning drives.  Among quarterbacks this season, Allen’s 105 rush yards trail only Lamar Jackson (172) and his 78 scramble yards are just behind Gardner Minshew (81). In fact, no one has more scramble yards than Allen since he entered the league last year, and his five scramble TDs are three more than any other quarterback. The Patriots have the second-highest sack rate, so Allen will be busy scrambling to another QB1 performance.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen's rookie season was as expected on one hand and anything but on the other. The expected part was his struggles as a passer. Allen posted an ugly 10-to-12 TD/INT mark and ranked dead last in both completion percentage (53 percent) and off-target rate (22 percent). His 6.5 yards per attempt was fourth worst despite a league-high 11.2 aDOT. The surprising aspect was Allen's elite rushing production. Allen carried the ball 89 times for 631 yards and 8 touchdowns and his 7.1 yards per carry topped the position. The latter allowed Allen the most fantasy points at the position once he returned from injury in Week 12 through Week 17. Allen's passing struggles make him a risky fantasy investment, but he's worth a late-round flier because of his rushing contributions.

outlooksByWeek.1: The NFC West has been a goldmine for D/ST units in recent years, and the Rams stand out as the pick from the current crop. This group has finished near the top of the leaderboard among D/STs for two straight seasons and there's no reason to pick against them in 2019. With some new faces like Eric Weddle and Clay Matthews joining an already solid core, this is a "set it and-forget it" D/ST for the entire season. Well, as long as you don't forget about their bye week!
outlooksByWeek.2: Remember, splash plays like turnovers forced, touchdowns scored and sacks made matter more for a fantasy D/ST's long-term value than points allowed. So, while the Rams may have ceded 27 points on the scoreboard in Week 1, they picked up three sacks, made two fumble recoveries and an interception to help rack up nine fantasy points. That's what you should expect most weeks from this talented defense. They're a set-and-forget option, and Week 2 against Detroit is no exception.
outlooksByWeek.3: Baker Mayfield is certainly prone to throwing interceptions -- four so far this year. The Browns offensive line, plus Mayfield's style of play, can certainly lead to sacks -- eight over the first two games. The Rams are already one of the premier D/STs in fantasy, so having any sort of appealing matchup makes them a must-start in all leagues. Don't hesitate to plug them in to your lineup.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Rams have been the seventh-best D/ST so far this season, and it would be an upset for them to ever leave the top 10. They've got the right combination of playmakers who create turnovers, sack the quarterback and also keep points allowed low. This unit is a good pick almost any week - and this week is no different, as they host a very turnover-prone Buccaneers squad.

player.seasonOutlook: Most eyes are focused on the Rams' Sean McVay-led offense, but their Wade Phillips-led defense has finished top-four in fantasy points each of the past two seasons. The Rams have ranked top-six in forced turnovers, interceptions, blocks and D/ST touchdowns both seasons. Ndamukong Suh and Lamarcus Joyner were notable offseason losses, but the team remains strong up front with Aaron Donald and added Eric Weddle in the secondary. A new-look pass rush (Dante Fowler Jr., Clay Matthews) is improved from last season, and the secondary remains a strength of the roster. This unit is, once again, a top D/ST option.

outlooksByWeek.1: The fourth back on a crowded depth chart, it's fine to leave Burkhead in fantasy free agency for this meeting with a solid Pittsburgh rush defense.
outlooksByWeek.2: With more targets and touches than James White in Week 1, Burkhead reemerged as a playmaker for the Pats against the Steelers. It's always tough to predict this backfield breakdown, but for those in deeper leagues, there is some growing appeal for Burkhead given his rewarding gadget role in a top offense. Without a defined role just yet, it's best to consider Burkhead a savvy stash for now.
outlooksByWeek.3: With a real role carved out in this offense, Burkhead leads the team through two weeks in scrimmage yards per game (76.5). There likely isn't a very high ceiling for Burkhead as part of a three-man committee backfield, however.
outlooksByWeek.4: Leading the Patriots with 74 scrimmage yards per game thanks to strong receiving production, this versatile vet led the team's backfield in snap percentage last week. The return of James White to the fold will cut into Burkhead's receiving potential, but he's entering the streaming tier of tailbacks thanks to his dual-threat role for the Patriots. The Bills have been solid against tailbacks this season, adding some risk to Burkhead's profile.

player.seasonOutlook: Burkhead has appeared in 23 games across two seasons with the Patriots, handling roughly one quarter of the carries and just under 10 percent of the targets during both seasons. Last season's 3.3 YPC was both the worst of his career and fourth-worst at the position, but note that he has finished second and first, respectively, in average box defenders each of the past two seasons. The 29-year-old is a competent rusher and effective receiver with a defined role in one of the league's best offenses. He has little standalone value, and that's doubtful to change with James White, Sony Michel and Damien Harris all on the roster.

outlooksByWeek.1: Valdes-Scantling emerged as the best rookie receiver from the Packers' draft class in 2018, handling a decent workload in terms of targets and hauling in a couple of touchdowns. With Randall Cobb no longer on the team, there's an opening for the role of No. 2 receiver behind Davante Adams, and the USF product is considered the front-runnner to claim that spot. However, it's an open audition and he's not yet proven himself, so he's a bit of a flex flier for now until his role becomes more obvious -- especially against a tough Bears defense.
outlooksByWeek.2: Valdes-Scantling played the second-most snaps of any Packers wideout (or any pass-catcher for that matter) and led Green Bay in both catches and yards in an ugly win over the Bears. That's an encourgaing sign, to be sure, but he's still a distant second to Davante Adams at the WR position and he will likely fall behind TE Jimmy Graham when the Packers are in the red zone. As such, he's one to keep on the bench -- especially in Week 2 against a solid Minnesota defense -- in the hopes of a breakout somewhere down the line this season.
outlooksByWeek.3: Valdes-Scantling is locked in as the No. 2 receiver for Green Bay, which is a great role for fantasy purposes. He's absolutely a name to consider -- in the future. However, the Packers' run of three impossible matchups concludes this week as they take on Denver's elite pass defense. Keep Valdes-Scantling on your bench against a team that has allowed only one passing touchdown over 2019's first two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.4: Tied for No. 1 in targets with Davante Adams, Valdes-Scantling seems to be locked in as the Packers' No. 2 wideout. He will see a healthy amount of looks in what should be an improving passing offense. After facing three consecutive defenses that are very strong against the pass, Week 4 brings with it a matchup with the Eagles, who have allowed at least one 100-yard receiver in each of the first three games. Look for Valdes-Scantling to show up regularly when Aaron Rodgers drops back to pass, making him a flex pick for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: The Packers drafted a trio of wide receivers in the mid-to-late rounds of the 2018 draft and fifth-rounder Valdes-Scantling emerged as the top producer of the three. Valdes-Scantling posted a 38/581/2 line and a solid 8.2 YPT despite 31 percent of balls thrown his way registering as off target (fifth highest). He averaged 5.7 yards after the catch, which was 11th best at the position. Especially with Randall Cobb gone, the Packers' wide receiver depth chart is wide open. Valdes-Scantling, who stands 6-foot-5 and aligned in the slot on 46 percent of his routes as a rookie, will have a shot at flex value if he locks down No. 2 or perhaps No. 3 duties in Green Bay's Aaron Rodgers-led offense. He's worth a mid-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Freeman's health has been his biggest enemy in recent seasons, and he played just two games in 2018. The departure of Tevin Coleman still doesn't completely clear him, because several young backs could steal work again. Still, Freeman is Atlanta's top back. Against a tough Vikings defense, he should be busy. Count him as a high-end fantasy RB2 in the 2019 opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: Freeman lost a fumble in a disappointing Week 1 effort, and Ito Smith continued to creep up on his workload. Atlanta was in comeback mode, so the run game took a backseat for most of the contest. He should be more involved against the Eagles, especially in the passing game, though he's squarely outside the fantasy RB1 tier -- and even his RB2 stock is dipping.
outlooksByWeek.3: Freeman slightly made up for another abysmal showing in Week 2 by doing more work as a receiver, but he's still losing momentum atop this backfield. Atlanta's play-calling in the first two games hasn't done him any favors, but neither does averaging 2.2 yards-per-carry. The Colts have been one of the friendliest fantasy defenses against the run so far (allowing 33.1 RB fantasy points-per-game) making Freeman a flex play for Week 3. It's dangerous for fantasy players to consider him as anything more than that, given  the presence of Ito Smith.
outlooksByWeek.4: Freeman took advantage of a favorable matchup with a 95-yard day on offense in Week 3. He should continue to split work with Ito Smith, but this was a positive sign that Freeman's health isn't bothering him. Tennessee's tough run defense awaits in Week 4, but Freeman deserves at least high-end flex trust for fantasy lineups.

player.seasonOutlook: Freeman enters his sixth NFL season after missing all but 64 snaps due to injury last season. Of course, he posted stellar numbers in each of his previous three seasons. The 2014 fourth-round pick paced the position in fantasy points in 2015, finished sixth in 2016 and ranked ninth in the 13 weeks he was active and healthy in 2017. Freeman's efficiency has been good, but where he really stands out is volume near the goal line. He rushed for 29 touchdowns from 2015 to 2017, thanks to 41 carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line (second-most). He finished top-five in the category all three seasons and scored six touchdown receptions in that span. Tevin Coleman is gone, which helps solidify the 27-year-old's standing as a solid RB2 with RB1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Carson held off the Seahawks' 2018 first-round pick (Rashaad Penny) and kept his spot as the lead back in the Seattle offense heading into the 2019 season. He carried a respectable workload as a runner and racked up 1,151 rushing yards and eight scores, but was limited in his duties as a pass catcher. Even still, against a Bengals defense that allowed the most points to running backs last year, he's locked in as an RB1 in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Carson had a massive opening week, especially through the air. He saw a career-high seven targets, matching his career-best by hauling in six. He also scored touchdowns via both the air and the ground. Keep in mind that those stats did come against a Bengals team that allowed the most fantasy points to the RB position a year ago. Even still, it's a "statement game" to begin a season with that level of production. Carson's next opponent will be Pittsburgh, who allowed James White and Rex Burkhead to combine for 10 catches and 97 yards in Week 1. He's an easy pick as an RB2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Carson couldn't follow up on Week 1's 2-TD performance, failing to find the end zone against the Steelers and picking up only 87 yards from scrimmage on 18 touches. That said, the Oklahoma State product is still Seattle's lead back and one of the better options at the RB position in fantasy. In Week 3, he'll face the Saints, who haven't allowed a ton of production to opposing backs this season. As such, Carson isn't in a spot to break out by any means. Still, he's on the cusp of being an RB1 and more than good enough to start for any team in any format.
outlooksByWeek.4: Carson's 15 carries in Week 3 perfectly matched his totals from Weeks 1 and 2. It's been a humorously consistent workload for the Seahawks' starting back. However, one thing that has not remained consistent is his passing-game involvement. His seven targets in Week 1 now seem like an outlier, as he saw just three looks in Week 2 and only one in Week 3. He's also yet to break off a run of longer than 23 yards, averaging only 3.5 YPC. It's this lack of production, perhaps, that prompted Russell Wilson to run on his own more in Week 3. That's bad news, but the good news is that in Week 4 he faces an Arizona defense that was embarrassed by Christian McCaffrey in Week 3.

player.seasonOutlook: The Seahawks drafted a running back (Rashaad Penny) in the first round of the 2018 draft, but that didn't stop second-year Carson from taking a firm grasp of lead back duties last season. Carson posted 247 carries (seventh-most) for 1,151 yards (fifth-most) and nine scores (seventh-most) in 14 games as the lead back in Seattle's run-heavy offense. Carson averaged 2.29 yards after contact (11th-best) and, though he played a minimal role as a receiver, caught all but three of his 23 targets. Seattle's run-heavy scheme will be back in 2019, and Carson's terrific second season gives him the leg up on Penny for the bulk of the backfield touches. Carson is expected to see a boost in receiving work, as well, so he'll touch the ball more than enough to allow RB2 numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Penny was selected in the first round by the Seahawks in 2018, but draft status alone couldn't propel him to the top of the RB depth chart. Chris Carson carried the load as a runner, but Penny offered up a nice change of pace at times. He figures to do the same again in 2019. His value as a handcuff outweighs his Week 1 value, however, and he's no more than a flex option heading into a matchup with the Bengals, who struggled to stop the run a year ago.
outlooksByWeek.2: Penny was one of only two Seattle running backs to even see the field in Week 1, but he was clearly the second choice as Chris Carson had a huge game as the starter. Penny is a handcuff and high-value backup. Just don't start him in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Penny has seen a healthy workload through two weeks as Seattle's No. 2 running back. While he trails Chris Carson in snaps by over 40, he has had 16 carries plus  a target in the passing game when he's been on the field. That said, he's still not seeing enough volume to merit fantasy consideration, as only those in very deep leagues will have room for a player likely to see only seven carries-per-game with no involvement in the passing game. Keep him on the bench and wait to see if things change on the depth chart in Seattle.
outlooksByWeek.4: Penny missed out on Seattle's Week 3 loss, but could return for Week 4 against the Cardinals. That's a good time to return, as Arizona allowed Christian McCaffrey to run wild in Week 3. That said, Chris Carson is still Seattle's lead back and Russell Wilson took rushing matters more into his own hands in Week 3. The combination of Penny's injury status and the state of the Seahawks offense leave him as a risky flex option at best.

player.seasonOutlook: Penny was a surprise selection in the first round of the 2018 draft, and his rookie season was derailed by injuries and the emergence of Chris Carson. Penny appeared in 14 games and was on the field for 17 percent of Seattle's offensive snaps. The good news is that he was effective, racking up 419 yards on 85 carries (4.9 YPC) and 75 yards on 12 targets (6.3 YPT). The 23-year-old back has the size, talent and skill set to emerge into a three-down back, but he remains behind Carson on the depth chart. Penny is a terrific handcuff but lacks stand-alone value in his current role.

outlooksByWeek.1: Wilson has shown a variable ceiling over his seven-year NFL career, but his floor has been as steady as anyone at the QB position. He's averaged 20-plus fantasy points-per-game every year, and you can expect more of the same in 2019. The Bengals allowed the most passing yards-per-game in the NFL last season, rendering the decision quite easy for those with Wilson heading into Week 1. He's a starter in almost every kind of league.
outlooksByWeek.2: Wilson was efficient but not incredibly productive in Week 1, averaging 9.8 yards-per-attempt but only tossing 20 passes. He did score a pair of touchdowns and posted a solid fantasy score, but didn't add anything with his feet in the running game. He's a solid QB1 this week (and most weeks), especially against a Steelers defense that seems to be in transition, struggling in Week 1 against the Patriots. Still, you shouldn't be expecting huge numbers from Wilson every week.
outlooksByWeek.3: It's easy to look at passing statistics when considering how a quarterback will do against a defense, but don't forget to check the rushing stats, too. Both the Texans and Rams scored rushing touchdowns with their passers against the Saints this season. In 2018, five different quarterbacks ran for scores against New Orleans. Russell Wilson would have been a must-start against the Saints even without the added rushing upside. Added to the mix, he absolutely belongs in your lineup. His ceiling might not be all that high, but you can expect a solid return from the veteran signal-caller.
outlooksByWeek.4: Wilson registered his first rushing touchdown since 2017 in a Week 3 loss to New Orleans -- and then added another for good measure. In fact, he was two yards away from being Seattle's leading rusher against the Saints, all while throwing for 406 yards and a pair of touchdowns. It was a fantasy manager's dream, as rushing yards from a quarterback are like icing on a delicious cake. Whether it's by air or by land, expect more goodness from Wilson in Week 4 against the Cardinals, who have allowed the third-most QB fantasy points this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Wilson paced all quarterbacks in fantasy scoring by 49 points in 2017, but Seattle's move to a run-heavy offense led to a dip all the way to ninth in 2018. Wilson posted eight top-10 outings (fifth most), but failed to clear 29 points in a single week. Wilson's 427 pass attempts ranked 20th and were his fewest since 2013. Wilson is a strong candidate for touchdown regression to the mean (his 8.2 percent TD rate ranks third over the past decade). Offensive line remains a concern after Wilson was sacked on 10.7 percent of his dropbacks (fifth highest). Wilson is extremely efficient and adds value with his legs, but Seattle's commitment to a run-heavy offense limits his fantasy upside. He's a back-end QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Patriots couldn't slow opposing rushers last season, as tailbacks averaged 4.8 yards per carry against New England in 2018, the sixth-highest allowance in the league. With almost no competition for carries and what should still be a sizable portion of receiving usage despite the emergence of Jaylen Samuels, Conner is set to deliver RB1 results as a versatile bell cow against the Patriots in prime time.
outlooksByWeek.2: One the field for just 46% of the Steelers' offensive snaps, Conner has seemingly lost some offensive equity to Jaylen Samuels (33% snap rate). This doesn't mean Conner isn't still an awesome fantasy option, because he is, but rather he might not have the same dominant share of touches that helped fuel last season's breakout. The Seahawks have allowed 4.55 yards per rush to backs since the stat of last season (league average is 4.35 for this sample), evidence Conner can deliver value as a rushing force this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: ESPN's Jeremy Fowler reported Conner's knee injury is considered minor and shouldn't limit him from playing this week. Monitoring practice reports will prove important this week ahead of a meeting with an improved 49ers defense. It isn't an ideal matchup, but Conner's majority share of backfield work for Pittsburgh keeps him in the RB2 discussion.
outlooksByWeek.4: Only the Dolphins have allowed more rushing yards to opposing backs than the Bengals. Conner retook command of receiving usage this past week, confirming he's a solid RB1 option heading into this division matchup with a weak Cincinnati front.

player.seasonOutlook: Second-year Conner was abruptly thrown into the fire last season with Le'Veon Bell sitting out the season. Conner picked up where his predecessor left off, handling 81 percent of the team's carries and 13 percent of the targets prior to suffering an injury in Week 13. During those 13 weeks, Conner put up 1,368 scrimmage yards and 13 touchdowns, which helped him to the fifth-most fantasy points among running backs. Conner's efficiency was solid and, unlike Bell, he benefited from getting many carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line (15, third-most). With Bell now in New York, the 24-year-old Conner returns as the Steelers' clear feature back. He's a back-end RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Facing a potential trace corner this week, Hill will need to be at his playmaking best to overcome a matchup with a top secondary. Then again, few schemes or individual talents have been able to slow Hill. Given his penchant for getting past defenses, Hill is a must-start option heading into this meeting with Jalen Ramsey.
outlooksByWeek.2: Hill left Week 1's win over the Jags in the first quarter with a shoulder injury and did not return. Reports suggest Hill avoided a serious injury but should miss multiple games as a result.
outlooksByWeek.3: Hill is still several weeks away from playing due to a shoulder injury.

player.seasonOutlook: Hill has seen his production increase during each of his NFL seasons. Fantasy's No. 19 scoring receiver as a rookie in 2016, Hill climbed to eighth in 2017 and to first in 2018. Though Hill's usage has progressively increased, he has made his hay with outstanding efficiency. He paced all wide receivers with an 11.5 YPT in 2017 and finished fifth at 10.9 last season. He also has ranked top 12 in YPR and RAC both seasons, while actually reaching a career high 14.7 aDOT last season (eighth highest). The versatile Hill has ranked second among wideouts in carries during each of his three seasons and has added four rushing and five return touchdowns along the way. Hill is a mid-range WR1 with upside to again pace the position in fantasy points.

outlooksByWeek.1: Thielen has emerged as one the league's most consistent receivers, starting off last season with an incredible run of eight consecutive 100-yard games. The 29-year-old had some soreness and injury concerns during the preseason, but assuming nothing alarming comes out about his status prior to kickoff, he should be set to lead Vikings receivers against the Falcons. Atlanta allowed the sixth-most fantasy points to wideouts last season, which means a healthy Thielen is a WR1 for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: The Vikings hardly had to throw the ball at all on Sunday and, when they did, it went the way of their star wideouts and lead running back. Thielen combined with Stefon Diggs and Dalvin Cook to account for seven of the team's targets on Kirk Cousins' 10 attempts. He also hauled in a team-high three passes and caught a touchdown before Minnesota turned off the passing game in favor of a run-first approach in a game that quickly got out of hand. A matchup with the Packers is tougher from a personnel standpoint, but better from a competitiveness standpoint, so don't worry about Thielen at all this week. He's a borderline WR1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Minnesota pass-catchers have seen only 42 targets over two weeks -- and 20 of those have gone to Thielen and fellow wideout Stefon Diggs. When the Vikings do air it out, those are clearly their preferred options, with Thielen seeing a slight edge in volume so far. The Vikings are certainly a run-first team this year, but they will pass it enough to sustain the fantasy value of their receivers. The Raiders allowed a big day to the Chiefs in Week 2 (to no one's surprise), but also let Emmanuel Sanders post decent numbers in Week 1. That bodes well enough for Thielen that he can be locked in as a WR2 for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Vikings don't take to the air often, but when they do, it seems to go to Thielen more often than not. He has seen 16 targets (most on the Vikings), and has reeled in two of the three receiving touchdowns the team has scored. A Week 4 matchup with the Bears will be difficult, as Chicago has one of the more talented defenses in the league, but Emmanuel Sanders found paydirt against them, as did Washington's Paul Richardson and Terry McLaurin. Trust Thielen as a WR2, despite the difficult opponent.

player.seasonOutlook: Thielen did it again. For the fourth consecutive season, he posted a career high in receptions (113), receiving yards (1,373) and fantasy points (307). Thielen also scored a career-high nine touchdowns, which nearly matched his previous career total of 10. Thielen posted eight top 10 fantasy weeks, which tied for most in the league, though he ended up seventh in fantasy points at season's end after Minnesota switched offensive coordinators and to a run-heavy offense down the stretch. Thielen has never cleared 10 end zone targets in a season, and Mike Zimmer's commitment to establishing the run could limit his upside a bit, but the 28-year-old has proven to be one of the best in the business. He's a strong WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: No tight end in history has racked up more receiving yards than Kittle did last season in what was the definition of a breakout campaign for the 2017 draftee. He hasn't proven to be a go-to guy in the red zone yet, and he saw only seven end-zone targets last season, but don't let that dissuade you. Against a Buccaneers side that allowed the third-most passing touchdowns a season ago, Kittle is a must-start tight end in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.2: Week 1 was more of the same for Kittle, who saw a team-high 10 targets (no one elese had more than three) and racked up 54 yards. He even found the end zone on a play that was called back due to a penalty. He's a high-volume tight end in a pretty tame offense, so he's got a high floor every week, especially in PPR leagues. The Bengals were one of the weaker teams at defending tight ends a year ago, so Kittle is locked in as a TE1 this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Kittle leads all 49ers pass-catchers in targets through two weeks. While he doesn't yet have any official touchdowns, he has found the end zone on more than one occasion this season only to see a yellow flag negate his efforts. He did see a surprising dip in volume in Week 2, but some variance is to be expected in an offense led by a somewhat inconsistent passer. He's still an elite tight end from a fantasy perspective and is a must-start against a Steelers defense that allowed Will Dissly to score twice in Week 2.

player.seasonOutlook: After showing flashes of his massive ceiling as a fifth-round rookie in 2017, Kittle exploded for a tight-end record 1,377 receiving yards last season. The Iowa product also ranked first at the position RAC (9.7) and was third in targets (136), receptions (88), fantasy points (259) and YPR (15.6). The only area where Kittle was truly underwhelming was in the scoring department, as he managed only five touchdowns (5.8 OTD) and seven end-zone targets. The future is bright for the 25-year-old Kittle, who will sustain a massive target share in the 49ers' improving offense. Scoop him up in the third round of your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kupp has been a solid fantasy contributor since making his debut for the Rams in 2017 after being selected in the third round of the NFL Draft. The Eastern Washignton product was holding his own among a crowded WR picture in 2018 before injuries cut his season short. He figures to handle a healthy workload in 2019 in a fantasy-friendly offense. The Panthers allowed the eight-most fantasy points to wideouts a year ago, so this is a great spot for Kupp to get back into a rhythm, assuming he's cleared to play and featured in the starting lineup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Welcome back, Cooper! Mr. Kupp hadn't played since November of last year, but stepped right back in and played his part in the Rams offense, seeing only a few snaps from the sideline. He finished second on the team in targets and, while he didn't rack up a ton of yards this time around, the yards will come -- especially on days when the Rams are working at a slightly higher level than they were in a bit of a slow Week 1 performance. He's definitely a WR2 for this week's contest against the Saints.
outlooksByWeek.3: Of the Rams' three elite wideouts, it's Kupp who has led the way so far this season, ranking first in catches, targets and yards. He's not yet found the end zone, but that's certain to come soon as this Jared Goff-led team gets into more back-and-forth offensive contests later this year. That kind of affair certainly could come in Week 3, as the Browns appear to be capable with the ball, but shaky without it. In Week 1, they allowed Marcus Mariota to throw for three scores. While Luke Falk and the Jets couldn't find paydirt in Week 2, they're a far cry from the Rams' prolific offense. Kupp is a borderline WR1 for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jared Goff may have three great receivers in his huddle, but Kupp has stood out above the others so far this season in terms of the numbers we care about in fantasy. The Eastern Washington product has the most targets and touchdowns of the WR trio, and has also seen the most red-zone looks. In Week 4, Kupp and the Rams host the Buccaneers, who allowed Sterling Shepard to go for 100 yards and a score in Week 3. They are not a defense to be feared. Start Kupp as a WR1 with confidence.

player.seasonOutlook: Kupp has been a solid fantasy asset since being selected in the third round of the 2017 draft, but a pair of injuries derailed what would've been a major breakout in 2018. During the seven full games he played with Brandin Cooks and Robert Woods last season, Kupp handled a solid 22 percent target share (7.3 per game) and ranked eighth in fantasy points. Kupp scored six touchdowns during those seven games (though his 2.7 OTD suggests he was over his head in that department). He also ranked third among receivers with a 77 percent catch rate, fourth with a 10.9 YPT, and second with a 7.6 RAC last season. The 26-year-old has the look of a solid WR2 play.

outlooksByWeek.1: You know the story with White; he's going to net tons of targets out of the backfield in the Patriots' quick-hitting passing attack. Success around the red zone is gravy for White, who has a penchant for big plays in high-leverage moments. Given the expectedly high score in this meeting with the Steelers, White is a solid RB2 option in PPR formats.
outlooksByWeek.2: With 82 scrimmage yards thanks to valuable receiving duties, White's Week 1 confirmed his high-floor persists. The Dolphins were badly gashed by the Ravens' backfield last week, with White and his backfield peers poised for strong fantasy results in South Beach.
outlooksByWeek.3: It's becoming clear White won't approach the amazing 120 targets he netted last season for a Patriots team that was missing several playmakers in the passing phase. Now flush with receiving depth, including fellow back Rex Burkhead, the Patriots don’t need to feed White all those receptions. This clearly hurts his stock heading into this matchup with a Jets front missing its best playmaker in C.J. Mosley, but he remains in the flex tier in PPR formats if for his unique red zone efficiency.
outlooksByWeek.4: White missed last week's win over the Jets due to the birth of his child. We all wish White's sleeping pattern some luck. Upon returning to the lineup this week we can expect White to resume his target-rich role out of the backfield, albeit with more competition from Rex Burkhead. The Bills present a matchup challenge, but White's consistent receiving share should support a solid flex performance.

player.seasonOutlook: White took his game to another level in 2018 and has cemented himself as one of the game's best receiving backs. In fact, the past four seasons, White ranks first at the position in targets (328), second in receptions (243), second in receiving yards (2141) and easily first in receiving touchdowns (19). He posted career-high marks in each of those categories in 2018, as well as carries (94) and yards per carry (4.5). White was fantasy's No. 6 scoring back through Week 9 last season, but his usage dropped when Sony Michel and Rex Burkhead were active, and he ranked 27th from Week 10 on. A similar backfield share is expected in 2019, which positions White more as a fringe RB2 than a likely repeat RB1. Downgrade him in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Can Lindsay sustain last season's brilliant yardage and scoring efficiency? The Raiders might not be the right team to ask; Lindsay burned Oakland for 6.4 yards per carry in two meetings last season. Lindsay is in the RB2 mix for this division meeting on Monday evening, as he's due roughly half of the total work out of the backfield against last season's league-worst defense.
outlooksByWeek.2: Lindsay's 66 scrimmage yards on 15 touches for the Broncos in Week 1 is likely the usage recipe we can expect for him going forward. Receiving usage could help Lindsay produce in an otherwise difficult setup facing a stingy Chicago front seven. With a tough opponent and a seemingly firm usage ceiling, Lindsay enters Week 2 as a low-end flex.
