outlooksByWeek.3: Denver wants to split work between Lindsay and Royce Freeman as evenly as possible. Lindsay netted 17 touches while running 23 routes to Freeman's 16 and 21 in the loss to the Bears in Week 2. Without the clear majority share of valuable receiving duties, Lindsay is a flex option against a Packers front that has allowed the second-most yards per carry (6.1) to backs this season.
outlooksByWeek.4: Lindsay thrived as a rusher and receiver in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Packers. Even while Royce Freeman is matching Lindsay in nearly every usage indicator, Lindsay is the stronger receiving option and a solid RB2 in a meeting with a respectable Jacksonville defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Lindsay entered the 2018 season as a notable combine snub who signed on with Denver as an undrafted free agent. It didn't take him long to become one of the league's most explosive playmakers. Lindsay averaged 5.4 YPC (sixth-highest) on 192 attempts and finished 13th among backs in fantasy points. Although Lindsay's explosiveness can't be overlooked, there were some red flags. He benefited from 3.82 yards before contact per attempt (second-highest), averaged 1.58 after contact (14th-worst), averaged 5.0 yards per target (sixth-worst) and saw his YPC plummet to 2.6 in his final three games. It's possible that we've already seen Lindsay's ceiling, as he turns 25 years old this summer, but he is set for a significant role along with fellow second-year back Royce Freeman this season. Lindsay figures to return to earth a bit, but he's still in the RB2 discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tate will be suspended for the first four regular-season games of 2019. He's worth a stash roster spot in many fantasy leagues, considering he'll be a big part of the Giants offense upon his Week 5 return. Make sure he's not in your Week 1 lineup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tate remains suspended for Week 2 against the Bills. He'll be banned for two more games before returning in Week 5 versus the Vikings. Those who can afford to stash him for the next three weeks can pick him up off the waiver wire as he should assume a top role in the Giants offense upon his return.
outlooksByWeek.3: Tate will serve the third contest of his four-game suspension in Week 3 against the Buccaneers. Continue stashing him, as he'll be a focal point of the Giants passing game upon his Week 5 return.
outlooksByWeek.4: Tate will serve the final game of his suspension in Week 4. If you have a spot to stash an impact player and the veteran is available, pick him up. The Giants have more downfield potential with Daniel Jones under center, and Tate will at least offer a valuable bye-week replacement moving forward.

player.seasonOutlook: Only months after being traded from the Lions to the Eagles, Tate signed with a Giants team in major need of wide receiver help after it traded away Odell Beckham Jr. during the offseason. Beckham averaged 10.5 targets per game during his five seasons in New York, whereas Tate averaged 8.0 per game during that same span. Of course, whereas Beckham was a down-field threat and high-end touchdown producer, Tate's 6.9 aDOT is lowest at the position and his 6.5 RAC is highest during the past five seasons. He has scored more than five touchdowns in a season just twice in nine years (2012, 2015). Tate, who has managed six-consecutive Top 30 fantasy campaigns, is suspended for four games to open 2019, but once back, the 31 year old will be a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season's highest scoring D/ST is back to defend the top spot in the rankings, and they'll start the season with a rivalry matchup against the Packers. Don't let a game against Green Bay scare you away, though. Since defense and special teams scoring is driven by splash plays, consider that the Bears led the NFL in interceptions and ranked No. 3 in sacks last season, fueling their fantasy point total. They're an easy pick to start this and every week of the 2019 season.
outlooksByWeek.2: In what turned out to be a bit of an ugly opening game to the 2019 NFL season, the Bears limited the Packers to only 10 points while picking up five sacks to start the season off on the right foot for those who invested in this premium D/ST unit. This week, the Bears take on a Denver team that stumbled to a loss in a primetime matchup with the divisional-rival Raiders. This is another great spot to start what is arguably the top D/ST in fantasy fotoball.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Bears have an elite defensive unit, but that hasn't translated to fantasy success quite yet in 2019. The seven sacks are nice, but with only one turnover forced, they're not making the splash plays we want to see from a high-end D/ST. Washington might not have an offense loaded with stars, but they've been protecting the quarterback and taking care of the ball through two weeks, so we could be in for another lackluster performance from the Bears D/ST. That said, they're still a must-start as one of the most talent-laden defenses in football.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bears entered the 2018 season with arguably the league's best defense on paper, and boy, did they deliver. Fantasy's top-scoring D/ST (55 points more than second place) paced the NFL in interceptions (27), D/ST touchdowns (six), passes defensed (92) and points allowed (283). They ranked third in sacks with 50. Chicago lost Adrian Amos and Bryce Callahan in free agency but remains stocked with star talent on every level, led by the likes of Akiem Hicks, Khalil Mack, Kyle Fuller, Danny Trevathan and Eddie Jackson. The addition of star returner Cordarrelle Patterson (league-high four kick return touchdowns since 2014) adds to the appeal. This elite unit should be the first off the board in 2019 fantasy drafts.

After finishing seventh at the position in fantasy points in 2017, Butker improved to fifth in his second season. Butker attempted 15 fewer field goals last season, but his 69 extra-point attempts were 16 more than the next-closest kicker. His 89.9 percent field goal conversion rate is seventh best in the league during his two seasons in the league. He's missed only one of 41 attempts under 40 yards. The 24-year-old is one of the league's best young kickers and a strong fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Waller has a cool story of redemption and recovery and should serve as the team's top receiving threat from the tight end position. It's not year clear if Waller can mimic or even approach the usage and production Jared Cook posted last year with Oakland, but this is at least an encouraging opening matchup -- Denver allowed the seventh-most yards to tight ends in 2018 -- for those considering streaming Waller.
outlooksByWeek.2: Waller impressively played on all of Oakland's 55 offensive snaps in Week 1 and earned a robust 31% target share. For some context, Waller had seven catches on Monday against Denver and had six catches all of last season. The Chiefs have allowed 1,098 yards to tight ends since the start of last season, sixth most in the league and a strong indicator Waller could thrive as a top target fo Derek Carr this Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.3: Another solid showing for this former college wideout in Week 2 included catching all but one of his seven targets while tallying a team-high 54 yards after the catch in the loss to the Chiefs. The Vikings have ceded the seventh-fewest yards to tight ends dating back to Week 1 of last year, but Waller's stellar usage pattern thus far supports TE1 expectations yet again.
outlooksByWeek.4: From college wideout to standout NFL tight end, Waller is somehow on pace for over 130 receptions. The reception pace will surely slow, but Waller is officially now a TE1 for fantasy purposes, especially as the Colts have allowed the eighth-most catches to the position on the year.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's unclear just how rushing work—especially at the goal line—will be divvied between Hyde and Duke Johnson, but it's safe to assume Hyde won't see much passing work in this one. The Saints allowed the fewest rushing yards to tailbacks last season, more evidence Hyde should ride the fantasy pine.
outlooksByWeek.2: On the field for 37% of Houston's offensive snaps in the opener, Hyde spent just seven of those plays as a receiving threat. The Jaguars have allowed the ninth-fewest yards per carry to tailbacks since the start of last season, adding another reason to fade Hyde.
outlooksByWeek.3: Tons of work on the ground fostered some fantasy value for the Texans' Hyde in a Week 2, when he had 20 carries for 90 yards, his most in a game since Week 3 last season with the Browns. The Chargers have been solid against the run since the start of last season (allowing 91.2 rushing yards to backfields during that span), leaving Hyde outside of the flex tier this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Held to just 1.9 yards per carry and without any targets, Hyde's fantasy stock plummeted after Week 3. The Panthers are allowing 4.4 yards per carry to opposing backs, but starting Hyde is a bet that he both capitalizes on the matchup and nets a good deal of touches.

player.seasonOutlook: Hyde is now with Houston after a disappointing 2018 campaign in which he managed only 571 yards on 172 carries (3.3 YPC) and 33 yards on 10 catches (2.1 YPT) in 14 games with Cleveland and Jacksonville. Although the 27-year-old's efficiency has dipped after an explosive start to his career, Hyde has often ranked near the top of the league in stacked boxes (76th percentile or higher in average box defenders in four of his five seasons) and quietly posted a solid 1.9 YAC last season. Hyde has a path to consistent carries with only Duke Johnson Jr. in his way in Houston and, though he isn't an effective receiver, flex value is within range if he locks down 13-to-15 carries per game. He's worth a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: McLaurin looks like the favorite to occupy a starting spot on the outside after Josh Doctson's release. The rookie is an intriguing bench player, but should stay there for Week 1 against the Eagles.
outlooksByWeek.2: McLaurin averaged a ridiculous 17.9 yards-per-target in Week 1, catching five balls for 125 yards and his first NFL touchdown. The rookie out of Ohio State has shot into an immediate path for frequent work on a club thirsty for wideout consistency, and his role as a deep-play asset makes him a weekly "all or nothing" dart throw in many fantasy leagues. Rank him as a WR3/flex against the Cowboys in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: McLaurin followed up his electric NFL debut by scoring for the second straight game in Week 2. A tough Bears matchup awaits in Week 3, which likely lowers his ceiling. Still, the big-play rookie adds a much-needed dimension to Washington's offense, and his prowess with the deep ball has the upside to pay off -- even in tough draws. That gives him some WR3 appeal this weekend, but more safely pegs him as a flex starter.
outlooksByWeek.4: McLaurin has been one of fantasy's best rookies so far in 2019. In each of his first three outings, he's scored once, seen seven-plus targets and caught at least five passes. He'll square off with Giants CB Janoris Jenkins in Week 4, but the aging defensive back has been burned a bit more than usual this season. The Giants, in fact, have allowed the second-most WR fantasy points-per-game this year. McLaurin is a strong fantasy WR3, with his downfield prowess keeping his ceiling high, even if Washington switches quarterbacks from Case Keenum to rookie Dwayne Haskins.

player.seasonOutlook: The Redskins drafted McLaurin in the third round of April's draft, adding the Ohio State product to a wide receiver room that also includes Paul Richardson, Kelvin Harmon and Trey Quinn. McLaurin is an older prospect (he turned 23 in April) with an average frame (6-foot, 208 pounds) who is extremely fast (4.35 40-yard dash). An efficient receiver, the former Buckeye averaged 14.3 yards per target last season, which topped this class. McLaurin could settle in as a depth receiver and special-teams standout, but he has a terrific opportunity for a major rookie-season role because of Washington's shaky depth chart. That puts him on the late-round radar in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: On pace to return from a preseason concussion, Chark will compete with several other veteran wideouts for targets to begin the year. It's best to let Chark prove himself first, despite a matchup against Kansas City's porous pass defense, given it's uncertain how Jaguars' receivers other than Dede Westbrook will contribute.
outlooksByWeek.2: Chark's 146 receiving yards set the Jaguars' franchise record for most in a season-opener (set by Jimmy Smith in 1999). With an average depth of target just above 24 yards, Chark was a high-volume deep threat in a game the Jaguars were scrambling to come back in against the Chiefs. The Texans have been exploitable for wideouts since the start of last season, although it's not clear which Jacksonville receiver to trust in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Leading the Jaguars in receiving yardage through two games, Chark has found fun chemistry with quarterback Gardner Minshew.
outlooksByWeek.4: The team's leading receiver the past two weeks thanks to netting 14 targets with healthy air yardage during this sample, Chark is arguably the strongest fantasy option on the Jaguars' passing game at the moment. With a growing rapport developing with Gardner Minshew, Chark is in the flex discussion in deep leagues facing a somewhat reeling Denver defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Chark was selected by Jacksonville in the second round of the 2018 draft. He was limited to 178 routes in 11 games, which allowed for a 14/174/0 receiving line. He failed to find the end zone despite three end zone targets and caught only 42 percent of his 33 targets. It obviously wasn't a great start to Chark's career, but also nothing to overreact to. The team's quarterback situation has gone from terrible to Nick Foles, and Chark is still only 22 years old. The speedy and super-athletic Chark is a solid deep sleeper.

outlooksByWeek.1: Due just a handful of routes in a complementary role, you can surely source stronger options than Robinson from your waiver wire.
outlooksByWeek.2: Fourth on the team in routes even in a game with Tyreek Hill absent, it's quite possible Robinson doesn't net much of a boost in usage or production with Hill sidelined. The Raiders present a fun matchup, but it's unlikely Robinson sees enough looks to earn the confidence of fantasy managers.
outlooksByWeek.3: Before delivering two scores in a breakout performance this past week, Robinson had four career touchdowns to his name. Robinson has now run more routes than Mecole Hardman on the season and is in stronger position to deliver flex-worthy production at home this Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.4: It's amazing to think Robinson has been targeted just 10 times the past two weeks and yet has converted them into nine catches for three scores and 215 yards. Pretty efficient of you, Demarcus. The Lions have yielded the 10th-most yards to wideouts on the season, thus Robinson's efficient ways could continue for yet another week.

outlooksByWeek.1: Winston has been learning Bruce Arians' offense this offseason. Mastering it quickly could give him huge fantasy upside, especially with a full season of TE O.J Howard in the fold. Though the 49ers defense has improved on paper, it's still a unit that allowed the most passing touchdowns last year (35). Winston will typically rank on the fence for QB1 value but, with a quick study in this scheme, could earn a more secure place there. Mark him in that tier for Week 1, though, considering the favorable matchup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Winston threw three interceptions in his first regular-season action in Bruce Arians' offense. While he could emerge as a more exciting fantasy option as he gains understanding of the system, while undergoing the transition, he will be quite the risky play. Against Carolina in Week 2 on Thursday night, he's best left as a second starting quarterback in 2-QB or superflex leagues. Otherwise, leave him on the bench until he shows he's worth anything more.
outlooksByWeek.3: Winston has struggled with the Buccaneers' new offense, failing to surpass 208 passing yards in either of his two contests to start 2019. Of course, a prime opportunity is lined up for Week 3 improvement versus the Giants defense, which has allowed the third-highest QB fantasy points-per-game rate (31.1) and passing yardage total (658) so far. At home, Winston again lines up as a borderline QB1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Winston unleashed against the Giants, chiefly via the hands and legs of big-play wideout Mike Evans, with whom he connected for three touchdowns. He averaged a whopping 10.3 yards-per-attempt on Sunday, improving on his 8.3 from Week 2. It seems that he's slowly getting more comfortable challenging downfield in Bruce Arians' system. However, the Rams have stifled QB production so far, giving up just 14 fantasy points-per-game (third-lowest rate). This puts Winston close to the border of being a QB1 for Week 4 fantasy lineups, though more comfortably into QB2 territory.

player.seasonOutlook: Winston's 2018 season was marred by a three-game suspension and an interception-fueled benching, but he still ended up showing improvement in several areas. Winston completed 65 percent of his passes and was off target on 16 percent of his attempts, both of which were career-best marks. Winston also rushed for a career-high 281 yards despite appearing in just 11 games. During the nine weeks he started, Winston ranked fourth in fantasy points. He continues to struggle with interceptions (58 in 56 career games), though part of that is a product of a propensity for attacking deep down field (he's ranked top five in aDOT in all four seasons). Winston has flashed enough to keep him in the QB1 discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite starring at times in the preseason, Jones will start the 2019 season behind starting QB Eli Manning. It's difficult to justify using a roster spot on him in single-season leagues just yet, but dynasty players should consider stashing him if roster size allows it.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jones made his debut in Week 1 garbage time but lost a fumble. He'll continue backing up Eli Manning and remains more of a dynasty-league fantasy prospect than a roster-worthy player in single-year leagues.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Giants announced on Tuesday that Jones will take over as starting quarterback, supplanting Eli Manning. His first assignment in Week 3 looks promising against the Buccaneers, who have been somewhat fortunate to face Jimmy Garoppolo and an injured Cam Newton. Not that Jones is spectacular, and the Giants receiving corps is ravaged with injuries and a suspended Golden Tate, but anyone with Saquon Barkley and Evan Engram as receiving options has a fine starting point. If either Sterling Shepard or Cody Latimer returns from a concussion, Jones is squarely in consideration for a starting spot in 2-QB fantasy leagues.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Daniel Jones era started off with a fury as the rookie accounted for four total touchdowns (two rushing) against the Buccaneers in Week 3. That defense was a pushover, but Washington's has also been easy to conquer. The Redskins have allowed 28.1 QB fantasy points-per-game -- the fifth-highest average in the league. Though expecting a repeat of his debut is a stretch, he should still border on fantasy QB1 numbers in Week 4. Those deploying him as a QB2 in 2-QB lineups should be giddy.

player.seasonOutlook: The Giants selected Jones with the sixth overall pick in April's draft. The 6-foot-5, 221-pound Duke product was far from impressive in his final FBS season. Jones was off target on 9.4 percent of his throws (best in this class), but he was very conservative (8.1 aDOT), which led to a weak 6.8 YPA. Jones did deal with a ton of drops, but his weak efficiency and struggles throwing the deep ball are red flags. Jones is a good athlete who will add some value at the pro level with his legs. Eli Manning will be the team's starter as long as he's healthy and the Giants are competitive this season, but Jones figures to get a few starts late in the season. He's only a fantasy option in dynasty.

outlooksByWeek.1: The volume was certainly there for  Johnson last season, but the efficiency was not. That said, his 308 total touches propelled him to an eighth-place finish among running backs in total scoring. He'll be the focal point of Arizona's offense again this season alongside new quarterback Kyler Murray, and should be started until further notice.
outlooksByWeek.2: Johnson was involved in all facets of the Arizona offense to open the season, showing good rapport with rookie Kyler Murray and catching 6-of-7 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown. He's on pace for well over 300 touches -- a number only an injury will stop him from reaching. The Ravens do not offer an appealing matchup, nor does a trip across the country inspire much confidence, but Johnson is still squarely among the RB1 ranks. He deserves a spot in any fantasy lineup.
outlooksByWeek.3: After a Week 2 injury scare forced Johnson out of the game for a series and limited his overall playing time (only 36 snaps), things appear to be fine for the superstar running back. The Cardinals have been keeping games close so far this season and should be able to provide Johnson with his normal workload this week -- assuming his wrist cooperates. Keep an eye on his injury status, as the only way you'll bench him against a mediocre Panthers defense is if he's ruled out.
outlooksByWeek.4: Johnson bounced back in Week 3, finding the end zone and posting a respectable score on the back of his prowess in the passing game. Johnson has 17 targets on the season and is clearly a key figure in the passing game, which is something that can also be said for Alvin Kamara of the Saints. Kamara had a huge game through the air in Week 3 against Seattle, who will travel to Arizona to face the Cardinals in Week 4. That's the silver lining on what promises to be a tough matchup for the star running back, but it's enough to say he's an RB1 in all formats.

player.seasonOutlook: Johnson's career has hit a snag since he dominated the fantasy scene in 2016, pacing all backs in snaps, touches, yardage, touchdowns and fantasy points. An injury cost him all but 43 snaps in 2017, and inefficient play in a weak offense limited him to only two top-10 fantasy weeks (24 backs had more) in 2018. Johnson's yards per carry plummeted to 3.64, his YAC to 1.44 (seventh-worst among running backs) and his catch rate to 66 percent (second-worst). On the plus side, Johnson ranked top-five at the position in snaps (714) and touches (308), which allowed him his third top-10 fantasy campaign in four seasons. The 27-year-old workhorse is expected to retain a hefty role in new coach Kliff Kingsbury's offense. An intriguing bounce-back candidate, Johnson is a mid-pack RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Set with a big new deal and a large role as the key playmaker for a Jets team in dire need of creation, Bell should see a sizable workload against a stout Bills defense that allowed the 11th-fewest yards per carry last season. Even with a tough matchup the hope is that a heavy workload helps Bell match or best his projection this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Yardage was hard to come by against Buffalo this past Sunday afternoon, but touches weren't for Bell, as he led the team with 23. Most valuably, Bell netted nine targets in the loss. Supporting a strong projection for this week against the Browns is the fact Cleveland has allowed 4.75 yards per carry to tailbacks over 365 carries dating back to Week 1 last season, the eighth-highest allowance in the league during this sample.
outlooksByWeek.3: Back to seeing the amazing workload he enjoyed with the Steelers, Bell is again a top-five fantasy back thanks to his rare blend of volume and skills. The Patriots could knock the Jets out of this game early, but this could see Bell earn a glut of targets in similar fashion to Week 2's 10-catch outing.

player.seasonOutlook: Bell has signed on with the Jets after infamously sitting out the entire 2018 season due to a contract dispute. A longtime NFL workhorse, Bell ranked first among running backs in snaps (3,449), fourth in carries (1,229), third in rushing yards (5,336), fourth in rushing touchdowns (35), first in targets (390) and first in receiving yards (312) from 2013-17 despite missing 18 of 80 possible games. Bell, who has appeared in all 16 regular-season games once in his career, saw his efficiency take a dip in 2017, but pacing the position in rushes and receptions was enough to help him post his third top-three-overall fantasy season in four years. Jets coach Adam Gase's tendency to pass near the goal line (NFL-low 23 carries inside the 5 during his three seasons in Miami) could cost Bell some touchdowns, but the former Steeler won't have trouble generating big volume in an improving offense. He's a solid RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: As of Monday, Cooper (foot/heel) looked like he should be on a normal practice course on the way to suiting up in Week 1. Watch to see if that changes but, if he's on the field, he's the best bet to be Dak Prescott's top receiver. He's probably going to have to deal with Giants CB Janoris Jenkins, who helped hold Cooper to a five-catch, 31-yard day in a Week 16 meeting last season. Cooper's health concerns and Dallas' possible need not to do much through the air in this one should force fantasy managers to consider him as a fantasy WR2 for the opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: Cooper was targeted nine times in Week 1, catching six balls for 106 yards and a score. That should calm concerns over his preseason lower-body injury. Kellen Moore's offense looks exciting enough to possibly elevate Dak Prescott to a must-start fantasy quarterback, and Cooper's comfort with the starter keeps him in fantasy WR1 territory, too. Even with solid CB Josh Norman potentially shadowing him, it's hard to ding his Week 2 value too much. In Week 10 last year, Cooper obliterated Washington for a ridiculous 8-180-2 day on nine targets.
outlooksByWeek.3: In Week 2, Cooper found the end zone for the second straight week to begin the 2019 season. So far, QB Dak Prescott looks like an MVP in Kellen Moore's new system. Though the Dolphins defense that awaits in Week 3 has been obliterated for two straight games, CB Xavien Howard remains solid-to-great, and he'll probably stick on Cooper most of the day. That being said, Howard has almost no help, so Cooper still could be in position to deliver WR2 fantasy numbers. The floor isn't all that low unless he's removed early thanks to a blowout. Unless your receiver corps is stacked, don't consider benching him.
outlooksByWeek.4: Cooper scored two touchdowns in a Week 3 blowout win, showing little trouble working against Dolphins CB Xavien Howard. Next up, he will tangle with Saints CB Marshon Lattimore, who gets a lot of takeaways but has wilted against top wideouts in recent memory. Cooper remains a strong fantasy WR2 and could even pass as a WR1 for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Cooper kicked off his career with a pair of 1,000-yard and top 25 fantasy seasons in Oakland, but it took a trade to Dallas last season for him to really take off. Cooper, who handled 21 percent target share in Oakland, had a career-high 25 percent share in 11 games with Dallas. In fact, he never fell below a 16 percent share in a single game and was fantasy's No. 9 wide receiver from Week 9 on. Cooper's boost in volume coincided with improved efficiency (he caught a career-high 71 percent of his targets and averaged a career-best 9.5 YPT), which is enough to make the 25-year-old a strong WR2 with top-10 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Lockett has emerged as the unquestioned top option in the passing game for Seattle now that Doug Baldwin is no longer on the roster. The Kansas State product had already passed the veteran Baldwin in terms of fantasy appeal thanks to his eye-catching 16.9 yards-per-reception and 10 touchdowns in 2018. The Bengals are a middle-of-the-road matchup for receivers based on last season's performances, meaning there's no need to worry about Lockett if he's your WR2 in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Lockett picked up a touchdown on his only catch of the game in Week 1 -- a fitting reminder of the sort of player he is as he begins his fifth season as a pro. Last year, he scored a touchdown for every seven targets he saw, so scoring on limited chances seems to be a skill for Lockett. Still, you can expect more than two targets in Week 2 against a Steelers defense that struggled against the Patriots in Week 1. As such, he's a borderline WR2, with lots of big-play upside.
outlooksByWeek.3: Despite possessing game-changing athleticism, Lockett has almost half the yards-per-catch of teammate DK Metcalf. That's not what fantasy managers want to see, but that could all change in Week 3. The Saints have allowed 443 yards on 24 catches by wideouts so far this season, including five grabs for 120 yards by Cooper Kupp in Week 2. That bodes well for Lockett, who is certainly capable of breaking off a big play and making a big impact on your fantasy matchup. He's a solid flex option.
outlooksByWeek.4: Lockett had a huge game in Week 3 and will look to build upon that against the Cardinals in Week 4. The Kansas State product saw double-digit targets for the second week in a row and found the end zone for the second time this season. He'll be a favorite to repeat against an Arizona defense which has allowed the fourth-most points per game in the NFL this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Lockett defied logic last season by posting an absurd 57/965/10 line on only 68 targets. Lockett had posted between 64 and 69 targets during each of his first three NFL seasons but never cleared 51 receptions, 664 yards or six touchdowns. Lockett, who hasn't dropped a pass since 2016, caught 84 percent of his targets (second best), posted a 14.2 YPT (best) and scored on 14.7 percent of his targets (second best). Lockett was fantasy's No. 16 receiver (his first career top 40) despite managing only one weekly finish better than 14th. Needless to say, Lockett's efficiency isn't close to sustainable and that includes touchdowns (he scored 10 times despite a 3.0 OTD and seven end zone targets). Lockett is a very good player but he needs more volume to be more than a WR3/flex option. He figures to get it following Doug Baldwin's retirement.

outlooksByWeek.1: Considered by many to be a Steve Smith clone, Moore looks primed to be the Panthers' No. 1 wideout this season, though Christian McCaffrey, Greg Olsen and Curtis Samuel will all eat into his ceiling. Cam Newton's health (foot) could compromise his ability in Week 1, but assuming he's set to go, Moore should slot in as a WR2/WR3 for Week 1 against the Rams. Carolina likely will have to sling the ball around to keep pace in the second half.
outlooksByWeek.2: Moore led the way among Panthers receiving options in Week 1, catching 7-of-10 targets. Still, he took a back seat to Christian McCaffrey (206 scrimmage yards, 2 TDs). Moore could be even busier in Week 2 against the Buccaneers if TE Greg Olsen (back) has to miss the contest. Count Moore as a solid fantasy WR2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Moore enjoyed a 14-target, 9-catch Week 2 but stands to be the player most negatively impacted if QB Cam Newton (foot) has to miss Week 3 at Arizona. If Kyle Allen or Will Grier takes snaps, Moore's ceiling takes a major dent. Fantasy managers can hope that his talent wins out. Expect him to put up fantasy WR3 numbers, especially with Cardinals CB Patrick Peterson's suspension removing a centerpiece of the defense.
outlooksByWeek.4: Moore slipped down to just two targets as Kyle Allen took over for QB Cam Newton (foot) in Week 3, but he made his one catch count -- a 52-yard catch-and-run for a touchdown. Allen's presence in Week 4 shouldn't scare off Moore's shareholders from starting him, etiher. Houston has allowed the fifth-highest WR fantasy points-per-game. Count Moore as a solid fantasy WR3, with top-end upside if Allen looks his way more often.

player.seasonOutlook: Moore was the first wide receiver selected in the 2018 draft and it didn't take long for the Maryland product to take on a large offensive role. Moore first played more than half of Carolina's offensive snaps in Week 8 and was fantasy's No. 20 wideout from that point forward. He ended up 31st at the position in receiving yards (788) despite ranking 53rd in pass routes (406) thanks to a league-best average of 7.7 yards after catch. He was limited to two touchdowns (2.2 OTD), but offset that a bit with 172 rushing yards. The versatile 22-year-old is now Carolina's clear No. 1 wide receiver and well positioned for a second-year breakout. He's a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: A potential breakout candidate with stellar red zone metrics over his career, Henry is in a great spot to deliver value given the Colts, this week's opponent, allowed the most yards (1,194) to tight ends last year. After a lost 2018, there is potential for a memorable start to the 2019 season for Henry.
outlooksByWeek.2: Only Keenan Allen ran more routes than Henry in Week 1, suggesting his role could grow in the weeks ahead. The Lions have been strong against tight ends since the start of last season in allowing the seventh-fewest yards to the position during this sample, but Henry's blend of talent and usage at a shallow position keeps him firmly in the starting range of the position.

player.seasonOutlook: Henry is entering his fourth NFL season but has yet to manage a top-12 fantasy campaign. The culprit, of course, has been injuries. Henry missed three games during his first two seasons while also being limited by the presence of Antonio Gates. The 2016 second-round pick was on the verge of a 2018 promotion and likely breakout, but a torn ACL cost him the entire regular season (he did return and play 13 snaps in the playoffs). Henry has posted a career 81-1,057-12 line with 20 end-zone targets in 29 games. His efficiency has been terrific (70 percent catch rate, 9.3 YPT), and he's still only 24 years old. Now healthy and finally positioned for a full-time role in a good Chargers offense, Henry has breakout written all over him. He's a fringe top-five fantasy tight end.

outlooksByWeek.1: Breida earned his shot as the top back in the 49ers offense in 2018 after serving as the backup to Carlos Hyde in 2017 as a rookie. He didn't have anything resembling a breakout campaign, however, so San Francisco brought in Tevin Coleman to supplement their backfield depth chart. That relegates the former undrafted free-agent to a timeshare, but one where he's certain to see at least some of the work early on as Kyle Shanahan scouts out his best offensive options. As such, he's a flex option against a weak Buccaneers squad in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Breida played on only 30 snaps in Week 1 and, while he earned 15 carries while on the field, he's obviously a part of a timeshare with Raheem Mostert. Tevin Coleman also figured to play a role, but he'll be sidelined with an ankle injury for a few weeks, which clears up the situation a bit. The Bengals offer a great matchup for running backs, having allowed the most RB fantasy points last season and ceding a pair of touchdowns to Chris Carson in Week 1. All signs point to RB2 status for Breida, but don't be too surprised if he shares time and production with Mostert and Jeff Wilson Jr.
outlooksByWeek.3: Breida is in a three-way timeshare at running back with Raheem Mostert and Jeff Wilson Jr., but he leads the team in both carries and yards on the ground this season with an impressive 5.9 yards-per-attempt. There are obvious red flags here, with Mostert playing more snaps than Breida in Week 2 and Wilson scoring a pair of touchdowns, so don't bank on Week 2's production all the time, especially in tougher matchups. Week 3 will see the 49ers host the Steelers without Ben Roethlisberger, which could mean opportunities for Breida to run with a favorable game script, but even then he's best viewed as a flex play.

player.seasonOutlook: Breida went undrafted in 2017 but received significant hype leading into his rookie season. He has lived up to it, averaging 5.0 YPC on 258 career carries, including 5.3 YPC in 2018 (seventh-best). Breida stepped up his game as a receiver in 2018, catching 84 percent of his targets (fifth-best) and averaging 8.2 yards per target (third-best) on 32 targets. Breida is on the small side at 5-foot-11, 190 pounds, which has led to a limited role near the goal line (five rushing touchdowns and seven carries inside the 5 in his career). If there's a red flag here, it's Breida's poor post-contact production (career 1.62 YAC). Breida has been effective, but he'll need to share the 49er's backfield with Tevin Coleman in 2019. That leaves the 24-year-old as more of a fringe flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Goff has an embarrassment of riches in terms of talent around him on offense, and he's taken advantage of that by delivering a few notable fantasy performances over the past two seasons. However, he lacks the upside of the superstar fantasy quarterbacks and falls squarely in the middle of the second tier, alongside names like Dak Prescott, Matt Ryan and Kirk Cousins. The Panthers allowed the fifth-most passing touchdowns (32) a year ago, making Goff a fringe QB1 pick for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Goff averaged only 4.8 yards-per-attempt in Week 1, the second-lowest rate in the league ahead of only New York's Sam Darnold. That is not what we expect from Goff, who had healthy YPA rates of 8.0 and 8.4 in 2017 and 2018.  Likely to have to pass early and often against a good Saints team, Goff is a borderline starting quarterback in fantasy for Week 2, but consider other options if you have them.
outlooksByWeek.3: Goff and the Rams have won both of their games, but the 24-year-old's fantasy numbers aren't all that impressive. Week 2's win over New Orleans proved how willing Los Angeles is to control the game in order to see out a victory, as the Rams won easily while Goff attempted only 28 passes. It's hard to judge Cleveland's pass defense based on Week 2, when they faced Jets third-stringer Luke Falk, but in Week 1 they ceded 248 yards and three touchdowns to Marcus Mariota. This looks like a good matchup, but Goff isn't guaranteed to have a good game. He's a streaming option if he's available as a pickup in your league, but he's not a set-and-forget starter.
outlooksByWeek.4: Goff remains just outside the top tier of fantasy quarterbacks, showing promise at times and failing to deliver at others. He's at the helm of one of the best offenses in football, but that doesn't translate into "video game numbers" like it does for Patrick Mahomes or Tom Brady. That said, he'll face a Buccaneers defense in Week 4 that's coming off of a poor performance against rookie Daniel Jones, who scored four times in a comeback victory. That makes Goff a premier streaming option if he's on waivers, and a name to consider as a borderline QB1 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Goff has flourished during his two seasons with Sean McVay at the helm. The Rams have finished top five in offensive touchdowns and Goff has finished top five in both yards per completion and yards per attempt each of those seasons. Goff was fantasy's No. 12 scoring QB in 2017 and improved to No. 7 in 2018. Goff adds little with his legs as he has only tallied 175 rushing yards in 38 career games. His accuracy remains a question, too, finishing no better than in the 63rd percentile in off-target rate each of his three seasons. However, terrific hands (2.1 percent drop rate) and post-catch production (6.2 RAC) from his receivers have led to excellent passing numbers. Goff is a fringe QB1.

Gostkowski has finished as a top-three kicker six of the past eight seasons, but his two worst finishes in that span (eighth in 2016 and ninth in 2018) have come in the past three seasons. His 50 extra-point attempts last season were fourth most in the league. His efficiency was lacking last season, as he missed five of 32 field goal attempts, despite an average distance of 36.2 yards (second lowest). Gostkowski is now 35 years old, but just signed a contract extension to remain the kicker for one of the league's top offenses. He's a solid starting option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hockenson proved himself worthy of a top-10 NFL Draft selection this April, with the Lions looking to add an impact player to the position after failing to see any of their tight ends catch more than 21 passes a year ago. He's joined by former Steeler Jesse James on the TE depth chart, but Hockenson is the one to watch. The Cardinals are fairly stingy when it comes to allowing production to opposing passing games, and particularly so against tight ends, so don't expect much from Hockenson in his debut. Keep him on the bench for now.
outlooksByWeek.2: Hockenson had an incredible NFL debut, hauling in six passes for 131 yards and his first professional touchdown. The Iowa product definitely has the trust and attention of QB Matthew Stafford and should have the attention of fantasy managers, as well. Rookie tight ends are usually overrated in fantasy as they rarely produce at a level befitting their draft hype, but there's already hard evidence that Hockenson might break the mold. Consider him a borderline TE1 for what should be a competitive matchup with a Chargers defense that allowed the Colts to score twice via the air in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Hockenson wasted no time in establishing himself as a fantasy option at tight end, racking up 131 yards and a score in Week 1. Things came crashing down to earth in Week 2, however, with only three targets thrown his way against the Chargers. His playing time didn't decrease, however, so there's no need to panic. If you bought in after Week 1, there's no reason to ditch him after Week 2. The Eagles allowed Vernon Davis into the end zone in Week 1 and have given up six passing touchdowns so far in 2019. Consider Hockenson to be on the fringe of the TE1 ranks in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: While Hockenson hasn't yet repeated his huge numbers from Week 1, there are still positives to take away from his play since then. The rookie ranks No. 4 among Lions pass-catchers in both targets and yards, putting him clearly in the picture for production when the Lions take to the air. He's also playing on plenty of snaps, sharing time with Jesse James in 2-TE sets but sitting out only about 25% of the time. So while we can't expect huge performances every week, he's certainly a viable fantasy option. He's worthy of a spot in your lineup in what should be a high-scoring matchup with Kansas City in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Detroit selected Hockenson eighth overall in April's draft. The Iowa product joins free-agent signing Jesse James atop the Lions' depth chart. Hockenson is a terrific pass catcher and good blocker who has drawn comparisons to Travis Kelce, Rob Gronkowski and even former Hawkeye George Kittle. Hockenson is a superb athlete, with good size (6-foot-5, 251 pounds) and toughness. He crushed it at the combine, placing near the top of the position in all but the bench press. Hockenson has every-down tight end written all over him, but, as is usual for rookie tight ends, he figures to learn the ropes in 2019 before emerging as a fantasy threat in 2020. Hockenson doesn't need to be on your radar in 10-team leagues in 2019.

outlooksByWeek.1: Our projections deem Brown a fringe fantasy option for his debut with the Bills. The upside? The Jets allowed the most yards to receivers among AFC teams last year, and Josh Allen has a big arm and a penchant for taking risks. Brown is a vertical threat, but it's wise to let him first earn a starting fantasy role.
outlooksByWeek.2: An awesome Week 1 saw Brown lead the Bills in targets, air yards, yards and receptions. Brown also scored a touchdown and should be considered a strong flex candidate against a Giants defense that has allowed the fifth-most receiving yards to wideouts since the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.3: Brown is 12th in the league with a 28.6% target share of Buffalo's passing offense, aligned with the usage rates we find for Odell Beckham and T.Y. Hilton this season. With plenty of opportunities to produce, and many of them valuable downfield chances, Brown is a solid flex option facing a Bengals pass defense that has allowed the 10th-most yards to wideouts dating to the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.4: With his average target traveling 13 air yards, it's not surprising to see Brown netting 13.7 yards per reception this season. Brown, who is tied for the team lead in targets with Cole Beasley, gets a big share of Buffalo's high-leverage vertical work. He's still in the flex discussion against a stingy New England secondary for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown signed with the Bills after spending the first five seasons of his career in Arizona and Baltimore. Brown's best season saw him post a 65/1,003/7 line in 2015. He was fantasy's No. 25-scoring receiver that season, but he has been unable to come close to that production since. A sickle trait issue cost Brown game action during his stint in Arizona, but with that behind him, the 29-year-old didn't miss a single game en route to a 42/717/5 line last season. Brown's 14.9 average depth of target is highest in the NFL among 41 players with 400-plus targets since he entered the league. Brown figures to be an extremely boom/bust producer as a situational deep threat for strong-armed but inaccurate Josh Allen. He's only worth a late flier, especially in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Olsen didn't show up at Monday practice but, barring a wild turn of events, looks like he'll be ready for Week 1 against the Rams. He played in just nine games in 2018 after suiting up for just seven the year before, but he's been a bit ignored this fantasy draft season. Carolina will probably have to utilize him frequently against the Rams, giving him a decent shot at TE1 fantasy production in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Olsen caught four passes in Week 1 but ended up with a back injury. The short turn-around before a Thursday night game jeopardizes his availability for Week 2 against the Buccaneers, in which case Ian Thomas would receive a bump in offensive attention. If you need a logical handcuff for the week, feel free to pick up Thomas.
outlooksByWeek.3: Olsen convinced us he was over his back issue by showing up strong in Week 2. He may remain busy in Week 3 against the Cardinals, who are without suspended CB Patrick Peterson, but that's because Carolina has its own major problem -- QB Cam Newton (foot) is uncertain to play. Kyle Allen or Will Grier may fill in and probably would lean on Olsen in that case, giving the veteran tight end a strong case to start in many fantasy TE slots Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.4: Olsen tore apart Arizona's Patrick Peterson-less defense with a 6-75-2 line in Week 3. He's an optimal pickup for any fantasy manager needing a bye-week replacement. The switch from Cam Newton (foot) to Kyle Allen hasn't tripped him up, eithe. He's had seven-plus targets in every game this year and looks to be at the healthiest we've seen him in recent years. Houston has allowed just 90 receiving yards to tight ends this year but hasn't faced one as heavily involved as Olsen. He's a safe fantasy starter as long as Allen is under center.

player.seasonOutlook: Injuries have derailed Olsen's past two seasons, limiting the veteran tight end to 44 catches for 482 yards and five touchdowns in 16 games during that span. Olsen played a majority of the snaps in seven games last season and was fantasy's No. 8 scoring tight end. Olsen's slump came after he ranked no lower than second at the position in snaps in five consecutive seasons, finishing each as a top-seven fantasy tight end. Olsen is expected back for Week 1 and should be no lower than third on the team in targets behind Christian McCaffrey and DJ Moore. Olsen is no spring chicken at 34 years old, but he's an obvious rebound candidate and can be had at a major discount late in drafts. He's worth a flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: An impressive preseason doesn’t necessarily mean Washington will see the field much to begin the regular campaign. Behind Donte Moncrief for meaningful snaps on the outside, Washington is for now a promising bench stash for this meeting with the Patriots.
outlooksByWeek.2: Serving a specialist role as a vertical threat for the Steelers in Week 1, Washington netted a team-high 27.5 air yards per target, albeit on just two looks. Without a sizable role just yet, Washington remains a sleeper stash ideal for deeper leagues.
outlooksByWeek.3: Washington enjoyed a strong rapport with Mason Rudolph in the preseason that could eventually convert into regular season production. While Washington could be a rising option in the passing game, he's not above Donte Moncrief yet on the depth chart and thus isn't worth starting in lineups against a 49ers defense that has been generous to wideouts thus far.
outlooksByWeek.4: We didn't see the awesome preseason rapport Washington had with Mason Rudolph surface in San Francisco, but there is at least some long-term upside to this pairing. The Bengals have allowed nearly 15 yards per catch to wideouts, but we'll want to see Washington prove it on the field before rolling him out in lineups.

player.seasonOutlook: The Steelers have a lengthy resume of developing wide receivers into stars, and Washington could be next. The 2018 second-round pick underwhelmed as a rookie, but he was an explosive downfield playmaker at Oklahoma State and last preseason. With Antonio Brown gone, Washington will compete with Donte Moncrief and rookie Diontae Johnson for No. 2 duties opposite JuJu Smith-Schuster in an offense that set a franchise record for touchdowns last season. Washington, whose vertical role yielded a 16.2 aDOT on 37 targets last season, has WR2 upside if he's able to carve out an every-down role in his second season. He's a high-risk/high-reward prospect worth your attention in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cleared to play but only back with the team for the past few weeks, Gordon could play a limited role in this matchup with the Steelers, a team that struggled with big-play receivers in 2018. It's likely best to stash Gordon for now and see how his usage and production play out from the bench, but there is enough fantasy upside in this potential shootout with the Steelers to support flex value for the gifted wideout.
outlooksByWeek.2: Third on the team in routes in Week 1 and with a solid 14 air yards per target in returning to action this past Sunday, Gordon is a fine WR3 prospect heading into a choice matchup with the Dolphins' feeble back seven. There is some risk in using Gordon given the presence of target hog Antonio Brown, but there's still a lot to like about Gordon's role going forward.
outlooksByWeek.3: A quiet Week 2 saw Gordon finish second on the team in routes but a lack of efficiency left him with just two catches on the afternoon. There will be some natural variance to Gordon's role given the sheer talent and depth on this offense, but he's still in the starting flex discussion in deeper leagues given his playmaking upside against a mistake-prone Jets secondary.
outlooksByWeek.4: With Julian Edelman leaving the field in the second quarter with an injury, Gordon led the Patriots in routes and targets in Week 3. The Bills have a strong defense overall, but have allowed the third-most catches to receivers so far, setting up Gordon as a solid starting option in Orchard Park.

player.seasonOutlook: Gordon was reinstated in August and will rejoin the Patriots this season. The 28-year-old wide receiver wasn't nearly as dominant last season as he was back at his peak in 2013, but was still very effective, ranking sixth among wide receivers in ypr (18.0), 10th in ypt (10.2) and fourth in RAC (6.7). Gordon was often utilized as a vertical threat (13.8 aDOT), which limited his volume a bit; during the nine full games he played, Gordon (63) was behind both Julian Edelman (83) and James White (70) in targets. Gordon ranked 24th in fantasy points during those nine weeks. He's back in the WR3 discussion, but his off-field troubles make him a risky early-round investment.

outlooksByWeek.1: LeSean McCoy's release could see Singletary, in his professional debut, lead Buffalo’s backfield in touches. However, the presence of two veterans, Frank Gore and T.J. Yeldon, will limit Singletary's workload. He is a risky flex play against a Jets defense that allowed the 10th-fewest yards before contact per rush last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: We're guessing Singletary won't always make so much of four attempts—he netted 17.5 yards per carry in Week 1—but it was impressive to see the rookie's big-play potential realized against the Jets. He also had a big receiving role, which bodes well for his potential as a flex option in Week 2 against a Giants front seven that could struggle to cover him in space.
outlooksByWeek.3: Hopefully Singletary can overcome a hamstring ailment and suit up for Week 3's matchup with Cincinnati's soft rush defense. After all, this exciting rookie has averaged an awesome 12.7 yards per rush this season. If Singletary ever grabs a bigger share of Buffalo's backfield workload, he could emerge as a fantasy star.  For now, he's a solid flex with realistic upside given the opponent.
outlooksByWeek.4: A big-play maven averaging a ridiculous 12.7 yards per rushing attempt through two appearances, Singletary's hamstring issue and the presence of Frank Gore curb any potential enthusiasm. In addition, the Bill will face a Patriots defense allowing the fewest yards per attempt to running backs.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bills selected Singletary in the third round of April's draft. Singletary is very undersized (5-foot-7, 203 pounds) and lacks home run speed (4.66 40-yard dash), but makes up for that with toughness and elusiveness. The Florida Atlantic star ran for 22 touchdowns and ranked among the top backs in the class in broken tackle rate and evaded tackle rate in 2018. Singletary can contribute as a receiver and is a strong pass-blocker. Following the offseason release of LeSean McCoy, the rookie is positioned for a big role ahead of Frank Gore and TJ Yeldon. Take a shot on Singletary in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Steelers have led the league in sacks the past two years, which is often a strong indicator of fantasy production. The Patriots, however, allowed one of the lower pressure rates in football last season and with a lofty point total in place for this prime-time matchup, it's likely wise to avoid this group until the schedule improves.
outlooksByWeek.2: New England had their way with the Steelers' defense in week one, resulting in a negative fantasy performance for Pittsburgh. The Seahawks aren't quite the dynamic threat the Patriots pose, but they do enter town with a star quarterback and solid playmakers, revealing some risk in streaming this Steelers' D/ST in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Pittsburgh's injured and underwhelming offense has gotten the attention through two weeks, but it's worth noting the Steelers have allowed the fifth-most yards per dropback to opponents. To be fair, those two opponents were Tom Brady and Russell Wilson. This week presents the Steelers with a challenge against a 49ers offense seemingly finding its fitting. There is a correlation between being sizable road underdogs and poor fantasy production for defenses, adding some risk to Pittsburgh's profile this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Steelers produced five takeaways in Week 4, but failed to capitalize on offense. It was encouraging at least to see this defense thrive in the big-play department, especially with new import Minkah Fitzpatrick producing. The Bengals enter with some of the higher interception and sack rates per dropback in the league, setting up this Pittsburgh D/ST with solid streaming status.

player.seasonOutlook: Believe it or not, the Steelers have led the NFL in sacks the past two seasons. They generated 52 last season to go with 99 tackles for loss (eighth-most) while allowing 5.3 yards per play (sixth-best) and blocking three kicks (second-most). Pittsburgh's D/ST salvaged an eighth-place fantasy season despite ranking 29th in forced turnovers (15), its lowest total since 2011 (15). Following minimal offseason turnover, Pittsburgh remains outstanding up front with T.J. Watt, Cameron Heyward, Stephon Tuitt and Javon Hargrave leading the way. The unit is suspect beyond that, though LB Devin Bush was scooped up in the first round of the draft, and Steven Nelson is an underrated addition at corner. This is a mid-pack D/ST option in 2019, though a Week 1 trip to New England hurts the draft appeal.

outlooksByWeek.1: Peterson tore up opponents for a 1,042-yard rushing mark in 2018, his age-33 season. He'll now have to share carriers with the healthy Derrius Guice, though, in addition to Chris Thompson for pass-catching duties. Peterson deserves a fantasy roster spot, but most weeks is best used as a flex play. Consider him in that capacity against the tough Eagles defense. The holdout of LT Trent Williams could affect the Washington run game for much of the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Peterson was scratched due to a coach's decision in Week 1, but Derrius Guice is dealing with a meniscus issue in his knee and expected to miss at least one week. Peterson should be active in Week 2 and for however long Guice sits. Dallas ranked in the middle of the pack in fantasy RB defense last year (24.0 PPR points per game), which doesn't do much to force Peterson's fantasy value any lower than a flex play.
outlooksByWeek.3: Derrius Guice (knee) was placed on injured reserve before Week 2, giving Peterson the keys to between-the-tackles work at least through the Week 10 bye. He's going to split plenty of work with pass-catching back Chris Thompson, though. In fact, Thompson looks like the better play against the strong Bears defense, due to his penchant for reeling in short tosses. Peterson is a mere flex play with a low floor for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Peterson averaged just 3.1 YPC in Week 3 against a tough Bears defense while splitting work again with receiving threat Chris Thompson. The Giants await with a friendlier matchup in Week 4, though. Wendell Smallwood may eat into Peterson's already limited ceiling, unfortunately, keeping him in mere flex territory this weekend.

player.seasonOutlook: Peterson's 2018 prospects seemed dim during most of last offseason, but Derrius Guice's torn ACL allowed the former fantasy star one more shot at lead back duties. Peterson held down the fort, finishing fifth in the league with 251 carries and averaging 4.2 yards per carry. As usual, Peterson played a minimal role as a receiver (26 targets) but scored enough touchdowns (eight) to manage a 19th-place finish in fantasy points. Peterson re-signed with Washington, but with Guice healthy and ready to roll, the 2018 second-round pick will be the team's primary back. The 34-year-old Peterson will have flex value only if Guice misses time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Elliott remains away from the team while holding out for a new contract. Barring any news that'll quickly change his availability for Week 1, he's unlikely to suit up for the opener. Tony Pollard will likely lead a backfield committee in his place. If Elliott signs and somehow starts in the opener, go ahead and roll him back out as a fantasy RB1. Your likelier course of action is to leave him on your bench for Dallas' first 2019 outing against the Giants.
outlooksByWeek.2: Elliott wasted little time paying off on his new extension, rumbling into the end zone in the Cowboys' opening blowout victory. He only touched the ball 14 times, but Dallas was comfortable with resting him in an easy win during his first NFL action of the season after the long layoff. The star back should be a bit busier as he gets his footing under him for Week 2 against Washington, against whom he averaged 92.5 scrimmage yards and scored twice over two meetings last year. He remains squarely in the RB1 fantasy tier.
outlooksByWeek.3: Elliott got tons of carries in Week 2, regaining his workhorse workload after being eased into Week 1 following his holdout. Against a wilting Dolphins defense that just traded safety Minkah Fitzpatrick, Elliott shouldn't have trouble reaching the second level. Elliott remains a star fantasy RB1 for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Elliott is averaging 5.3 YPC this year, topped off by a 139-yard day from scrimmage in a Week 3 obliteration of the Dolphins. The Saints rank among the strongest fantasy defenses against running backs so far, but haven't faced a back of Elliott's quality yet. Elliott again ranks among the top fantasy RB1s heading into Week 4 thanks to his busy workload. He should get plenty of second-half yardage should New Orleans fail to move the ball without QB Drew Brees (thumb).

player.seasonOutlook: An absolute workhorse since entering the NFL in 2016, Elliott has played just under 90 percent of Dallas' snaps and handled over 80 percent of the carries when active over the past two seasons. That's led to a league-high 868 carries despite Elliott having missed eight games during that span. Elliott's game reached a new level last season as he easily reached career highs in targets (94), receptions (77) and receiving yards (567). Elliott led all backs in touches (381) and was second in scrimmage yards (2,001). His underwhelming usage near the goal line remains a concern (his 10 carries inside the 5 ranked 17th last season). Nonetheless, Elliott is a young, high-end talent set for a ton of volume. With his contract situation resolved, he should be off the board in the top 4 of every draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones rebounded in both the touchdown and receiving yardage columns in 2018. The elite wideout was a frequent first-round pick in this summer's fantasy drafts and will remain a virtual must-start. He'll likely tangle with tough Vikings CB Xavier Rhodes, who's given him troubles in the past. However, even with a lower ceiling, Jones again belongs among the top 12-15 wideouts for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jones found the end zone in Week 1 but averaged just 5.2 yards on his six catches. He had a wrap on his wrist on Monday, so watch to see whether or not that amounts to anything significant later in the week. Atlanta's Week 2 game is on Sunday night, which could complicate things. Still, if he's active against an Eagles defense that just let Washington's Case Keenum set a career-best passing day, Jones remains a solid fantasy WR1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jones scored twice in Week 2, including a late 54-yard touchdown off a WR screen to win the game. His three touchdowns so far should have his fantasy shareholders optimistic heading into Week 3 versus the Colts, despite their strong defense so far. Neither of the Colts cornerbacks presents a daunting matchup, though bracketing him with safety Malik Hooker could limit his chances for big plays. You can start Jones with confidence as a fantasy WR1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jones has seen at least nine targets and five catches in every game this season,  while scoring four touchdowns. After his 8-128-1 domination against the Colts in Week 3, his biggest fantasy concern -- red-zone attention -- looks like it's not a concern after all. Jones remains a star fantasy WR1 in Week 4 against the Titans, who've allowed three touchdowns to wideouts over the last two games.

player.seasonOutlook: Say what you want about Jones' occasional touchdown deficiencies, he arguably has been the league's best wide receiver since entering the league in 2011. Incredibly, Jones' yards per target has ranked inside the top 20 wide receivers all eight seasons of his career. Despite an unlucky 2017 season in the touchdown department (3 TDs, 8.4 OTD), Jones predictably regressed to the mean and found paydirt eight times (8.0 OTD) in 2018. He finished fourth in fantasy points and hasn't finished a season worse than seventh since 2013. Jones is 30, but his game hasn't slipped, and a role that allowed a position-best eight top 10 fantasy weeks in 2018 is unlikely to change. He's a rock solid top 5 fantasy wideout.

outlooksByWeek.1: A strong projection for Fournette in Week 1 is supported by the Chiefs allowing the most yards per carry (4.96) to opposing tailbacks in 2018. Healthy and essentially unchallenged for every-down work to begin the season, Fournette is a potential RB1 candidate given the positive matchup and usage metrics in place.
outlooksByWeek.2: Despite registering his first career fumble and not scoring a touchdown, it still was somehow a promising opener for Fournette, who dominated backfield usage (no other back had more than one touch). He also led the team with 13 rushes and an impressive 5.1 yards per tote and was second on the team with six targets. Fournette remains a high-end RB2 heading into Week 2 against Houston's solid front seven.
outlooksByWeek.3: The workload has been there for Fournette to prove productive this season. The former LSU star is averaging 18 touches and 90.5 scrimmage yards, but a lack of touchdown production is holding him back from solid fantasy results. The Titans have been gashed on the ground to the tune of 117 yards per game allowed to tailbacks this season, helping Fournette's case as a volume-driven fantasy asset.
outlooksByWeek.4: Fournette hasn't gotten truly untracked this season and yet is still averaging 91 yards from scrimmage. The Broncos have limited opposing backs to just 3.49 yards per carry this season, but have also allowed a league-high five rushing scores to tailbacks this year. Given such a great weekly workload, Fournette remains a solid starting option.

player.seasonOutlook: Fournette hasn't quite lived up to lofty expectations since being selected fourth overall in the 2017 draft. The 24-year-old back has already missed 11 games and has seen his yards per carry fall from 3.9 in 2017 to 3.3 (fifth-worst) in 2018. Though, in his defense, Fournette has dealt with a large number of stacked boxes and horrific quarterback play. On the plus side, an extensive workload near the goal line (19 carries inside the 5 in 21 games) and good receiving efficiency (82 percent catch rate, 8.4 YPR) have helped him to two straight seasons finishing top-12 in fantasy points per game. Fournette's Trent Richardson-like efficiency woes are a concern, but the addition QB Nick Foles and massive volume he receives keep him in the RB1 discussion and offer hope for a breakout season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gordon is unlikely to return to the team from his extended contractual holdout in time to play against the visiting Colts. Austin Ekeler is expected to start and split work with Justin Jackson in Gordon's place.
outlooksByWeek.2: Gordon's holdout continues, with reports from NFL Network suggesting we might not see him until midseason.
outlooksByWeek.3: Still embroiled in an extended contract holdout, Gordon is unlikely to surface this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Gordon missed four games last season, but still finished top-10 among running backs in scrimmage yards, offensive touchdowns and fantasy points for the third consecutive season. Gordon maintained a substantial (albeit slightly reduced) share of the team's carries, and saw an uptick to 6.1 targets per game. That helped offset a bizarre drop in usage near the goal line; Gordon carried the ball inside the 5-yard line a total of 31 times during the 2016 and 2017 seasons but only four times in 2018. The goal-line usage is a concern, but Gordon is still in his prime at age 26 and is positioned for 300-plus touches in one of the league's better offenses. That, of course, assumes he reports to the team prior to Week 1. For now, Gordon is only worth a look in the fourth or fifth round.

outlooksByWeek.1: Golladay had the breakout season many expected in 2018, going over the 1,000-yard mark and hauling in five touchdowns. He's tops among Lions wideouts on the depth chart and should be one off Matthew Stafford's most-frequent targets this season. The Cardinals don't present an amazing matchup for the Detroit passing game in Week 1, but there's no reason to bench Golladay, who is safely in the WR2 discussion to start the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Golladay saw nine targets in Week 1, an encouraging sign and something to remember for those despairing after checking the box score to see a rookie tight end and veteran slot receiver racking up the yards in the Detroit passing game. It's far too early to despair, as Golladay did catch a touchdown and played the most snaps of any Detroit receiver. The Chargers were the fifth-toughest matchup for wideouts a year ago, but did allow T.Y. Hilton to score twice in Week 1, meaning Golladay is a strong Week 2 pick with some touchdown option -- consider him a high-end flex option.
outlooksByWeek.3: Golladay found the end zone in Week 2, giving him two scores in two games to start his third season as a pro. He's been heavily targeted through two weeks and appears to be locked in as Matthew Stafford's top target. That's a great place to be entering a Week 3 matchup with the Eagles, who just allowed Calvin Ridley and Julio Jones to both go over 100 yards receiving on Sunday. That duo combined for three scores, as well, adding even more appeal to Golladay's matcup. He's a safe pick as a WR2 this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Detroit's top receiver in terms of touchdowns and targets, Golladay remains the Lions wideout to have in fantasy on a weekly basis. However, this offense has seen its share of ups and downs this season - and Week 3 was definitely a down for Golladay, who only caught two of the eight passes thrown his way. That certainly wasn't all his fault, and it's encouraging to see the volume of targets remained high even when things weren't working. Look for that to continue in a game that should feature plenty of scoring as the Lions host the Chiefs. Golladay is locked in as a WR2.

player.seasonOutlook: The Lions turned to a run-first scheme and struggled with efficiency last season, but that didn't stop Golladay from enjoying a breakout season. The 2017 third-round pick exploded for a 70/1063/5 line despite 25 percent of balls thrown his way registering as off target (15th highest). Golladay was limited to two top 10 fantasy weeks and his touchdown total leaves something to be desired (6.0 OTD), but he still managed to put together a 21st-place finish in fantasy points in 15 games. The 25-year-old is, at least, a fringe WR2 and there's upside for more in his third NFL season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Engram has a chance to start the season in a big way with WR Golden Tate suspended. The third-year tight end improved his yards-per-target (9.0) and average reception yardage (12.8) in 2018 and should be busy in a likely comeback attempt against the Cowboys. Slot Engram comfortably in the TE1 fantasy tier for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Engram piled on 11 catches on 14 targets against the Cowboys, proving to be even busier than usual. Golden Tate was suspended and Sterling Shepard came out of this game with a concussion. Even if they were both on the field, Engram still has one of the safest workloads at his position. The Bills faced a Jets offense that didn't have much TE power, so don't count those stats against his outlook. He's still a fantasy TE1 in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Engram has seen 22 targets over the first two weeks of the season as the Giants receiving corps deals with numerous injuries and Golden Tate's suspension. In Week 3 against the Buccaneers, a team that has allowed 15.2 fantasy TE points-per-game (among the 10-highest rates), Engram should again lock in as a strong fantasy starter. Daniel Jones takes over at quarterback for New York, which could lead to an improved downfield passing game.
outlooksByWeek.4: Following a 6-113-1 Week 3 during Daniel Jones' debut at quarterback, Engram has now had at least eight targets, six receptions and one red-zone target in each of his first three games of 2019. The combination of Golden Tate's suspension and (in Week 3) Saquon Barkley's ankle injury have gradually opened up more targets for the talented third-year catcher. Besides, even when Tate returns, Engram will be heavily involved. Washington hasn't been damaged much by tight ends yet but their defense has allowed them to catch 85% of their targets so far, which helps cement Engram as a fantasy starter in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: A first-round pick back in 2017, Engram has missed six games due to injury but has produced at a high level when he's been healthy. In fact, he's ranked fourth and seventh, respectively, in fantasy points per game during his two seasons. Engram enters his third season positioned for an even larger role after New York traded Odell Beckham to Cleveland. Engram exploded during the four games Beckham missed last season, posting weekly fantasy finishes of 12th, first, fourth and third to finish off the 2018 season. Engram posted a top-10 fantasy week during 45 percent of his 2018 outings, which was sixth-best at the position. He ranked seventh with a 9.2 YPR and third with an 8.6 RAC. Engram is locked into a huge role in his third season and is a midrange TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: On the mend from a significant ankle injury suffered on the first day of camp, Green won't suit up this week in Seattle.
outlooksByWeek.2: Green is still on the mend from ankle surgery and isn't expected to suit up in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Green remains on the mend from August ankle surgery and isn't expected to make this trip to Buffalo.
outlooksByWeek.4: It's unlikely we see Green—who has yet to fully practice—activated for this matchup with the rival Steelers.

player.seasonOutlook: Green has been one of the league's top wide receivers since entering the league in 2011, but he hasn't finished a season better than ninth in fantasy points since 2013. Durability has been a big culprit, as Green has missed at least three games during three of the past five seasons, including a total of 12 games over the past three seasons. He's also expected to miss around a month to begin 2019. When Green has been on the field, he has been effective, ranking no lower than 16th in fantasy points per game during each of his eight NFL seasons. Green, who is averaging 9.0 targets per game since the start of the 2017 season, turns 31 this season and figures to have a few good years left in the tank. He's a solid WR2 once back from injury.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Wentz-versus-Nick Foles controversy is over, with the latter hving inked a deal with Jacksonville. Even so, Wentz could certainly stand to have a strong start to 2019 to prove any physical concerns are behind him. Washington's defense has enough holes that Wentz could excel immediately, with help from the Eagles' deep group of offensive playmakers -- including new RBs Jordan Howard and rookie Miles Sanders, plus rookie WR JJ Arcega-Whiteside. Count Wentz in the QB1 fantasy tier for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Wentz woke up in the second half, throwing for three scores against Washington in a comeback victory. He completed 71.8% of his passes. The Falcons let the Vikings offense pick them apart in Week 1, and though this game takes place in Atlanta, Wentz should put up capable borderline QB1 numbers in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Wentz struggled on the road in Week 2 at Atlanta but returns home against the Lions in Week 3. Unfortunately, injuries to three key receiving options -- Alshon Jeffery (calf), DeSean Jackson (groin) and Dallas Goedert (calf) -- loom over his fantasy outlook. If all are absent, downgrade him significantly. If some of them can play, Philadelphia should be able to adjust, with WR Nelson Agholor able to step in more frequently alongside star TE Zach Ertz. In the latter case, Wentz could remain a decent fantasy QB1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Wentz has failed to surpass 259 passing yards in either of his past two games, despite logging six passes of 20-plus yards in Philadelphia's Week 3 loss. Having to play without Alshon Jeffery (calf) and DeSean Jackson (groin) could hurt him in Week 4, as well, especially with the quick turnaround to Thursday night at the Packers. Wentz was able to adapt without that duo in the lineup in Week 3 with depth options, though, which keeps Wentz on the border of being a fantasy QB1.

player.seasonOutlook: Wentz came back to earth last season following a breakout 2017 campaign in which he tossed 33 touchdowns and seven interceptions in 13 games prior to tearing his ACL. Wentz, who was third in fantasy points per game in 2017, fell to 17th last season during the 11 weeks he was active. On the plus side, Wentz finished top 15 in yards per attempt for the second season in a row and improved his completion rate from 60 to 70 percent (fourth best). Likely related to his ACL recovery but still notable, Wentz's rushing production plummeted (93 yards on 34 carries). Wentz has the support of a great offensive line and now has DeSean Jackson, JJ Arcega-Whiteside and Jordan Howard in his arsenal. He is best valued as a good QB2, but has huge upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Shepard has shed his thumb splint and looks ready to serve as the Giants' top wide receiver for Week 1. The trade of Odell Beckham Jr., the four-game suspension of Golden Tate and a lack of other reliable wideouts all keep him in position to share most of the passing attention with TE Evan Engram. Even if those passes are coming from Eli Manning, Shepard still qualifies as a decent fantasy WR3 in Week 1 for volume alone against the Cowboys -- especially if the Giants must mount a furious comeback late in the contest.
outlooksByWeek.2: Shepard caught 6-of-7 targets in Week 1 but ended up in the league's concussion protocol, which jeopardizes his Week 2 availability. Buffalo contained Jets wideouts but allowed a big game to slot man Jamison Crowder, which would play well considering Shepard has a similar skill set. Still, even if he's active, Shepard is a fantasy WR3, at best.
outlooksByWeek.3: Shepard (concussion) missed Week 2 and is questionable against the Buccaneers in Week 3. If he suits up and Cody Latimer (concussion) doesn't, he could be a decent fantasy WR3 against the Buccaneers. Keep in mind, though, you may need to wait until late inactives land to make a decision, which may require a Plan B. (Maybe teammate Bennie Fowler?) Daniel Jones takes over at quarterback for New York, which could lead to an improved downfield passing game that could improve Shepard's weekly outlook whenever he does resurface.
outlooksByWeek.4: Shepard welcomed Daniel Jones as New York's new starting quarterback with open arms, as he went 7-100-1 on nine targets in Week 3. The new man under center elevates the Giants' weekly upside through the air, and Shepard should remain a heavy piece of this offense. He's a WR3 against Washington, despite a looming matchup with CB Josh Norman, though he may move around enough to avoid him. Washington, in fact, has allowed the most WR fantasy points-per-game so far in 2019.

player.seasonOutlook: Shepard received a contract extension during the offseason and, with Odell Beckham Jr. gone, he will team up with Golden Tate to lead the Giants' wide receiver position in 2019. The 2016 second-round pick averaged 6.3 targets per game during the 12 games Beckham played and 8.0 per game during the four he missed last season.
