Shepard has finished 36th, 42nd and 30th in fantasy points during his three seasons. Though the 25-year-old is primarily a short-to-intermediate area target (9.3 career aDOT) who doesn't add much in the touchdown department (six during the past two seasons), Shepard figures to reach a career-high in targets this season and that would allow him to push for WR2 production.

outlooksByWeek.1: The perils of paying up for a fantasy defense are on display right away here with the Jaguars as they face a deep and dynamic Kansas City offense right away. Try to avoid feeling pot committed to starting this D/ST in an unfavorable spot against what was an historic offense last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Even for this deep-and-dynamic Jaguars group, it's tough when you get Deshaun Watson the week after facing Patrick Mahomes. There isn't a great history of fantasy defenses meeting value as heavy road underdogs, as the Jaguars are this week. It's tough to move off of a defense with a strong reputation, but it could be wise to look for stronger alternatives than Jacksonville in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: In part due to a lack of playmaking from this back seven, the Jaguars are off to the ninth 0-2 start in franchise history. But the Titans aren't a very threatening offense given the lack of playmakers in the receiving department, aiding the Jaguars' case as a solid starting D/ST this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Broncos' passing game only presents a few weapons, which this Jacksonville secondary appears capable of containing. With the potential to pressure Joe Flacco throughout the afternoon, the Jaguars' D/ST is in a solid spot to produce on the road this week.

player.seasonOutlook: The Jaguars' D/ST predictably took a step back in 2018 following about as dominant a defensive performance as you'll see in 2017. After ranking top-nine in every fantasy-relevant category the year prior, the 2018 Jaguars' D/ST fell to 22nd in forced turnovers (17) and 22nd in sacks (37). They still showed well in yardage allowed (fifth) and points allowed (fourth), however, which salvaged a top-10 fantasy campaign. Malik Jackson's offseason release is notable, but 2018 first-round pick Taven Bryan is waiting in the wings and joins a terrific core led by Calais Campbell, Myles Jack, Jalen Ramsey, A.J. Bouye and first-round pick Josh Allen. This extremely talented group should be one of the first D/STs off the board, though streamers should note that the Jaguars play the Chiefs in Week 1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trubisky is one of several quarterbacks who must be evaluated differently by fantasy managers because of his production as a runner. He finished with the fifth-most rushing yards of signal-callers last season, giving him a very healthy floor in terms of weekly point hauls. So, while a matchup with the Packers seems mediocre, consider that he carried the ball for 32 yards and a score to open the season against them last year. That's a nice chunk of points before you even look to his passing line. He's a QB2, but not one to shy away from.
outlooksByWeek.2: Trubisky did not impress in his 2019 debut, averaging only 5.1 yards-per-attempt and failing to find the end zone as his team managed to put only three points on the scoreboard. However, Thursday games can often be outliers and fantasy managers should not have expected a ton out of a still-developing young passer. His outlook is a bit better for Week 2, as he'll face a Broncos defense that allowed Derek Carr to produce an impressive 10 yards-per-attempt with no interceptions or sacks allowed in Week 1. There are still quite a few preferred options out there, including many on waiver wires in most leagues, but Trubisky is in the conversation as a QB2 for leagues that start more than one signal-caller.
outlooksByWeek.3: Trubisky enters Week 3 in need of a breakout performance, having yet to score a touchdown and leading his Chicago's offense to only 19 points thus far on the season. That said, he has faced two tough defenses (Green Bay and Denver) and Week 3 brings an easier matchup against Washington -- a team that has given up three TD passes in both of its first two contests. This is a prime spot for Trubisky to break out of his early-season funk, so he's a borderline QB1 and certainly someone to consider in 2-QB leagues.
outlooksByWeek.4: Trubisky had a breakout game in Week 3, passing for three touchdowns in a much-needed big win over Washington. After facing two of the league's tougher pass defenses in Green Bay and Denver, it was encouraging to see Trubisky fare better in a more favorable matchup. Week 4 brings another tough contest, however, as divisional rival Minnesota comes to town. That relegates Trubisky back to the fantasy bench, although he's certainly a name to keep an eye on as a streaming option later in the year.

player.seasonOutlook: Trubisky took a giant step forward in his second season, throwing for 3,223 yards and 24 touchdowns, while adding 421 yards (fifth most among quarterbacks) and three touchdowns with his legs in 14 games. He ranked 11th in fantasy points per game. A closer look shows average or worse efficiency nearly across the board, including a 2.8 percent interception rate (11th worst). Trubisky has struggled with accuracy, as shown by his 20 percent off-target rate in 2017 (sixth worst) and 19 percent rate in 2018 (seventh worst). Trubisky's rushing ability and good supporting cast help his fantasy appeal, but he hasn't proven to be a good -- or even average -- starting quarterback yet. Consider him a midrange QB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: An ideal depth addition in deeper PPR leagues given his ability to thrive over the middle -- a coveted trait in an Adam Gase offense -- it's difficult to trust Crowder in starting lineups this week against a Bills defense that stifled receivers last season in allowing the fewest yards to the position.
outlooksByWeek.2: Leading the league with 19 targets, Crowder's debut saw him serve a huge role as Sam Darnold's security blanket. It's more than likely Crowder never gets 19 targets in a game again this year, but double-digit looks is reasonable to expect in this matchup against a sound, if exploitable, Cleveland back seven. Driven by a high-volume role, Crowder is a solid WR3 or flex this Monday night.
outlooksByWeek.3: The target hog role from Week 1 didn't translate into Week 2 for Crowder, as he dealt six targets with modest depth of target in the loss to Cleveland this past Monday. Even with a third-string quarterback possibly behind center, Crowder is still in the flex discussion given his ability to churn out PPR points in a game that could see the Jets forced to pass against the Pats.

player.seasonOutlook: Crowder joins the Jets after spending his first four seasons in Washington. Crowder aligned inside on 77 percent of his routes during four seasons with Washington and will operate between Robby Anderson and Quincy Enunwa in New York. Crowder cleared 65 receptions and 780 receiving yards in both 2016 and 2017, posting his best fantasy campaign (26th) during the former, but missed seven games due to injury in 2018. Extremely undersized, the 5-foot-8, 185-pound Crowder has 14 touchdowns (13.3 OTD) in 56 career games, seven of which came during the aforementioned 2016 season. New Jets head coach Adam Gase has made good use of his receivers, which adds to Crowder's fantasy appeal. He's a fine target in the middle rounds, but downgrade him in non-PPR leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Howard arrives from a complicated situation in Chicago, only to try his luck in a complicated situation in Philadelphia. Still, he has plenty of positives with which to work -- including a more competent quarterback in Carson Wentz and a clear advantage in goal-line and early-down work. Miles Sanders could prove to be an exciting complement, but Howard should be a busy back in Week 1 against Washington, who is trotting out QB Case Keenum and is still developing many parts of its game. Howard is a useful fantasy flex play, with a potential bump to RB2 in non-PPR formats that enhance TD-centric potential.
outlooksByWeek.2: Howard scrounged together 55 scrimmage yards in Week 1, thanks to an unexpected situation where the Eagles needed to log a comeback for a victory against Washington. In settings when the Eagles will have more control over the game flow, Howard should be busier. Atlanta's light run defense was trampled by the Vikings in Week 1, so expect Howard to show a glimmer of workhorse duties in Week 2, making him a solid fantasy flex.
outlooksByWeek.3: Howard spun his wheels, gaining just 18 yards on six carries in Week 2, reminding fantasy players of how shaky his week-to-week workload is in this offense. However, Week 3 could be tantalizing. The Lions have allowed 169.5 RB scrimmage yards-per-game. Howard and Miles Sanders could each enjoy a big day, and the Eagles may rely more heavily on the run if at least one of Alshon Jeffery (calf), DeSean Jackson (groin) and Dallas Goedert (calf) is forced to be inactive. Howard can be a handy fantasy flex for Week 3, with the upside of an RB2 if things go in Philadelphia's favor, allowing them to chew time off the clock late.
outlooksByWeek.4: Howard added a touchdown to an otherwise mediocre day in Week 3. He could be leaned on heavily in Week 4, at least in the similar 11-touch role he had on Sunday, After all, the Eagles are still dealing with injuries to Alshon Jeffery (calf) and DeSean Jackson (groin), which could make the running game more important. He's an acceptable flex play, especially with bye weeks starting.

player.seasonOutlook: Howard was traded to the Eagles after a successful three-year tenure in Chicago. With 3,370 career rushing yards, the 2016 fifth-round pick trails only Ezekiel Elliott and Todd Gurley II in the category the past three seasons. Howard has rushed for nine touchdowns each of the past two seasons but has seen both his yards per carry and yards after contact numbers fall each of the past two seasons. He has finished as a top-20 fantasy back in each of his three seasons despite a lack of receiving volume (106 career targets) and efficiency (career 68 percent catch rate and 5.4 YPT). Howard will share touches with rookie Miles Sanders and Darren Sproles this season, so his role as an early-down and short-yardage bruiser will limit him to flex numbers in non-PPR leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Agholor is fighting for WR3 work with rookie JJ Arcega-Whiteside -- a troubling development for him to scrape together attention in an already crowded Eagles receiving picture. Leave him on fantasy waiver wires for now, but he'll probably be useful later in the year if an injury surfaces or bye-week replacements thin out.
outlooksByWeek.2: Agholor totaled just 11 yards despite getting five targets in Week 1. He may not be that busy unless, as was the case in Week 1, the Eagles are in comeback mode. Behind Zach Ertz, Alshon Jeffery and DeSean Jackson, more often than not he won't find much work headed his way. Leave him on fantasy waiver wires.
outlooksByWeek.3: Agholor stepped up in Week 2 after injuries ended the game for both Alshon Jeffery (calf) and DeSean Jackson (groin). He'd again be in line for an expanded role if at least one of them is absent. Either way, against the Lions, Agholor would at least be a flex. Multiple inactives among this WR corps could slide him up to a fantasy WR3. Keep an eye on who suits up and adjust expectations accordingly.
outlooksByWeek.4: Despite becoming a hashtag after a few mistakes, Agholor paid off for his fantasy investors in Week 3 with a pair of touchdowns and eight catches. Assuming DeSean Jackson (groin) misses Week 4, as is expected, Agholor should be worth at least a fantay flex spot for the short turnaround Thursday at the Packers. However, Green Bay has been one of the stingiest fantasy defenses against receivers (23.6 points-per-game, the second-lowest mark).

player.seasonOutlook: Agholor's 2017 season felt like a success and his 2018 a disappointment, but his production was closer than you probably realize. The 2015 first-round pick posted a 62/768/8 line during a breakout 2017 season, but his 5.0 OTD suggested touchdown regression to the mean was on tap. Sure enough, the Eagles slot receiver posted a similar 64/743/4 line in 2018 with touchdowns being the notable exception. Agholor still managed a 34th-place finish in fantasy points (he was 23rd in 2017), though half of his four weekly finishes better than 38th came in Weeks 16-17. The 26-year-old still has a role in a good Eagles offense, but he has a lot of competition for targets with DeSean Jackson and J.J. Arcega-Whiteside now in the fold and Dallas Goedert entering his second season. Agholor is fine bench depth, but not a weekly starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams is far from a big-play back, but the BYU product has stuck with the Packers and heads into his third season, right behind Aaron Jones on the depth chart. The Bears offer a very tough matchup and Williams isn't the most efficenct back in the first place, though, so Week 1 isn't the best time to try to sneak him into a flex spot.
outlooksByWeek.2: Williams is definitely in a timeshare with Aaron Jones in the Green Bay backfield, but he seems to be squarely in the No. 2 position on the depth chart. Jones played on more snaps and saw eight more carries, even though Williams did manage two catches and targets (compared to just one for Jones). The Packers go from one tough divisional matchup to another in Week 2, facing a Vikings team that limited Devonta Freeman to 19 yards on eight rushes in Week 1. Keep Williams on your fantasy bench in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Williams isn't Green Bay's lead back, but that doesn't disqualify him from fantasy consideration. He's seeing just under 50% of the Packers' offensive snaps and has been targeted in the passing game six times while picking up 14 carries. That said, the Green Bay matchups  have been very difficult for the first two weeks, and that remains true in Week 3. As such, Williams' lack of efficiency and production is likely to continue. He's a risky flex play best left on benches in most leagues.
outlooksByWeek.4: It can be difficult to make sense of the Packers backfield, as Williams leap-frogged Aaron Jones in terms of playing time in Week 3 after being out-snapped in Weeks 1 and 2. Williams also had a better performance in Week 3 in terms of yards-per-carry, yet both of the rushing touchdowns from the duo came from Jones. It's safe to say we're unlikely to see either back pull away from the other any time soon. For now, both can be viewed as partners in what should be an improving offense. In Week 4, however, they face the Eagles, one of the best defenses against the run so far this season. With that in mind, Williams is just a flex option.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams has struggled with efficiency during his first two NFL seasons, but he has still managed to register 921 snaps and 326 touches during that span. The 2017 fourth-round pick increased his rookie-season 3.6 YPC to 3.8 in 2018, but his YAC fell from 1.9 to 1.7. That is despite facing extremely light boxes both seasons. Williams has also ranked near the bottom of the position in catch rate (73 percent) on 71 career targets. Though he'll sustain a role in the Packers' backfield, Williams won't see enough volume to allow fantasy relevance as long as the more effective Aaron Jones is healthy.

Crosby was fantasy's No. 7 kicker in 2018 after finishing 16th or worse each of the previous three seasons. He attempted 37 field goals, which tied for his second most in a single season in his 12-year career. Crosby has benefited from plenty of opportunity in Green Bay's high-scoring offense, but efficiency has eluded him nearly his entire career. He made 30 of 37 attempts last season (81.1 percent) and, in terms of expected conversion rate based on distance, Crosby has been below average in nine of 12 seasons, including each of the past three. Crosby is a fringe fantasy starter and loses some value in leagues that dock for misses.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last year, Kamara squashed any doubts from his productive rookie season by finding the end zone 18 times, matching his 81-reception debut and piling up 883 yards on 74 more carries than in his first go-around. The agile back looks primed for another top-end RB1 fantasy season. Even a moderately difficult matchup like the Texans shouldn't prevent fantasy managers from parking him in Week 1 lineups.
outlooksByWeek.2: Kamara recorded 20 touches and 169 scrimmage yards in Week 1, averaging 7.5 yards-per-carry and 9.0 yards-per-target. One of the top picks in most fantasy drafts, the third-year ball carrier is once again set for a RB1 tier fantasy ranking in Week 2 against the Rams in what is expected to be a high-scoring clash.
outlooksByWeek.3: The thumb injury that forced Drew Brees to exit Week 2 could throw off the entire Saints offense if he's going to miss 6-to-8 weeks. Kamara struggled after Brees left the game last week and probably will face many stacked boxes while the Hall of Famer is out. Teddy Bridgewater and Taysom Hill should improve with more prep, but their presence under center limits New Orleans' fantasy upside. That being said, Kamara's value may not dip too harshly in PPR fantasy leagues as he may be relied on for plenty of short routes and after-the-catch production. He's still a low-end fantasy RB1 against Seattle.
outlooksByWeek.4: Kamara recorded 25 touches -- his highest count on the season -- in Week 3, the team's first without Drew Brees (thumb). Expect the Saints to continue having their top back take pressure off QB Teddy Bridgewater with busy workloads. This added security, combined with his elite talent, keeps Kamara in fantasy RB1 territory for Week 4 against the Cowboys, who rank in the middle of the league with 23.2 RB fantasy points allowed per game.

player.seasonOutlook: Following as efficient a season as you'll find for any running back (let alone a rookie) in 2017, Kamara's 2018 went about as expected: He regressed to the mean, but still played at a high level and was a terrific fantasy asset. The former third-round pick finished top-eight among backs in snaps (628), touches (275), scrimmage yards (1592), offensive touchdowns (18) and fantasy points (354). Kamara has yet to clear 200 carries in a season, but he has caught 81 passes in both of his NFL seasons and saw a significant uptick in work near the goal line last season (his 14.5 OTD ranked second in the league). Kamara's role won't change much with Latavius Murray added to replace Mark Ingram II. The 23-year-old back remains a solid RB1 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: A quadriceps injury has hindered Evans this preseason but, barring a rapid change in the coming days, he looks ready to play against the 49ers. Evans marked a career high with 1,524 yards last year with a ridiculous 11.0 yards-per-target average. QB Jameis Winston has had to learn Bruce Arians' offense, but mastering it would offer a similarly lofty ceiling for the experienced 26-year-old wideout, who remains a low-end fantasy WR1 for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Evans was seemingly hindered by an illness in Week 1, registering just 28 receiving yards against the 49ers. Still, Jameis Winston looked ugly running this new offense, so perhaps it's not all Evans' fault. Still, it does hinder his upside against the Panthers in Week 2 on Thursday. Consider him to be more of a fantasy WR2 until Winston shows more comfort slinging the rock.
outlooksByWeek.3: Evans has dealt with an illness and the emergence of Chris Godwin in a quiet two-game start to 2019. Still, he's in a prime position to rebound. The Giants, Tampa Bay's Week 3 opponents, have allowed a league-high 550 WR receiving yards. Expect a breakthrough performance from the deep threat as a borderline fantasy WR1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Evans caught three scores against the Giants including his season-long catch of 55-yards. He saw 15 targets and 12.7 yards-per-target, living up to his big-play reputation. However, awaiting in Week 4 is the Rams defense, which has allowed the sixth-fewest WR fantasy points-per-game. Of course, considering Evans can break one off at any time, he's still at least a fantasy WR2.

player.seasonOutlook: Evans has finished no lower than 11th in targets, no lower than 12th in receiving yardage and no lower than eighth in OTD among wide receivers during each of the past four seasons. Despite that consistency, his fantasy output has been inconsistent due to fluctuating touchdown output. After catching 12 touchdowns as a rookie, his totals have been 3, 12, 5 and 8, respectively. Evans was fantasy's No. 9 wideout last season despite a career-low 23 percent target share. Impressively, he caught a career-high 62 percent of his targets despite a career-high 15.7 aDOT. Evans ranked third among receivers in both YPR (17.7) and YPT (11.0) and sits second in the NFL with 88 end zone targets since entering the league. The 6-foot-5 25-year-old is a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jacobs is so elusive that he was barely ever on camera for the team's Hard Knocks experience during camp. The top back selected in April's draft, Jacobs is likely to consume the majority of touches out of the Oakland backfield to begin the season. The Broncos were gashed badly on the ground last season in allowing nearly 4.8 yards per carry to tailbacks, supporting solid RB2 expectations for Jacobs in his professional debut.
outlooksByWeek.2: All Jacobs did in his first NFL game was tally 113 scrimmage yards and two touchdowns, becoming the first player since LaDainian Tomlinson in 2001 with 100 yards from scrimmage and two rushing scores in his debut. The Chiefs present an inviting matchup for this promising RB2 this week, as Kansas City has allowed 4.96 yards per carry to tailbacks since the start of last season, the highest rate in the league over this sample.
outlooksByWeek.3: Volume is a great quality for a feature back in fantasy football. Jacobs is one of only 14 players currently averaging at least 18 touches this season. The Green Bay backfield got untracked against this Vikings defense last week, but it's unclear if this Oakland offense can move the ball as capably as the Packers last week. Given the difficult road matchup and some wear and tear already affecting the rookie, Jacobs is in the flex discussion for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jacobs has been solid when given the ball, but since he's isolated to rushing work almost exclusively, his fantasy profile suffers somewhat in PPR formats. There is talk of getting Jacobs more targets, but until we see them, he's a solid RB2 given his rushing production and this matchup with a banged-up Colts front.

player.seasonOutlook: Oakland has a new feature back after selecting Jacobs with the No. 24 overall pick in April's draft. Jacobs has a solid frame (5-foot-10, 220 pounds) and is a terrific rusher, good receiver and even offers value as a kick returner. The Alabama product lacks top-end speed, but is quick, elusive and strong. Jacobs broke one tackle for every 6.1 touches last season, which was best among backs who attended the combine. Jacobs has the skill set to quickly step in as a three-down back in the pros and, aside from deferring some work to Jalen Richard in passing situations, he figures to play that full-time role right out of the gate. Jacobs shouldn't have trouble pushing for 250 touches as a rookie and should be viewed as an RB2 in season-long leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: The former Saint and Patriot has settled in Los Angeles, getting off to a flying start in his first full season with the Rams. Cooks set a career-high for receiving yards in 2018 and is poised to meet or exceed that figure now that he's built some rapport with Jared Goff. The Panthers allowed the eighth-most fantasy points to wideouts a year ago, making Cooks an easy pick as a WR2 for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Among the "big three" at receiver for the Rams, Cooks was surpassed by both Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp in Week 1. The former Saint and Patriot saw only six targets, compared to the 23 shared between his position-mates, and he caught just two of them for 39 yards. He was on the field for almost every offensive snap, so his playing time isn't the question. This just seems to be an issue of QB Jared Goff having too many mouths to feed in the offense. This may happen from time to time, but don't let it shake your confidence. Cooks is a WR2 in all formats in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Rams may have three elite receivers in Cooks, Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp, but the former Saint and Patriot is certainly the one with the most big-play potential. He put that on display in Week 2, hauling in a long TD pass from Jared Goff to help fantasy managers forget about a rough Week 1 outing. Cooks is a threat to have a massive score in any given week -- and that includes Week 3 against the Browns. Cleveland allowed Tennessee to pass for three scores in Week 1, so there's no reason to downgrade Cooks at all. He's a WR2 you can start with confidence.
outlooksByWeek.4: Cooks had a bit of a breakout in Week 3, seeing 12 targets and hauling in eight of them for a respectable 112 yards. Yet he was kept out of the end zone, limiting his fantasy performance to "good" and not "great." Since most drafted him to be great, they'll be hoping for things to change in Week 4 against Tampa Bay. The Buccaneers struggled against rookie Daniel Jones and the Giants in Week 3 and should provide Cooks with opportunities to get open and gain yards. He's a WR2 for this week's fantasy slate.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite bouncing all over the league in recent years, Cooks has put together four consecutive top 15 fantasy campaigns. He has ranked no lower than 11th in pass routes or 13th in receiving yards during the span. Though he's known for his speed and vertical presence, Cooks has ranked near the top of the position in screens and carries during the past two seasons. He has been about as efficient as you could reasonably expect, ranking no worse than 11th in yards per target each of the past three seasons. During the seven full games Cooks, Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp played together last season, Cooks handled a strong 23 percent target share (7.7 per game) and ranked ninth in fantasy points. The 25-year-old is a solid WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ryan fell 76 passing yards short of 5,000 in 2018 and ranks as one of fantasy's top quarterbacks once again. A big play in his favor is that Atlanta plays 13 of its 16 games indoors in 2019. That'll be the case in Week 1 , though it comes, unfortunately, at a tough Vikings defense. Still, with Julio Jones, Calvin Ridley, Austin Hooper and a healthy Devonta Freeman, Ryan has a group of talented receivers who'll keep him steadily among the QB1 fantasy rankings most weeks. Feel free to keep him there even in this difficult assignment.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ryan posted garbage-time volume in Week 1, topping 300 passing yards and accounting for two passing scores. He should feel more comfortable at home in Week 2 against the Eagles, who just allowed Washington's Case Keenum to post a career-high in passing yards against them in the opener. Despite his disappointing kickoff to 2019, Ryan deserves steady QB1 trust for Week 2 fantasy lineups.
outlooksByWeek.3: Despite having thrown five interceptions over his first two games, Ryan has also put five tallies in the TD column. The Colts have kept opposing quarterbacks in check, but the last one was Detroit's Matthew Stafford, which helped their numbers. Ryan will play indoors for the third straight game to open the season, which propels this high-octane offense. He'll again rank as a solid fantasy QB1 in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Week 3 marked Ryan's second straight game with three passing scores and the third with 300-plus passing yards. He has also increased his YPA each time, culminating at 8.9 at the Colts on Sunday. Atlanta is at home in Week 4, where Ryan has typically perfored better. The Titans have allowed six TD passes so far and, while they're among the tougher fantasy matchups for quarterbacks, Ryan still deserves the trust of a low-end fantasy QB1 this Sunday.

player.seasonOutlook: Perhaps one of the league's most underrated players, Ryan has ranked ninth or better in completions, passing yards and completion percentage each of the past seven seasons. Last season, Ryan finished second at the position in fantasy points for the second time in three seasons. He will be reunited with offensive coordinator Dirk Koetter. Ryan finished top five in the NFL in passing yards during each of Koetter's previous three seasons with Atlanta (2012-14). Ryan doesn't add much with his legs (though he did add three rushing scores along with 35 passing touchdowns last season), but he's never short on top-end volume and efficiency. Especially with a terrific wide receiver trio and solid offensive line, Ryan is positioned for another top-five fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cohen may have only carried the ball 99 times last season, but he did enough with those carries (plus his 71 receptions) to rank No. 11 in fantasy scoring among running backs. He's got a different backfield mate in David Montgomery this season, but that just means his role should remain the same. Cohen scored against the Packers in their contest last December, and nothing about the matchup suggests he can't do the same in Week 1. He's a solid flex pick to start the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Cohen was the best Chicago running back in Week 1, but that's not saying much. The Bears only managed three points and only made it to the red zone once, but Cohen saw 10 targets in the passing game and hauled in eight of them. He was second on his team in targets behind only estabilshed No. 1 receiver Allen Robinson, but fellow running back Mike Davis was third with seven looks. There's no reason to shy away from Cohen, whose electric moves should be on display against a Broncos defense that failed to impress in a Week 1 loss to Oakland. Consider Cohen a flex consideration in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Cohen is essentially the No. 2 receiver for Chicago, as he and Allen Robinson have seen 35 combined targets. No other player has more than seven. However, unlike Robinson, Cohen's looks in the passing game are short and lack upside, meaning his value is amplified specifically in PPR leagues and quite depressed in leagues that don't award points for catches. With that in mind, PPR players can consider him to be a flex pick in Week 3 against a Washington defense that has struggled to defend the pass this season. Those in non-PPR leagues can bench him.
outlooksByWeek.4: Cohen doesn't seem poised to see 10 targets-per-week, as his Week 1 performance may have suggested to the optimistic. He's seen only nine looks combined in the two games since. While he has picked up eight carries over that span, it's added up to a rather lackluster fantasy point output. He's still the team's second "receiver" from a fantasy perspective, but a tough matchup with Minnesota means his upside is limited. Combined with his poor track record so far this season, he can be downgraded to a flex option or RB3. Don't be afraid to swap him out for someone else.

player.seasonOutlook: Cohen played an expanded role as a change-of-pace and receiving back last season and did enough damage to produce the 11th-most fantasy points at the position. Cohen ranked top-six among backs in targets (91), receptions (71), receiving yards (725), touchdown catches (five), yards per target (8.0) and average depth of target (3.6). That helped overcome underwhelming rushing production. The undersized Cohen has ranked 71st and 70th among 72 qualified backs in YAC and has three total carries inside the 5 in his two NFL seasons. Cohen's role allowed him four top-six fantasy weeks, but also six finishes worse than 33rd. Jordan Howard was replaced by David Montgomery, so 5-foot-6, 190-pound Cohen's situational role is unlikely to change. His limited rushing and goal-line role makes him safest as a fringe top-25 back.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cook joins the Saints, although with the team's new run-first approach, that should be a less exciting proposition than what many have drafted him as this summer. It could be a big start, though. The Texans allowed 97 catches, 1,104 yards and 10 touchdowns to the TE position last year and just traded pass rusher Jadeveon Clowney. Cook won't always be a surefire fantasy TE1, but he belongs in that tier for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Cook was targeted just twice in Week 1. This problem probably will be frequent, as Drew Brees often looks toward Ted Ginn Jr. and Tre'Quan Smith for secondary looks beyond Michael Thomas and Alvin Kamara. On a positive note, in his first game with the Saints, he averaged 12.3 yards on his three targets, which preserves his big-play potential. Cook remains on the borderline of fantasy TE1 value for Week 2 as New Orleans will probably have to throw often to keep up with the Rams offense on the road.
outlooksByWeek.3: Cook caught just 2-of-7 targets in Week 2 and must deal with injured QB Drew Brees (thumb) set to miss 6-to-8 weeks. Teddy Bridgewater and Taysom Hill could lean on the TE position to get by, but Cook isn't necessarily known for that type of intermediate game. His high-risk, high-reward profile could pay off against the Seahawks, though. Seattle has allowed 20.6 TE fantasy points-per-game, third-most in the league. Consider Cook a low-end TE1 for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Cook was in on 75.9% of snaps in Week 3 but was targeted just twice. His role could expand in Week 4 as Teddy Bridgewater gets tasked to once again replace Drew Brees (thumb). The Cowboys rank among the 10 friendliest TE matchups, giving up 15.1 fantasy points-per-game to the position so far. Despite Cook's erratic involvement in a transitioning Saints offense, he could surprise due to the advantageous defensive opponent. Consider him as a Week 4 bye replacement or flex.

player.seasonOutlook: Cook signed with the Saints during the offseason after stints with the Titans, Rams, Packers and Raiders. After nine seasons in the league and no top-10 fantasy campaigns to show, Cook finally reached his potential with a breakout 2018 campaign. Cook hit career highs in targets (101), receptions (68), receiving yards (896) and touchdowns (six). He was fantasy's No. 5 scoring tight end. Cook's usage has been incredibly consistent, as he's averaged target shares between 16 and 18 percent each of the past seven seasons. If he keeps that streak alive in the Saints' high-scoring offense this season, Cook will no doubt post his second consecutive top-10 fantasy campaign. The 32-year-old is a solid TE1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kirk didn't make a ton of noise in his pro debut last year, hauling in 43 catches and scoring three times. Still, the agile, tough Texas A&M product will have rookie Kyler Murray under center and a full season of experience under his belt, making him an interesting player to watch from a fantasy perspective. He's in the flex discussion against a Lions defense that allowed the fifth-most yards-per-catch last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Kirk handled a healthy workload in Week 1, seeing 12 targets and also getting a rushing attempt. However, only four of his targets were caught and they only amounted to 32 yards -- including just three yards after the catch. He's definitely second-in-line for looks in the passing game behind veteran Larry Fitzgerald, and that's unlikely to change even if Michael Crabtree suits up in the near future. Still, Kirk's outlook for Week 2 isn't great. The Ravens allowed the seventh-fewest points to opposing wideouts a season ago and, in Week 1, they limited every Dolphins wideout outside of top target DeVante Parker to fewer than 30 yards receiving. He's one for the bench given the tough matchup.
outlooksByWeek.3: While veteran Larry Fitzgerald gets the most looks in the Arizona passing game, Kirk is right behind him -- and still ranks among the top 15 in the NFL in terms of opportunity. Kirk hasn't done quite as much with the opportunities he's been given, but that's to be expected when comparing a young wideout to a generational talent like Fitzgerald. A matchup with the Panthers in Week 3 doesn't bode particularly well for Kirk, because even though Carolina did allow Chris Godwin to break out in Week 2, that's the only aerial damage anyone has done against them this season. Kirk is in the WR3/flex discussion.
outlooksByWeek.4: Kirk is matching Larry Fitzgerald target-for-target so far this season, as the Cardinals' top pair of receivers have seen 62 (31 each) of the team's 137 passing attempts. Kirk is not making any big plays, though, averaging only 10.3 yards-per-reception and failing to find the end zone. Still, his volume is valuable and he has the skills as a runner to turn even short completions into big plays, so the big point totals are certainly still to come. He's a WR2 this week against a Seattle defense which allowed John Ross to have a breakout game in Week 1 and has been good, but not great, against wide receivers since.

player.seasonOutlook: Arizona selected Kirk in the second round of the 2018 draft and immediately slotted him in as a full-time player. Kirk was on the field for 85 percent of the team's pass plays and handled a generous 21 percent target share before landing on injured reserve with a broken foot. Kirk failed to post a single top-10 fantasy week, but was efficient, managing an 8.8 YPT and 5.3 RAC. Larry Fitzgerald is another year older, so the 22-year-old Kirk could very well take over as the team's No. 1 receiver this season, though he'll need to fend off rookies Andy Isabella and and KeeSean Johnson. Arizona's quarterback upgrade to Kyler Murray further helps Kirk's breakout chances. Consider him a borderline flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Barber enters Week 1 as the Buccaneers' lead back. By many assessments, that's where the excitement ends. Ronald Jones and preseason star Dare Ogunbowale may overshadow him in hype circles, but Barber looks like the best bet for early-down and goal-line work. Against the visiting 49ers, that's enough to assign Barber high-end fantasy flex value. Fantasy managers shouldn't count on this stability for the entire season, though.
outlooksByWeek.2: Barber took a back seat to Ronald Jones with just 45 scrimmage yards in Week 1. Jameis Winston's struggles under center could limit this offense for the near future, though regardless, Jones looked like the better back. Barber is a mere flex fantasy starter against the Panthers, though Carolina did allow 150 yards and two scores to the Rams' ground game. The Rams are a much better backfield, but perhaps there are lingering holes in the Panthers defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: In a sluggish Thursday night win, the Buccaneers rode Barber with Jameis Winston struggling again under center. This plot could repeat itself in Week 3 against the lowly Giants defense, which is tied with several teams in allowing a league-high three RB ground scores. Count Barber as a high-end fantasy flex.
outlooksByWeek.4: Barber had 15 touches in Week 3 but took a backseat to Ronald Jones in a high-scoring clash with the Giants. Barber hasn't averaged better than 4.1 YPC in any game this year. He'll continue to split time with Ronald Jones in a pass-first offense. Expect the Buccaneers to need to throw often against the Rams in Week 4, which lowers Barber's ceiling to that of only a decent fantasy flex play.

player.seasonOutlook: An undrafted free-agent signing back in 2016, Barber plodded his way to a pair of nondescript first two NFL seasons. He was forced into a much larger role in 2018, however, with second-round pick Ronald Jones struggling badly immediately upon joining the team. Barber went on to rack up 234 carries (ninth-most), but failed to impress, averaging a career-low 3.7 YPC (1.9 YAC). Despite ranking 10th at the position in snaps (583), Barber was targeted only 28 times. He turned those looks into 20 catches for 92 yards (3.3 YPT). Barber finished five weeks better than 37th at the position in fantasy points. The Buccaneers will be hoping for a much better season from Jones, but even if Barber remains the starter, he's a replacement-level back who is only worth a mid-to-late pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gallup averaged 15.4 yards-per-catch as a rookie and displayed the occasional polish that predicts a big step forward in his second season. Amari Cooper (foot/heel) looks like he's on track to play in Week 1, so his presence should limit Gallup to no more than a flex play, given Dallas' run-first approach. Still, if Cooper is limited or a surprise inactive, Gallup could thrive against the Giants -- especially if RB Ezekiel Elliott continues his holdout. Either way, Gallup could spring a big play against New York's questionable secondary, giving every reason to get him somehwere into your lineup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Complementary receiver? That looks like an unfair label after Gallup's 7-catch, 158-yard Week 1 and how effective Kellen Moore's new offense looked. Washington CB Josh Norman may not shadow Amari Cooper, but even if he focuses on Gallup, the latter still deserves trust as at least a flex play in fantasy lineups, with the upside of a WR2 against the Redskins.
outlooksByWeek.3: Gallup is set to miss 2-to-4 weeks in order to have knee surgery. He enjoyed another great game in this revamped Dallas offense during Week 2, and he's worth stashing if possible throughout his absence. In the meantime, Randall Cobb and Devin Smith, who both scored on Sunday, are the best in-house replacements for fantasy managers, though both of their workloads will probably remain erratic.
outlooksByWeek.4: Gallup (knee) sat out in Week 3, marking the first game he's expected to miss due to knee surgery. He's set to be inactive for Week 4, as well, though he's worth rostering in most leagues until he can return. He's averaging a whopping 15.1 yards-per-target so far, displaying his big-play potential.

player.seasonOutlook: All eyes are on Amari Cooper in Dallas, but don't overlook the guy lined up opposite him. Gallup -- a third-round pick last season -- played a situational role early on in 2018, but took over as a full-timer just prior to the acquisition of Cooper. Gallup played 77 percent of Dallas' snaps from Week 6 forward and, though he was a minimal fantasy contributor, he certainly showed flashes. Gallup's 14.1 aDOT (13th highest), 5.1 RAC (22nd), 15.4 YPR (12th) all ranked near the top of the league, though he dealt with 31 percent of balls thrown his way registering as off target (sixth-highest). The 23-year-old is an intriguing prospect who figures to be no lower than third in line for targets in a good offense. Take a mid-to-late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Few tight ends past the handful of elites claim the potential workload McDonald could consume for an offense that saw more than 200 targets vacated over the offseason. It's rare to find a player break out as an offensive threat at 29, but McDonald might just be the outlier. Per this week's matchup, the Patriots allowed more than 800 yards and eight scores to tight ends last season, both above league average.
outlooksByWeek.2: For all the talk of Vance McDonald's quiet opener, he was fourth on the team with 30 routes and earned four targets with respectable air yardage (near eight yards per target). The Seahawks coughed up a good deal of yardage to the Bengals' tandem of tight ends, so there is at least some matchup appeal for McDonald heading in.
outlooksByWeek.3: The shift to Mason Rudolph at quarterback didn't stunt McDonald's fantasy profile; if anything their rapport was encouraging for the weeks ahead. The 49ers allowed Tyler Eifert to score this past week, but have been generally solid against tight ends dating back to last season. It's worth trusting McDonald in a starting spot given what should be a healthy share of the offense for this trip to San Francisco.
outlooksByWeek.4: McDonald's usage is likely to prove volatile a bit this season now that the total passing market is smaller sans Ben Roethlisberger, but he's still in the starting mix at the position given his big-play ability in a matchup with a Bengals defense allowing the third-most yards per catch to tight ends.

player.seasonOutlook: A consistent 2018 campaign led McDonald to a career-best 10th-place finish in fantasy points. The veteran tight end handled at least four targets in 12 of 15 games and scored between six and 14 fantasy points in 13 games. He ended up with a 50-640-4 line, and his eight end-zone targets were fifth most at the position. McDonald's 7.8 RAC was fourth-best last season, and he's never finished a season in which he's handled 40-plus targets lower than ninth in the category. A position-high 17 percent of his targets were on screens last season. With Antonio Brown and Jesse James gone, McDonald could move as high as second in targets on a good Steelers offense. The 29-year-old is a fine TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: The new man in town after being on the trade block for much of training camp with Miami, Stills is a gifted vertical threat who should fit well into Houston's big-play offense. It's unclear what Stills' role will be after being acquired just days before the season, making it more reasonable to stash the ex-Saints standout in his return to New Orleans.
outlooksByWeek.2: In his Texans debut, Stills' clutch touchdown catch in the final minute of Week 1 vs. the Saints helped give Houston a brief lead. But Stills only ran 19 routes (out of 35) and could face increased competition for snaps and routes with Keke Coutee on the mend. It's nice to get shares of a top passing attack, but it's best to avoid Stills against the Jaguars' tough secondary.
outlooksByWeek.3: Competing with the likes of Keke Coutee and Will Fuller for opportunities in the Houston passing game, Stills just doesn't have enough of Deshaun Watson's attention to merit trust in fantasy leagues for this meeting with a solid Chargers secondary.
outlooksByWeek.4: Stills led the Texans in air yardage and actual yardage in Week 3 and is now clearly ahead of Keke Coutee in the pecking order. Even with great vertical usage, Stills is a risky flex option because he's third in line for total targets and faces a solid secondary in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Stills has been around since 2013, but has yet to finish a season better than 28th at the position in fantasy points. That's despite missing only two games in six seasons and despite having scored at least six touchdowns each of the past three seasons. Volume is the chief concern for Stills, as he's ranked higher than 56th at the position in targets once in his career (2017). Stills is a terrific deep threat (he's ranked top 13 in aDOT and Top 22 in YPR each of the past four seasons), but his role as a situational deep threat limits his fantasy upside. In fact, he managed only two weekly finishes better than 25th last season. Traded to Houston, Stills' playing time figures to take a dive with DeAndre Hopkins, Will Fuller and Keke Coutee in the mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Broncos were weak in defending receiving backs last season (8.62 YPC), although Richard isn't likely to touch the ball more than six or seven times this week. Unlikely to match last season's 68-catch breakout, Richard will still be a steady factor on passing downs for the Raiders this season despite the presence of top pick Josh Jacobs.
outlooksByWeek.2: Given one touch and minimal exposure as a receiving threat in Week 1, Richard is at best a handcuff to Josh Jacobs and more realistically can be left in fantasy free agency.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Raiders have divvied routes almost equally between Richard, Josh Jacobs and DeAndre Washington, leaving Richard with essentially no fantasy value outside of handcuff potential for Jacobs.
outlooksByWeek.4: Even as he led the backfield in snaps in Week 3, Richard didn’t see the ball enough to surface as a fantasy force. Stuck far behind Josh Jacobs for meaningful rushing work, Richard isn't a worthy fantasy option this week against an Indianapolis defense struggling to stop the run.

player.seasonOutlook: After flashing on a grand total of 195 touches his first two NFL seasons, Richard finally earned an expanded role in Jon Gruden's first season at the helm. Richard was limited to a career-low 55 carries, but his 80 targets more than doubled his previous career high. He caught 85 percent of his targets (fourth-best) and finished top-eight at the position in yards per target (7.6) for the second season in a row. Although Oakland called pass on 81 percent of Richard's snaps, he averaged more than 4.7 YPC for the third consecutive season. Richard scored only one touchdown, his best weekly fantasy finish was 16th, and he's a candidate for a dip in targets after Oakland revamped at wide receiver. His role as a complement to Josh Jacobs is enough for flex value in deep PPR leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, the Vikings finished fifth in overall scoring among D/STs, fueled by their 50 sacks (fourth in the league). Things shouldn't be much different this time around, but a matchup with the Falcons isn't the best from a defense and special teams perspective. Atlanta tied for seventh in fewest turnovers by an offense last season and also ranked in the middle of the league in sacks allowed. Still, there aren't 10-12 better options, so lock Minnesota in as a starting D/ST.
outlooksByWeek.2: The Vikings D/ST looked solid in Week 1, especially from a fantasy perspective. They picked off a pair of passes, recovered a fumble, racked up four sacks and blocked a punt. Those actions, more than points or yards allowed, always fuel fantasy success, which is why the Vikings are a must-start even against the Packers in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: If you could have any Vikings fantasy option, you'd pick Dalvin Cook. After Cook, the D/ST might be the most valuable fantasy asset the team has to offer. With five turnovers forced and six sacks so far, they're off to a strong start -- and figure to only get better as the season goes on. This week's matchup with the Raiders is decent because, while they did throw two interceptions and allow three sacks against the Chiefs in Week 2, they allowed no sacks and did not give the ball away in Week 1 against an elite Broncos defense. Still, if you have the Vikings D/ST, you're starting them. Just don't expect the best score, given the Raiders' track record so far this season.
outlooksByWeek.4: They've yet to score a touchdown, but the Vikings D/ST has three interceptions, three recovered fumbles and 10 sacks through three games. That's the sort of consistent performance you can expect from one of fantasy's premier D/ST units. Keep Minnesota in your lineup in a favorable matchup with a Bears team that struggled against the other top defenses (Green Bay and Denver) they faced earlier this season.

player.seasonOutlook: The Minnesota D/ST finished fifth in fantasy points last season, marking its fourth consecutive top-11 campaign. Minnesota has been especially good in points allowed (ninth or better each of the past four seasons) and yards allowed (fourth or better each of the past three seasons) but added 50 sacks (third) to its arsenal in 2018. The losses of Sheldon Richardson and Andrew Sendejo cannot be ignored, but a strong core led by Linval Joseph, Danielle Hunter and Harrison Smith remains intact. Minnesota sports a solid top-five D/ST unit.

John Christian Ka'iminoeauloameka'ikeokekumupa'a Fairbairn paced all kickers in fantasy points last season thanks to a league-high 42 field goal attempts. He converted on 37 (or 88.1 percent), which was a step forward after he hit 20 of 25 attempts in 2017. Fairbairn also ranked eighth in extra-point attempts (he made 39 of 41). Houston's kicker benefited greatly from a strong offense that struggled to convert drives into touchdowns. It's possible that dynamic changes in 2019, but an offensive line still full of holes makes a big leap unlikely. That should make the 25-year-old a viable weekly fantasy starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rivers faces a solid Colts defense at home this week, placing him on the QB1 fringe in a contest with a modest projected point total. Helping Rivers' case as a starting option this Sunday is the deep and dynamic collection of skill players at his disposal, even sans Melvin Gordon.
outlooksByWeek.2: Rivers now has four career openers with at least 300 passing yards in his career, while all other Chargers QBs have combined for four such games in franchise history. The Lions were strong against the Cardinals' air raid offense for much of Week 1, only to still cough up a 300-yard showing to Kyler Murray in an eventual tie. Rivers should be able to push the ball downfield in Detroit on Sunday, setting up another solid QB1 showing.
outlooksByWeek.3: Found at No. 15 among quarterbacks in fantasy production, Rivers fittingly profiles as a fringe QB1 this week against a strong Houston pass rush. The Texans' secondary is exploitable as long as Rivers gets enough time to operate, which should prove more viable at home with better ability to manage adjustments at the line.
outlooksByWeek.4: Having just made his 211th consecutive regular-season start, Rivers ironically moved ahead of Eli Manning for the second-longest such streak by a QB in NFL history (Brett Favre, 297). You can enjoy consecutive start 212 in fantasy lineups thanks this meeting with an inept Miami defense allowing more than 10 yards per attempt to opposing arms.

player.seasonOutlook: Rivers enjoyed one of the best seasons of his career in 2018, throwing 32 touchdowns, which matched his second-highest total of the past decade. Rivers also cleared 4,200 passing yards for the sixth consecutive season and finished top five in yards per completion for the third consecutive season. Despite yet another terrific passing season, Rivers was limited to six top-10 fantasy weeks and failed to finish as a top-10 fantasy QB for the fourth time in five seasons. The culprit? Minimal rushing contributions. Rivers hasn't scored a rushing touchdown since 2011 and has a total of 5 rushing yards on 36 carries over the past two seasons. Unless your league awards more points for passing categories, Rivers is limited to QB2 territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: Adams has emerged as the go-to target on the Packers offense, which is a great place to be when Aaron Rodgers is under center. His 2018 can certainly be classified as a breakout, as he set career-high marks in catches, targets, yards and touchdowns. He has proven he can score just about a touchdown-per-game over the past three seasons, but things won't come easy against the Bears' talented defense. Still, there's no reason to downgrade Adams or worry about him at all in Week 1. He's locked in as a WR1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Adams led the Packers in targets in Week 1, so while his (and his team's) performance surely disappointed, don't lose faith. The Bears are a tough opponent and Thursday games tend to be tricky. That said, don't expect immediate regression to the mean in Week 2, as the Vikings are a tough bunch on defense, as well. They did allow both Julio Jones and Calvin Ridley to find the end zone in Week 1, but the Falcons did not look sharp on offense against this unit -- and the Packers may not, either. Adams is still a WR1, but not the most appealing one due to the quality of opponent.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Packers offense has one of the toughest schedules to start the season, facing a trio of great defenses -- including Week 3's opponent, Denver. The Broncos allowed Tyrell Williams to go over 100 yards and score in Week 1, but kept Allen Robinson in check in Week 2. That doesn't bode well for Adams. While he could well end up, like Williams,  succeeding in this tough matchup, he could just as easily be like Robinson, which would surely frustrate fantasy managers. He's too good to bench, just don't bank on him to carry your team in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: After three straight games against great pass defenses, Adams will finally get a chance to deliver on his preseason promise in Week 4. Adams has split targets with Marquez Valdes-Scantling so far this season -- both players have 19 of them on the year -- but that shouldn't cause any alarm for those who drafted him early. The Fresno State product is the unquestioned top option in the Green Bay passing game and will face an Eagles defense that has allowed a 100-yard receiver in every game this year. Lock him in as a WR1.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams took his game to another level in 2018. In fact, before missing Week 17 because of an injury, Adams was the No. 1 scoring fantasy wide receiver. Incredibly, Adams ranked in the top 18 among wide receivers in all but one week last season (27th in Week 4) aside from the one week he missed. In addition to catching 13 touchdowns (second most), Adams ranked fourth at the position in routes (618), fourth in targets (164), fifth in receptions (111) and sixth in receiving yards (1,386). Adams has hauled in 35 touchdowns over the past three seasons, which trails only Antonio Brown for most in the league. Adams has done this damage despite missing at least one game three of the past four seasons. The 26-year-old soaked up a massive 30 percent target share last season and has little competition for targets again in 2019. He's a fine choice in the middle of the first round.

outlooksByWeek.1: While it's unlikely any fantasy managers are considering benching Gurley for Week 1, it's not unfair to have doubts about last season's top pick for most drafters. The end of the 2018 campaign was rough for Gurley, who struggled with both injury and poor performances as the season drew to a close. However, he's a workhorse (250-plus carries in each of the past three seasons) who knows how to find the end zone (40 touchdowns combined over the past two seasons). Lock him into your lineup against a solid, but not overwhelming Panthers rushing defense and worry about "start or sit" decisions elsewhere.
outlooksByWeek.2: After ending the first half with just eight yards on five carries, you can be forgiven for worrying if your first-round pick was already a massive mistake. But Gurley came through when his team needed him, rushing for 64 yards in the fourth quarter alone and pacing his team in carries. However, Malcolm Brown saw most of the red-zone work and scored a pair of touchdowns. That's a concerning sign for the Georgia product who doesn't seem at 100% after struggling with injuries down the stretch a year ago. Don't hesitate to start Gurley this week, but don't be surprised if he's not the same "bell cow" we've seen in years past.
outlooksByWeek.3: It may appear as though Gurley's volume is down, as the 25-year-old appears to be limited due to the same sort of injuries that slowed him down at the end of 2018. However, with 30 carries and five targets so far, he's actually just shy of his career average for carries-per-game (18) and is right on track in terms of targets. He's also gaining yards at a very efficient rate (5.3 yards-per-attempt). Week 3 brings a matchup with the Browns, who allowed Derrick Henry to find paydirt in Week 1 before keeping the Luke Falk-led Jets in check in Week 2. There are no guarantees that this will be a huge game for Gurley, but something like Henry's 84 yards and a score should be expected.
outlooksByWeek.4: Gurley still gets tons of touches in the high-powered Rams offense, but those who drafted him have to be feeling a bit uneasy about his lack of production through three weeks. Sure, he has found the end zone once, but otherwise he's been limited to lots of short gains. He is seeing only around 14 carries-per-game. Combined with his struggles at the end of last season, there's every reason to worry he's taken a step back, with injuries likely to blame. Regardless, when evaluating him for Week 4, the Buccaneers defense poses a tough test, having yet to allow an RB rushing score this season. Tampa Bay has conceded only 160 RB rushing yards on 59 carries over three games. Gurley should still start, but he's more of a high-end RB2 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: After Gurley was the consensus No. 1 overall pick in 2018 fantasy drafts, his stock is down following an injury-fueled slow finish to the season. Gurley is expected to be fully healthy for 2019, of course, which means you may actually be able to get a discount on a player who scored 21 touchdowns in 14 games last season. The 24-year-old workhorse missed two games but still ranked fourth among backs in snaps, touches and scrimmage yards. He has paced running backs in fantasy points per game and top-10 fantasy weeks each of the past two seasons. Concerns about Gurley's knee remain, which has knocked down his fantasy stock, but his massive fantasy upside makes him a fine choice in Round 2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Johnson had his rookie season cut short due to injury, but was looking like a solid RB2 option up until that point. Healthy and ready to go for Week 1, he's got competition for touches but should be the lead back for Detroit as he looks to prove he can sustain his 5.4 yards-per-carry average and healthy pass-catching workload. The main risk comes in the form of competition from C.J. Anderson, but a matchup with the Cardinals (second-most points allowed to running backs last season) should only serve to increase your confidence locking Kerryon in as an RB2.
outlooksByWeek.2: Johnson led the Lions in both rushing attempts and yards in Week 1, but he unfortunately was only targeted twice in the passing game. He hauled in both of those chances, but another pair of passes went the way of late addition J.D. McKissic, who appears to have a role as a change-of-pace pass-catcher out of the backfield. That will slightly lower Johnson's offensive upside, but he's clearly the team's first-choice back ahead of C.J. Anderson. In Week 2, he'll face a Chargers defense which allowed Marlon Mack to break free for 175 yards in Week 1, so consider Johnson a solid RB2, although maybe with a bitof a lower ceiling than previously thought, due to McKissic's presence.
outlooksByWeek.3: Johnson is absolutely the lead back in Detroit, as C.J. Anderson lags behind him in both snaps and carries. While Ty Johnson and JD McKissic also see a handful of snaps, the top spot and the bulk of the work go to the second-year Auburn product. He's yet to deliver much as a runner, however, averaging only 3.2 yards-per-attempt. He's also seen only five targets, so while his receiving score in Week 2 was a nice boost, that's not a big part of his game yet. The Eagles have been one of the toughest matchups for opposing backs this season -- apart from allowing receiving specialist Chris Thompson to haul in seven passes in Week 1 -- so this is an unappealing spot for Johnson. He's a flex option in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Johnson is the unquestioned lead back in Detroit at this point. C.J. Anderson is no longer with the team and backups Ty Johnson and J.D. McKissic only see a few snaps per game. In Week 3 against Philadelphia, Kerryon saw a ton of carries, even though he wasn't able to do much with them. That is an encouraging sign that Detroit trusts in him -- despite the lack of results. He even managed to find the end zone to salvage his day from a fantasy perspective. The Chiefs have actually been somewhat prone to allowing big days from running backs, so while the Lions may have to throw to keep up, they're almost certain to keep Johnson involved in the running game as well. He's a solid RB2 option for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Johnson was one of the youngest players selected in the 2018 draft, but that didn't stop the Auburn product from making an immediate impact. Despite playing only 51 percent of the snaps, Johnson ranked 14th among running backs in fantasy points prior to suffering a season-ending injury in Week 11. Johnson averaged 5.4 YPC (fifth-best) and caught 84 percent (seventh-best) of his 38 targets. Johnson will defer some touches to C.J. Anderson and PJ Johnson this season, but his averages of 12.5 carries and 4.0 targets per game after Week 1 last season will suffice to allow him RB2 production. Plus, there's room for more if he continues to play at a high level and with Theo Riddick gone. Johnson is a solid RB2 and breakout candidate.

outlooksByWeek.1: Diggs combines with Adam Thielen to form one of the best combinations at receiver in the league, and there's always been enough to go around in the Minnesota offense to keep fantasy managers happy. Diggs had his best season a year ago, going over 100 catches and 1,000 yards for the first time while hauling in a career-best nine scores. Against an Atlanta team that allowed 24 touchdowns to wideouts last year -- the second-highest mark in the league -- Diggs is a "set it and forget it" WR2 on the cusp of being a WR1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Diggs was a victim of his team's success in Week 1, seeing only two targets among the Vikings' 10 total passing attempts. That's what happens when your team races out to a 28-0 lead and turns to the run to churn the clock and manage the game. He entered the season bothered by a hamstring injury, but played through it and seemed fine. There's no reason to be worried about him in Week 2 and beyond. He's a flex option against a fairly tough Packers defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: Diggs has lagged behind fellow receiver Adam Thielen a bit in volume this season, but not by enough to cause panic among those who invested in the Maryland product. The main cause for concern is the run-first nature of the Vikings offense. However, when they do pass, it's usually going to Diggs or Thielen. They'll get their numbers, even in a low-volume offense. The Raiders looked decent on defense in Week 1 against the Broncos, but then in Week 2 allowed Patrick Mahomes to post eye-popping numbers in the second quarter alone. Kirk Cousins and the Vikings might not recreate what the Chiefs did, but there's reason for optimism that the passing game can get something going in Week 3. Consider Diggs as a solid WR3/flex pick.
outlooksByWeek.4: Diggs saw only three targets in Week 3 as the Vikings again turned to the ground game in a victory. The Maryland product saw seven looks in a Week 2 loss to the Packers. It appears that the Vikings are only going to throw -- and subsequently throw to Diggs -- when the score absolutely dictates that they do so. So, while he may have commanded a fairly high pick in drafts, he's simply not seeing the sort of volume required to be a starting fantasy receiver. This is especially true against a Chicago defense that is talented from front to back. Diggs is a risky flex play (at best) in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Diggs has been a strong fantasy force when healthy, ranking no lower than 14th in fantasy points per game during each of the past three seasons. "When healthy" has been the key, however, as Diggs has yet to make it through a full 16-game season, missing nine games in four seasons. Diggs did manage a career-best 10th place fantasy finish last season, however, fueled by top-8 finishes in targets (148), receptions (102) and touchdowns (9). Primarily a short-area target, Diggs' 10.0 YPR was sixth lowest and his 6.9 YPT 16th lowest at the position. Even with Minnesota looking to run more often, the 25-year-old should get enough volume to allow strong WR2 value.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ridley dazzled with his 64-821-10 rookie season and should continue garnering plenty of attention from Matt Ryan. Likely to avoid Vikings CB Xavier Rhodes most of the time in Week 1, the sophomore could outperform top Atlanta WR Julio Jones, giving Ridley a strong WR2 ceiling in the season opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ridley found the end zone in his first 2019 action, despite falling behind both Julio Jones and Austin Hooper in targets. The big-play receiver averaged 10.7 yards-per-target, reflecting his weekly upside. That sets up well in Week 2 against the Eagles, who just let Washington QB Case Keenum work for a career-high in passing yards in Week 1 and were often torched by rookie deep threat Terry McLaurin. That fits well with Ridley's profile, making him a strong fantasy WR3 with tons of upside.
outlooksByWeek.3: Ridley's 8-105-1 Week 2 line marked his second straight outing with a touchdown to start the season. Julio Jones should draw much of the Colts' defensive attention in Week 3, which could leave Ridley open for more 1-on-1 matchups. He's earned Matt Ryan's attention in his own right since his 2018 rookie season, though, and he'll make for a solid fantasy WR3 on the heels of his 16 targets over the first two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Colts shut down Ridley for just one target in Week 3, far below his 8.0 average over the first two games. The Titans have allowed three touchdowns to wideouts over the past two weeks, and Ridley should remain in the fantasy WR3 realm for his big-play ability.

player.seasonOutlook: Ridley finished his rookie season 22nd in fantasy points despite playing third fiddle behind Julio Jones and Mohamed Sanu. He ranked 39th at the position in routes (451) but caught 70 percent of his targets, averaged 5.5 yards after the catch and scored 10 touchdowns. The latter is notable, as Ridley was limited to five end zone targets and posted a 4.1 OTD. The 24-year-old is an obvious strong bet for touchdown regression this season, but it's possible he sees an increase in targets in his second season. Consider him a fringe WR2 in 12-team leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Montgomery went from the Bears' third-round pick to their lead running back in a hurry, as the team looks to replace the work done by Jordan Howard (who has been traded to the Eagles). As such, look for the Iowa State product to handle most of the carries while teammate Tarik Cohen provies a change of pace and leads the way in terms of receptions out of the backfield. A healthy workload is in store for Montgomery, so consider him as a borderline RB2, or maybe a bit higher if you play in a non-PPR league.
outlooksByWeek.2: Montgomery was viewed by most as the running back to start behind Tarik Cohen in the Bears backfield, but he was outsnapped and lagged behind in opportunites compared to veteran Mike Davis. Davis had one fewer carry than Montgomery, but saw six more targets in the passing game. With two players splitting this role as the "traditional" compliment to Cohen, there's a lot of uncertainy here. That means Montogmery is going to be tough to trust in fantasy, even in a now-appealing matchup with a Broncos defense that allowed Josh Jacobs to score twice in Week 1. He's a risky flex pick for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Now that's more like it! Montgomery didn't get much of a chance to show what he can do in his NFL debut, receiving only six carries against the Packers in Week 1 and being outsnapped by veteran Mike Davis. The script was flipped in Week 2, with the Iowa State rookie seeing more snaps than Davis and picking up 18 carries along the way. He still didn't play on a majority of Chicago's snaps, which is concerning for his long-term volume, but he's looking more like the lead back everyone expected to see. In Week 3, he gets an appealing matchup with a Washington defense which allowed 111 yards and a score to Ezekiel Elliott just a week ago. He's solidly in the flex discussion for his third professional game.
outlooksByWeek.4: Montomgery had his best game as a pro in Week 3, picking up 67 yards on 13 carries for over 5.0 YPA. Yet, that's still not a great total for a starting running back -- especially one who will see limited action in the passing game with Tarik Cohen present. Even worse for Week 4, the Vikings come to town with their solid run defense. While the Packers' Aaron Jones did rush for 116 yards and a score in Week 2, no other back has eclipsed 44 yards in a game against them and Jones is the only one to have found paydirt as a runner. With that in mind, keep Montgomery as more of a speculative flex play, and consider other options for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bears selected Montgomery in the third round of April's draft to help replace Jordan Howard, whom they traded to the Eagles. Montgomery figures to immediately play a significant role along with change-of-pace back Tarik Cohen. He is one of the biggest backs in this class (5-foot-10, 222 pounds). His on-field profile is very similar to Kareem Hunt's, as he lacks some speed (4.63 40-yard dash) and explosiveness, but makes up for it with a combination of power, balance and especially elusiveness. The Iowa State product evaded a tackle once for every 5.1 touches last season (second best in the class) and is also a good receiver and blocker. Montgomery is a potential workhorse and, though he'll defer a lot of targets to Cohen this season, Montgomery could push for 200-plus carries. Consider him a fringe RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: It seems odd to say that a quarterback throwing 25 touchdowns and only two interceptions had a letdown of a season, but for Aaron Rodgers, 2018 could be classified as a disappointment. Normally the perennial All-Pro is tossing 30-40 touchdowns-per-season and sitting atop the fantasy leaderboards by the end of the campaign. He'll look to get back to those heights in 2019 starting with a matchup against the "aggressive but not unbreakable" Bears defense, who allowed the fifth-fewest points to quarterbacks last season. It's not a great matchup, but he's still a QB1, regardless of the opponent.
outlooksByWeek.2: Rodgers and the Packers offense did not impress in Week 1, but the Bears have a solid defense and Thursday games tend to be a bit on the ugly side. He did attempt 30 passes and ran the ball three times, so it's not as if Green Bay doesn't trust their veteran signal-caller and team leader. He's going to have better games than this. Heck, odds are he'll have about 15 of them. That starts in Week 2 against the Vikings, who are solid defensively but did allow Rodgers to throw for nearly 300 yards and a touchdown almost exactly a year ago (Week 2 of 2018). The upside isn't high, but this guy is a QB1 until further notice.
outlooksByWeek.3: Those who drafted Rodgers won't be thrilled with his performance so far, but his two starts have come against two tough defenses. To come away with three touchdowns and no interceptions is a credit to the 35-year-old's ability under center. Things get no easier in Week 3, however, as the Packers host the Broncos and their elite defense. Over two games, Denver has allowed only 379 passing yards and a single touchdown. Rodgers is still a must-start, but wait for better matchups before getting too angry about his lack of fantasy returns.
outlooksByWeek.4: It's unusual to have to scroll so far down the scoring leaders page to find Rodgers but, after three weeks, Green Bay's quarterback has been outscored by some surprising names, such as Gardner Minshew and Case Keenum. That said, he's faced three of the toughest pass defenses in the NFL, something that changes in Week 4. The Eagles allowed Keenum to pass for 380 yards and three scores to open the season and then conceded another three TD tosses to Matt Ryan in Week 2. They kept Matthew Stafford in check in Week 3, but there's more than enough proof here that the Eagles are a suspect pass defense -- or at least suspect enough for Rodgers to thrive. Lock him in as your QB1.

player.seasonOutlook: Rodgers enters 2019 off a relatively disappointing season in which he was limited to six top-10 fantasy weeks (eight QBs had more). Rodgers pushed the ball down field more (his 8.8 aDOT was ninth highest) and saw his completion percentage plummet to 62 percent and his off-target rate increase to 18 percent (eighth highest). On the plus side, Rodgers threw only two interceptions in 597 attempts. A supporting cast lacking depth and a new coach adds some risk, but Rodgers remains one of the best in the business and should be viewed as a strong QB1 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Odell Beckham and Nick Chubb set to consume huge workloads, Landry is no longer the Browns' top option and was more of a WR3 during the second half of last season under offensive coordinator Freddie Kitchens. But there is still potential for him to shine as a possession weapon this week against a Titans defense that struggled to contain receivers in 2018.
outlooksByWeek.2: While the target volume wasn't great in Week 1, Landry's average target travelled more than 13 yards against the Titans, resulting in nearly 17 yards per catch. The Jets have allowed 3,400 to receivers since the start of last season. If that seems like a lot, it is. Only the Saints have surrendered more yards over that span. No longer the high-floor target hog of years past, Landry is still a solid WR3 given this uptick in verticality combined with a sweet Week 2 matchup.
outlooksByWeek.3: Leading the Browns in routes and second in targets, Landry's advanced usage rates look better than his surface production. This could mean he's due for some positive regression and remains in the flex tier for this meeting with the Rams.
outlooksByWeek.4: Landry had a nice jump in usage for Week 3, when he tied Odell Beckham for the Cleveland's lead in targets. He also more than doubled his former college teammate in air yardage in the loss to the Rams. Thanks to the opportunities that'll come his way alone, Landry is a worthy WR3 against a solid secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: Landry has finished as a top 20 fantasy receiver each of the past four seasons, but he hit his lowest mark during that span last season (18th) and that was before Cleveland's trade for Odell Beckham Jr. Landry has handled a target share of at least 27 percent during each of the past four seasons, but he's unlikely to come close to that mark in 2019. The 2014 second-round pick enjoyed a 32 percent share during Weeks 1-8 last season, but plummeted to 21 percent once Freddie Kitchens took over the offense; he was 28th at the position in fantasy points during Kitchens' eight games. Landry's catch rate plummeted to 55 percent in 2018 after clearing 67 percent in all four seasons in Miami. There's enough volume to allow Landry WR3 production, but he's now second fiddle to Beckham.

outlooksByWeek.1: With the exicting young Kenny Golladay on the team, it can be easy to forget about Jones. The veteran wideout was limited due to injuries last season but had his best year as a pro in 2017. He was dealing with an undisclosed injury at some point this preseason, but if there are no red flags about his health leading up to kickoff, you can trust him as a WR3/flex option against a Cardinals defense that isn't weak against the pass.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jones failed to make an impact for the Lions as Matthew Stafford looked to rookie TE T.J. Hockenson and veteran slot man Danny Amendola on 22 of his 45 attempts. Jones only saw four targets, but caught them all, and that figures to be an outlier for the talented wideout. Week 2's matchup with the Chargers doesn't seem appealing based on last year's stats (Los Angeles allowed the fifth-fewest points to wide receivers), but they did allow T.Y. Hilton to score twice in Week 1. With that in mind, Jones remains in the mix as a WR3/flex option in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jones has spent most of his career serving as a very good secondary option in passing games, in the past complementing the likes of A.J. Green and Golden Tate.
