Currently, he serves as second in line behind Kenny Golladay. In other words, he might not be Detroit's top receiver, but that's been his role for a while and it's suited him well. Week 2 saw the Eagles allow big numbers to both the primary and secondary receivers of the Falcons (Julio Jones and Calvin Ridley), so there's reason to expect more of the same in Week 3. As such, Jones is in the conversation as a flex pick for the week ahead.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jones might be No. 2 on the Lions' WR depth chart (behind Kenny Golladay) from a fantasy perspective, but it's not a huge gap. The veteran has more catches and yards this season, while Golladay has more targets and touchdowns. Still, both have posted respectable scores through three weeks. They'll both be needed in Week 4 as the Lions host the high-scoring Chiefs. That means Jones is a high-end WR3/flex pick in almost every league.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones was well on his way to another solid fantasy campaign last season prior to suffering a knee injury in Week 10. At that point, Jones had scored five touchdowns and sat 27th among wide receivers in fantasy points. Granted his usage and production was down a bit in Matt Patricia's run-first scheme last season, but Jones has now averaged a target share of at least 19 percent each of the past four seasons (three with Detroit). He has finished top 15 in aDOT each of the past three seasons and posted a solid 8.5 YPT last season despite 33 percent of balls thrown his way registering as off target (second highest). The 29-year-old Jones is a fringe WR3.

outlooksByWeek.1: Remarkably back in action after suffering an Achilles injury last December, it's worth mentioning Sanders cruised to 94 yards on a season-best 24 yards per catch in his lone meeting with the Raiders' soft secondary in 2018. It's probably not wise to get too excited about a Joe Flacco-led passing offense, but Sanders is undeniably in a good spot to return value as a WR3 in Oakland on Monday.
outlooksByWeek.2: After a remarkable recover from an Achilles injury, Sanders led the Broncos in routes and finished second on the team in targets and yardage in Week 1. It's clear Sanders will play an integral role as a play-making threat for Joe Flacco. The Bears present a brutal matchup for Denver's offense, but Sanders is a worthy flex thanks to his strong market share and long-standing pattern of efficiency.
outlooksByWeek.3: Dominating the target market once again for Denver so quickly after a major Achilles injury, Sanders is again posting WR1 usage and production with yet another quarterback. The Packers have a talented secondary but have struggled to contain big plays this year, allowing receivers to gain 18.5 yards per catch. With some positive metrics in his favor, Sanders is a fine WR2 heading into Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Packers rolled coverage to Sanders throughout Week 3 in an effort to suppress the Broncos' top receiving threat. The plan worked, leaving Sanders with a weak line. This week, the Jaguars have two capable cover corners to work against him. But with a good deal of work from the slot and a nice share of the passing offense at home, Sanders is firmly in the flex tier for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Sanders has finished four of his five seasons in Denver as a top-25 fantasy receiver, but he also has been limited to 12 games each of the past two seasons due to injury. Sanders was terrific in 2018, catching 74 percent of his targets (seventh best) and posting a 9.0 YPT (his highest since 2014). Sanders was fantasy's No. 14 scoring wideout prior to a Week 13 torn Achilles and finished 33 percent of his outings as a top-10 fantasy receiver (10th best). Sanders is now 32 years old, but appears back to full health and is ready to roll for Week 1. Sanders has WR2 upside and is a solid mid-round target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hooper set a career-high, quietly catching 71 passes in 2018, but he scored just four times and didn't provide much yardage for that type of workload (660). He's no more than a borderline fantasy start most weeks, as will be the case against the Vikings.
outlooksByWeek.2: Hooper brought in all nine of his Week 1 targets, which is a fine start toward notching a bigger role in an offense that suddenly has plenty of questions on the ground. The passing game hasn't been in question, so Hooper looks to be a solid Week 2 play, as well. The Eagles let Washington TE Vernon Davis score on a catch-and-run as part of Case Keenum's career passing day. Matt Ryan should do well, and Hooper should benefit as a low-end fantasy TE1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Hooper took a statistical step back versus the Eagles in Week 2, despite seeing six targets. Most weeks, he'll be stuck as the third or fourth option behind Julio Jones and Calvin Ridley, which limits his fantasy ceiling. Among tight ends, however, he's still a top-15 type most of the time. Even against the Colts' solid defense, Hooper could do as a low-end fantasy starter.
outlooksByWeek.4: Hooper reached the end zone twice in Week 3 -- his first trips of the season -- and he's seen no fewer than six targets in any game this year. The Titans have allowed 13.6 TE fantasy points-per-game, preserving Hooper's chances of putting up fantasy TE1 numbers in Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Hooper doesn't get much hype, but the 2016 third-round pick enjoyed a third-year breakout last season en route to a sixth-place finish in fantasy points. Hooper ranked top five at the position in routes (474) and receptions (71). His 82 percent catch rate was second best among tight ends after he ranked fourth in the category in 2017. Hooper's primary drawback has been a lack of scoring, as he's yet to clear four touchdowns or five end-zone targets in a season. The reliable Hooper will be a full-timer in a good offense again this season and is a sneaky low-ceiling/high-floor fringe TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: The all-or-nothing statistical producer returns to his original organization, which adds him to a crowded pass-catching picture. Jackson will probably be on the fantasy starter radar most weeks, especially in Week 1 against one of his other old clubs, the Redskins. Jackson typically plays better for fantasy potential in non-PPR games that focus on yardage and touchdowns and -- be prepared to repeat this most weeks of the season -- in those cases, he could fly as a boom-or-bust WR3. He should be over a finger injury, but keep an eye on his practice status.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jackson enjoyed a revenge game against Washington, going 8-154-2 on 10 targets in Week 1. In his latest stint with the Eagles, he's again benefitting from the duo of WR Alshon Jeffery and TE Zach Ertz taking attention away from defensive backfields. Jackson's "boom or bust" makeup keeps him as a risky flex option most weeks, but the Falcons matchup keeps him there and maybe even ticks him up to having possible WR3 fantasy upside in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jackson is questionable for Week 3 with a groin injury. If he can gut through his setback and Alshon Jeffery (calf) and/or TE Dallas Goedert (calf) miss Week 3, Jackson could be in a better positon to perform for fantasy shareholders. The Lions have been poor while defending wideouts so far, so Jackson could be in for a big day, depending on who else suits up. An active Jackson would be a WR3/flex fantasy start, though you need to watch his status right up until kickoff.
outlooksByWeek.4: After missing Week 3, Jackson remains doubtful with a groin injury ahead of Philadelphia's Week 4's Thursday night matchup at the Packers. His fantasy shareholders should find another option.

player.seasonOutlook: Jackson spent his first six NFL seasons with the Eagles and now back with the team who drafted him following five combined seasons with Washington and Tampa Bay. The speedster is now 32 years old and has appeared in 16 games only twice in his 11-year career. Last season, Jackson was limited to 47 touches, but scored five touchdowns and posted an 18.9 YPR (highest) and 10.8 YPT (sixth highest). His 17.4 YPR and 10.0 YPT are tops in the NFL since he entered the league in 2008. Jackson is likely to miss a game or two and will serve as a situational deep threat behind Zach Ertz and Alshon Jeffery, but this is an offense that ranks fifth in passing attempts and third in passing touchdowns over the past two seasons. He'll see enough work to keep him in the flex discussion in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Now is as good a time as any to stream Brady in lineups. Welcome to 2019, where streaming Tom Brady is an entirely realistic and viable plan. The Steelers produced an elite sack rate last season but also struggled against big plays in the passing phase, setting up Brady with one of the more bankable projections at the position this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Brady posted his 48th career game with at least 300 passing yards and three passing scores this past Sunday night. The Patriots are 44-4 in such games. The Dolphins saw Lamar Jackson post five scores with Baltimore tallying 59 points in Week 1, setting up Brady with an ideal road matchup against a feeble division foe.
outlooksByWeek.3: Brady finally accomplished the goal he set for himself when he drafted in the sixth round all those years ago -- he compiled his 20th career rushing touchdown this past week and became the 13th different Patriots player to do so. We hear Brady is also a good passer, something that could surface facing an exploitable Jets secondary at home on Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.4: Brady is now just two touchdown passes from Drew Brees for the second-most passing scores ever and just 15 away from Peyton Manning's record. The Bills present the Patriots' first real defensive challenge this season, as Buffalo has allowed the fewest yards per dropback to passers since the start of last season. Then again, Brady has thrived against the Bills in his career and remains in a good spot to deliver fantasy value given an offense dependent on his quick-hitting accuracy.

player.seasonOutlook: Brady has finished no worse than 11th in pass attempts, completions, passing yards and passing touchdowns during nine of the past 10 seasons (the only exception being the 2016 suspension-shortened season). Despite consistently ranking near the top of the league in these key categories, Brady has posted only two fantasy campaigns better than ninth during the past six campaigns. Limited by a switch to a run-heavy scheme, Brady was held to five top-10 fantasy weeks last season (his fewest in the past decade). Adding concern is the retirement of Rob Gronkowski, as the New England offense saw a large dip in touchdowns, passing yards, completion percentage and yards per attempt during the 29 games Gronkowski missed from 2010 to 2018. Brady is still an elite player, but New England's run-first offense limits him to QB2 territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: This tall-and-speedy second-year talent was the talk of training camp thanks to developing a big-play rapport with Lamar Jackson. But his success in real games could be stunted if Baltimore continues a committee approach to the position with Andrews, Hayden Hurst and Nick Boyle. But if you are committed to starting a one tight end against Miami’s suspect defense, Andrews is the best option.
outlooksByWeek.2: Andrews was brilliant in the Ravens' opener with eight catches on eight targets, including a late touchdown from Robert Griffin III. Lamar Jackson peppered Andrews, who was targeted on a team-high 35% of the starting quarterback's attempts. With a blend of usage, chemistry and a positive matchup, Andrews is a viable Week 2 starting option against the Cardinals, who just allowed Detroit's top rookie tight end to top 100 yards.
outlooksByWeek.3: Through the first two weeks, Andrews is top tight end in fantasy football. He has secured an absurd 88% of his targets and amassed an amazing 12 first downs. Andrews consistently flashed his ability during Ravens practices prior to the season, and the hype is being realized. The Chiefs have surrendered the fifth-most yards to tight ends this season, helping Andrews' case as a locked-in TE1 option for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Second on the team with a target-per-route rate of 33.8%, Andrews is enjoying receiver-like usage during this early-seaosn breakout. The tight end, who was hampered by an injury in Week 3, was still second on the Ravens in targets despite 15 yards receiving against the Chiefs. The Browns have only allowed 77 yards to tight ends this season, tied for third fewest in the league, but usage and talent keep Andrews firmly in the TE1 tier for Week 4.

player.seasonOutlook: Andrews was the second tight end drafted by Baltimore last season, but that didn't stop the Oklahoma product from producing one of the best seasons by a rookie tight end over the past decade. Andrews' 552 receiving yards rank sixth, and his 16.2 YPR, 10.0 YPT and 10.4 aDOT all rank second among rookie tight ends since 2007. Andrews did all that damage despite playing only 35 percent of the snaps. Andrews' future looks bright, but he'll need to find ways to stay on the field with 2018 first-round pick Hayden Hurst and re-signed blocker Nick Boyle also on the roster. Andrews is a fine late-round flier, but Baltimore's run-heavy offense will limit his upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: This defense could emerge as a compelling fantasy option during appropriate matchups. Facing a Steelers team that led football in passing yardage last season isn’t a great example, as the high point total for this game suggests.
outlooksByWeek.2: A dominant showing against the talented Steelers' offense sets up this Patriots defense with arguably the best setup of the entire week with a matchup against the already reeling Miami Dolphins. Miami is led by turnover-machine Ryan Fitzpatrick, adding to the fun factor for this D/ST.
outlooksByWeek.3: The top fantasy defense through two weeks, the Patriots have allowed a meager three points to opponents, the fewest through two games in franchise history after producing their first shutout of the Dolphins in Miami since 1966. No matter who is under center for the Jets this week, they'll have trouble navigating what is the league's best secondary. Start and enjoy.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Patriots are the top fantasy defense this season thanks in part to posting five or more sacks in back-to-back games for first time since 2015. The Patriots have allowed a league-low 17 points this season, the fewest allowed through three games in franchise history and the fewest by any team since the 2009 Broncos. The Bills have been competitive on offense this season but Josh Allen is still prone to high-leverage mistakes in the passing phase, with the Patriots poised for yet another strong showing.

player.seasonOutlook: All eyes are usually on the New England offense, but the Patriots' defense has been good for a long time. In fact, their D/ST has posted seven top-10 fantasy campaigns the past nine seasons. New England struggled to only 30 sacks last season (third-fewest) but made up for it with 28 forced turnovers (fifth) and four touchdowns (tied for seventh). The Patriots ranked seventh in points allowed (325) and have ranked top-10 in the category 12 of the past 13 seasons. Fantasy's reigning No. 6 D/ST lost Trey Flowers, Malcom Brown and star returner Cordarrelle Patterson but added Michael Bennett to a core that includes Stephon Gilmore, Devin McCourty and Lawrence Guy. This is an average group on paper, but it is led by a coach who always maximizes his talent. As usual, the Patriots' D/ST is a back-end starting option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Thomas set career bests in receptions (125) and yardage (1,405) while matching his career-best nine touchdowns in 2018. Though the Saints are a run-first offense now, Thomas remains a target hog. He'll continue that role in Week 1 against the Texans, planting him near the top of the WR rankings.
outlooksByWeek.2: Thomas put up another fantasy WR1 outing in the 2019 opener, catching 10-of-13 targets for 123 yards. Drew Brees' top target will remain a fantasy WR1 in Week 2 versus the Rams.
outlooksByWeek.3: A thumb injury caused Drew Brees to exit Week 2 and is expected to cost him 6-to-8 more weeks of action. That's bad news for Thomas, his typical No. 1 target, who was picked in the first round of many fantasy drafts. The offense looked sluggish with Teddy Bridgewater taking most of the snaps after Brees was hurt, but Thomas still caught 10 passes on the day. Given Brees' injury, fantasy managers should drop Thomas to mere fantasy WR2 territory. Even with the QB difficulties, that seems about right in Week 3 versus Seattle, whose secondary has some holes.
outlooksByWeek.4: Different quarterback, similar fantasy reliability. Thomas saw just seven targets but found the end zone for the first time this year in Week 3, with Teddy Bridgewater directing the offense instead of the injured Drew Brees (thumb). Going forward, Thomas may not be the "target hog" we are used to seeing, but he'll still have a high floor for looks, keeping him in the lower end of the fantasy WR1 tier in Week 4 against the Cowboys.

player.seasonOutlook: Thomas has been in the NFL for three seasons and has finished each of them as a top 7 fantasy wide receiver. Thomas has ranked top 7 at the position in targets, receptions and yardage during each of the past two seasons. He paced the league with 125 receptions last season thanks to an otherworldly 84 percent catch rate. Thanks, in part, to super-accurate Drew Brees, Thomas has posted a catch rate of at least 72 percent during each of his three NFL seasons. Thomas has yet to reach double-digit touchdowns and has never cleared seven end zone targets in a season, but his elite efficiency and hefty target volume in the Saints' high-scoring offense is plenty enough to allow top-end fantasy production. He's a solid first-round target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Reunited with Jarvis Landry and paired with a gifted young quarterback for the first time in his career, Beckham could thrive in his debut with the Browns against a secondary that struggled to contain receivers in 2018. The Titans allowed the ninth-most yards and 12th-most yards per catch to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.2: Targeted on 12 of 43 routes in the loss to the Titans, Beckham was the clear top option in the Cleveland passing game in Week 1. However, Beckham's 10 air yards per target ranked third on the team and could stand to improve against the Jets, whose secondary was regularly gashed by Buffalo's passing attack in Week 1. Due for some positive regression, Beckham is in a strong spot back in North Jersey for a Week 2 prime-time game.
outlooksByWeek.3: With a target on 26% of his routes this season, Beckham is earning elite usage in Cleveland. The next test comes Sunday against the Rams' talented duo of cover corners. Even in a tougher matchup, Beckham's heavy involvement in the passing game should drive another WR1 performance.
outlooksByWeek.4: An average of just 5.9 air yards per target led to just 9.3 yards per reception in a quiet Week 3 outing for Beckham, who still paced the Browns with nine targets. The Ravens present a real challenge for Beckham given their deep secondary but, as the Chiefs proved, its still susceptible to the big play. Likely to command more than a quarter of Baker Mayfield's attempts this week, Beckham remains a solid WR1 option.

player.seasonOutlook: Following a tumultuous but highly productive five seasons in New York, Beckham was traded to the Browns during the offseason. After finishing each of his first three NFL seasons with 1,300-plus receiving yards, 10-plus touchdowns and as a top-7 fantasy receiver, Beckham has managed a total of 1,354 yards and nine touchdown receptions while missing 16 of 32 games because of injury during the past two seasons. Though his play came back to earth a bit in 2018, Beckham ranked top 8 at the position in fantasy points per game for the fourth time in five seasons. Baker Mayfield's new No. 1 target is a strong bet to blow by 1,000 receiving yards for the fifth time in six seasons. The 26-year-old is a midpack WR1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Chiefs added LeSean McCoy and Darwin Thompson to the backfield this offseason to compete with Williams. A productive finish to the season and strong preseason tape signals Williams is still the top fantasy option from this backfield, but a meeting with a stout Jacksonville front seven and this increased competition for work means Williams is best considered in the flex tier.
outlooksByWeek.2: It wasn't for lack of opportunities that Williams netted just 65 scrimmage yards in Week 1, as he led the Chiefs with 19 touches and earned a valuable seven targets in the win over Jacksonville. If Williams can continue to dominate receiving duties from the backfield, he's got a good shot to maintain RB2 value in PPR formats for this meeting with a generous Oakland defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: Receiving usage is the path to fantasy fun for Williams in a crowded committee. So far, he's leading the backfield in routes and targets by a sizable margin and should be considered the best flex option from the Chiefs' backfield for this meeting with a solid Baltimore defense.
outlooksByWeek.4: Expected back on the field to face an exploitable Detroit front seven, Williams should reclaim the majority share of receiving duties from the backfield. Such work drives Williams' fantasy stock at this point, especially given the Lions have allowed the second-most receiving yards to tailbacks this year.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams entered 2018 as an afterthought following four nondescript seasons in Miami in which he averaged an ugly 3.6 YPC on 133 carries and 6.5 yards per play on 112 targets. Williams barely played in the first half of the 2018 season, but Kareem Hunt's release led to a huge opportunity for him. He didn't disappoint, producing 352 yards and six touchdown on 60 touches in Weeks 14-17. Only two backs scored more fantasy points in the stretch. It's fair to be a bit suspicious of the now-27-year-old Williams after the small sample of success, especially after the team signed LeSean McCoy, but Williams still could lead the high-scoring Chiefs in touches out of the backfield. Williams was way overpriced during most 2019 fantasy drafts, but still could settle in as a flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: On the mend from a calf injury but likely ready to handle a big workload, it helps Henry's case as a fantasy prospect that the Browns allowed the seventh-most yards to tailbacks last season at a generous clip of 4.75 yards per attempt. We know Henry won't produce much in the passing phase, but the path to 20 touches is reasonable if the Titans can keep this one close.
outlooksByWeek.2: Henry made the most of his receiving opportunities in Week 1, turning in a 75-yard scoring reception that was the longest for the franchise (including the Oilers) by a tailback since 1985 and marked his first career game with a rushing and receiving score. We shouldn't expect such, if any, success as a receiver this week against the Colts, but roughly 20 touches and a dominant share of red zone work still supports borderline RB1 value for this bruising back.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Titans split backfield snaps evenly between Henry and Dion Lewis in Week 2, yet Henry still out-touched his mate 17-to-4 in the process. The Jaguars haven't been stellar against the run this season and we remember Henry's success against Jacksonville last season, helping his case as a solid RB2 play this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Splitting routes nearly evenly with Dion Lewis and consuming all of the valuable rushing chances, Henry is a solid RB2 option heading into this meeting with an Atlanta defense that has already allowed 290 rushing yards to tailbacks on the year.

player.seasonOutlook: It isn't often that a player has nearly as many rushing touchdowns as he has receptions, but that was the case for Henry last season. The oversized back rushed for 12 scores (third-most) thanks to 13 carries inside the 5 (fourth-most). Despite playing a situational role most of the season, Henry's 238-yard, four-touchdown effort in Week 14 vaulted him into a larger role down the stretch. He was the top-scoring fantasy back by 17 points from that point on. Henry has been very efficient as a rusher (top-three in YAC each of the past two seasons) but has yet to clear 15 receptions in a season. He's expected to take on the largest role of his career in 2019, but that doesn't figure to mean much of an uptick in targets. That limits him to RB2 territory, but upgrade him in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Baltimore’s backfield led the NFL in rushing yards per game (149) during the final eight weeks of last season. Ingram should enjoy a heavy workload in an offense that relies heavily on the ground game, especially against Miami, which allowed the seventh-most yards per rush and the sixth-most rushing scores in 2018.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ingram's first carry as a Raven went for 49 yards, and his five touches within 10 yards of the goal line led the league in Week 1 . While he wasn't targeted once on his four routes against the Dolphins, Ingram should feast, along with Lamar Jackson, in what could be the league's best rushing attack. The Cardinals have allowed 2,595 rushing yards to opponents dating to Week 1 of last season, the most in football. All signs point to another strong showing from Ingram.
outlooksByWeek.3: Ingram struggled to get untracked for Baltimore in Week 2, when he had a modest 1.7 yards before initial contact per carry vs. Arizona. There is real hope for a Week 3 bounce-back effort in Kansas City, which has allowed 111.1 rushing yards per game to backfields since the start of last season—the fifth-highest rate in the league. Despite a lack of upside as a receiving threat, Ingram is well positioned for early-down success this Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.4: In the loss to the Chiefs in Week 3, Ingram became just the third player in Ravens history with 100 rushing yards and three rushing scores a game, joining Willis McGahee (2009) and Jamal Lewis (2003). It was also good to see Ingram with four targets on his 16 routes in Week 3, which was a clear uptick. The Browns are allowing the seventh-fewest yards per attempt (3.7) to tailbacks this season, yet Ingram's rewarding goal-line role and improving receiving usage support a solid RB2 projection.

player.seasonOutlook: Ingram joins the Ravens after an eight-year stint in New Orleans. Following a slow start to his career, Ingram has averaged 4.73 YPC, including 2.10 after contact, the past six seasons. Those marks rank first and second, respectively, among 31 backs with 650 carries in that span. Ingram ranks second in the league in rushing touchdowns (39), second in rushing OTD (37.5) and tied for first in carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line (61) the past five seasons. The 29-year-old Ingram is a strong bet to pace the extremely run-heavy Ravens' backfield in carries and possibly targets. Ingram has a real shot to eclipse his previous career-high carry total of 230 (2017). He's a flex option who can be upgraded slightly in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Seahawks allowed the 10th-fewest yards to receivers last season, but target volume often leads to fantasy success. Boyd is the top receiving threat on the team with A.J. Green sidelined and is poised to demand as many as 10 targets in Seattle on Sunday afternoon.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tied for the Bengals' team lead with 12 targets in Week 1, Boyd's average depth of target (6.92 air yards) played a big part in limiting his yardage. Boyd netted 9.52 air yards per target last season, suggesting he's due for more valuable downfield usage against a 49ers team that has allowed the sixth-most yards per reception to receivers since the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.3: An impressive catch rate of 81.8% fuels strong value for Boyd despite not yet having many big plays. But keep this in mind: the Bills' stellar pass defense has surrendered the fewest receiving yards.
outlooksByWeek.4: Boyd, who leads the Bengals in targets by a sizable margin, is a fine WR2 option against a struggling Steelers secondary,. He's due at least a quarter of Andy Dalton's attempts for this Week 4 matchup.

player.seasonOutlook: Cincinnati selected Boyd in the second round of the 2016 draft. The former Pitt star's first two NFL seasons weren't particularly inspiring and he was even a healthy scratch at times in 2017. It's safe to say the light went on in 2018. With all eyes on second-year John Ross, Boyd came out of nowhere to post a 75/1016/7 line and finish 17th among receivers in fantasy points despite missing two games. Boyd was only 11 behind A.J. Green in targets during the eight full games the two played together. His efficiency was also terrific (71 percent catch rate, 9.6 YPT), though touchdown sustainability is a real concern after he saw only four end zone targets and posted a 3.3 OTD. Boyd is still only 24, so it's possible we've yet to see his best work. He's a solid WR3 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: When Jacoby Brissett and Hilton worked together over a full season in 2017, Hilton had a career-low catch rate and touchdown total. Then again, Brissett has more experience and should pepper Hilton with valuable vertical targets against a solid, if still exploitable, Los Angeles secondary. There is a fairly wide spectrum of outcomes possible for the Colts' wide out in this contest, with enough upside to keep him in the WR2 discussion.
outlooksByWeek.2: A strong opener saw Hilton become the first Colts receiver with multiple scores in Week 1 since Reggie Wayne did so against the Saints in 2007. Hilton, who had some rewarding red-zone attention, led the team in routes and targets, offsetting his average of just 7.4 air yards per target. Up next are the Titans, who rank 24th in yardage allowed to wide outs since the start of last season. With a good matchup and rewarding role, Hilton is a solid WR2 for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Three scores through two games is a solid clip, especially in the wake of Andrew Luck's departure. The Falcons struggled in coverage against the Eagles' second unit receivers in Week 2, revealing some promise for Hilton to excel in this matchup.
outlooksByWeek.4: A re-aggravation of a quad injury saw Hilton leave Week 3 a bit early after producing a solid line that included his fourth score of the season. We'll need to track Hilton's progress in practice this week ahead of what is a juicy matchup with a Raiders secondary allowing the eighth-most fantasy points to receivers.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite missing two games last season, Hilton finished as fantasy's No. 14 scoring wide receiver. Hilton has now finished all seven of his NFL seasons as a top 27 fantasy receiver. Hilton, who has missed only four games in his NFL career, averaged 16.7 YPR last season and has ranked above the 80th percentile in the category each of the past five seasons. He has ranked above the 85th percentile in YPR four of the past five seasons. Hilton's main concern area is touchdowns, as he has never managed more than seven scores in a single season and hasn't caught more than six since 2014. Hilton has ranked outside the top 30 wide receivers in end zone targets during each of the past two seasons. Hilton's value takes a hit following Andrew Luck's retirement, especially considering he was held to four touchdowns and a 55 percent catch rate (both career lows) with Jacoby Brissett under center in 2017. Consider Hilton a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sanders is the most exciting name in the Eagles backfield, but the rookie still must contend with the capable Jordan Howard, who remains the most seasoned goal-line and early-down worker. Sanders, however, could still thrive for fantasy purposes, considering Doug Pederson's offense has propped up multiple backs in the past. Against Washington, who has many flaws on offense, Philadelphia could ride Howard late in the game if the predicted Eagles domination holds up. Still, Sanders deserves flex consideration for Week 1 fantasy lineups.
outlooksByWeek.2: Sanders led the Eagles backfield in carries but didn't gain much (25 yards) in the process. Expect Philadelphia to continue its committee approach in Week 2, though the Falcons, who were just trampled by the Vikings' ground game, is a friendly matchup for the visitors. Sanders counts as at least a fantasy flex and has major upside if he were to become the hot hand over Jordan Howard.
outlooksByWeek.3: Sanders has spun his wheels, managing just 2.5 yards-per-carry so far this season, even as he remains the top option in the Eagles backfield. However, Week 3 could be tantalizing. The Lions have allowed 169.5 RB scrimmage yards-per-game. Sanders and Jordan Howard could each enjoy a big day, and the Eagles may rely more heavily on the run if at least one of Alshon Jeffery (calf), DeSean Jackson (groin) and Dallas Goedert (calf) is forced to be inactive. Sanders looks like a strong flex play with the upside of a high-end RB2 if things go in Philadelphia's favor, allowing them to chew time off the clock late.
outlooksByWeek.4: Sanders totaled 126 scrimmage yards in Week 3 as the Eagles dealt with numerous injuries to its receiving corps. The rookie contributed 73 yards through the air to help with that issue. Though he lost one of two fumbles, he should be back to claiming a big role in the backfield for Week 4, especially with the quick turnaround for Thursday's visit to the Packers. Count him as a high-end fantasy flex, at the very least.

player.seasonOutlook: The Eagles selected Sanders in the third round of April's draft. He joins fellow newcomer Jordan Howard atop the Philadelphia depth chart. Saquon Barkley's replacement at Penn State racked up 220 carries in 2018 and was one of the nation's most elusive backs, evading one tackler for every 6.4 touches. Sanders is shifty and agile, but not especially explosive and he's struggled with fumbles (five last season). Sanders checks in at 5-foot-11, 211 pounds and is a solid receiver and kick returner (which also fills a void for the Eagles). He had a very good combine, which was highlighted by a 4.49 40-yard dash and position-best 6.89 three cone. Sanders' shiftiness makes him a terrific complement to between-the-tackles bruiser Howard. Expect the two to split carries, with Howard the primary goal-line back and Sanders busier in passing situations. Sanders is a fringe top-25 fantasy back.

outlooksByWeek.1: There are high expectations when a player is selected with the top pick in the NFL Draft, and things don't always pan out right away. That said, the Cardinals are going to give Murray the keys to the offense right out of the gate in a matchup with a below-average pass defense. The Lions allowed the third-highest passer rating in the NFL last season, meaning this is a good first test for the rookie. He's easily a QB2 in Week 1, and it's not out of the question to consider him as a starter in a 1-QB league.
outlooksByWeek.2: Murray threw the ball an impressive 54 times in his NFL debut as the Cardinals climbed back from an early deficit to force a tie. He only completed 53.7% of those throws, however, which is a little on the low side. Plus, for such a dynamic athlete, you'd like to see more than just three rushing attempts, at least from a fantasy standpoint. Facing a Ravens defense that kept the Dolphins in check in Week 1 and that ranked as the third-worst matchup for opposing quarterbacks last season, it's safe to keep the rookie on your bench in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Murray has looked good at times during his first two NFL starts, flashing the ability that prompted him to leave behind his career in baseball for the gridiron and enticed the Cardinals to select him with the No. 1 overall pick in the draft. However, he's still yet to produce anything with his legs and has only two touchdowns in two games. That's not really a recipe for success againts a Panthers defense that has kept both Jared Goff and Jameis Winston to low double-digit fantasy points over the first two weeks. He's got the volume to merit a start in 2-QB leagues, but otherwise he's best left on the bench.
outlooksByWeek.4: Murray is one of the busiest quarterbacks in the NFL, leading the league in passing attempts through three weeks and carrying the ball 14 times, as well. That hasn't translated directly into fantasy points, so he's on the cusp of QB1 status rather than being at the top of the scoring charts. However, it's still an encouraging sign and a situation unlikely to change any time soon. He's going to air it out under head coach Kliff Kingsbury and has proven to be effective enough to take opportunities and make big plays. He's worth consideration for a start in Week 4 against the Seahawks,  against whom Andy Dalton, Mason Rudolph and Teddy Bridgewater have all thrown for a pair of touchdowns.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray was the first overall selection in April's draft and a strong favorite to open 2019 as Arizona's starter. The Oklahoma product is extremely undersized (5-foot-10, 207 pounds), but exceptionally efficient with his arm (he set an FBS record with an 11.6 YPA last season) and highly productive with his legs (1,001 rushing yards while averaging 7.2 YPC last season). There have been only three top-10 and six top-14 fantasy seasons by rookie quarterbacks over the past decade, but all who accomplished that did a lot of damage with their legs -- an area in which Murray will shine. Rookies are always risks, but Murray's skill set and path to snaps means he should be viewed as a QB2 with QB1 upside. He's worth a late-round pick in your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: Prescott had a relatively uneventful offseason. At least he showed up while his contract negotiations escalated. Once again set to lead a run-first offense -- focused on either Ezekiel Elliott or a Tony Pollard-led committee -- Prescott remains worth rostering in most fantasy games, though he typically will settle into the high-end QB2 territory. Mark him as one of those against the Giants, who have little consistency to offer with the ball outside Saquon Barkley, meaning Dallas should keep things focused on the ground game in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Prescott rolled over the Giants in Week 1 with a ridiculous 96.9 Total QBR, enjoying the debut of Kellen Moore's offensive scheme. This change looks to be an immensely positive development for Prescott's fantasy upside, as the design featured more three-wide sets and accentuated downfield plays more often. Prescott averaged 281 passing yards, 1.5 passing scores and 25.5 rushing yards in his two clashes with Washington last year and profiles as a decent QB1 in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Prescott again looked like an MVP in Kellen Moore's new offense on Sunday, torching Washington for three more passing touchdowns, with just four incompletions over 30 attempts, while adding 69 rushing yards to the mix. He's looking unstoppable at the moment and conveniently will get the Dolphins at home in Week 3. Prescott may get to take off the helmet early, should Miami suffer its third straight blowout loss, but he'll probably have plenty of opportunities to do damage before he goes. He's a strong fantasy QB1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Prescott has accounted for three-plus total touchdowns in each of his first three games with Kellen Moore as offensive coordinator. The new, more inventive system in Dallas has raised Prescott's weekly fantasy ceiling. The Saints have allowed the most QB fantasy points-per-game this season, so slide Prescott into your fantasy lineups with confidence as a QB1.

player.seasonOutlook: Prescott has finished sixth, 11th and 10th, respectively, in fantasy points during his three NFL seasons. Efficient and consistent, he's finished in the upper-third in completion percentage, has thrown either 22 or 23 touchdowns and has rushed for exactly six touchdowns each of the three seasons. Prescott was limited by 56 sacks last season (second most), but the return of center Travis Frederick should help cut that number down. The 25-year-old gets the job done with his arm, is one of the game's better rushing quarterbacks and has Amari Cooper, second-year Michael Gallup and now Jason Witten and Randall Cobb at his disposal. He's a fringe QB1 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Somewhat overlooked in drafts this summer given his age and absence from the field last season, Walker is again poised to command around 20 percent of the Titans' passing offense. The Browns were one of just eight teams to allow as many as 1,000 yards to tight ends last season, evidence Walker can return starting value in the opener.
outlooksByWeek.2: Leading his team in routes, targets, catches, and touchdowns is a pretty good way for Walker to declare his return to the top of the Tennessee passing game. Now that we know Walker is back in full force, we can get excited about this promising matchup with a Colts defense that has one glaring flaw; tight ends. Since the start of last season, the Colts have allowed the most yards (1,258) to tight ends by a sizable margin (league average is 881).
outlooksByWeek.3: Walker didn't match Week 1's awesome output, but still led the team in targets with an encouraging depth of target around 11 yards downdfield in the process. The Jags have been middle-of-the-pack defending tight ends since the start of last season (18th in yards allowed), while a steady stream of targets should sustain another strong showing from Walker.
outlooksByWeek.4: The most valuable receiving threat on Tennessee even late into his career, Walker's strong batch of targets each week drives TE1 status ahead of a meeting with a Falcons back seven allowing nearly 13 fantasy points per game to the position in PPR formats this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Walker is back after his 2018 season was derailed by a broken ankle after only 38 snaps. One of the league's most underrated players of the past decade, Walker entered last season having posted three consecutive top-five fantasy campaigns and five straight top-12 finishes. Prior to 2018, Walker had appeared in at least 15 games in seven consecutive seasons and, from 2014-17, finished no lower than ninth at tight end in targets, receptions and receiving yards. Walker turns 35 years old this year but is again positioned for a large target share in Tennessee. He's a terrific mid- to late-round target with top-five upside.

Lutz finished third in fantasy points last season after posting finishes of seventh and six during his first two NFL seasons. He attempted 53 extra points last season (second most) and has never ranked lower than second in the category in his career. Lutz has steadily improved his efficiency, improving from an 82.4 field goal conversion rate in 2016 to 86.1 percent in 2017 and 93.3 percent last season. The latter was fifth best in the league. The 24-year-old is one of the game's top kickers and works in the Saints' high-scoring offense. He's a solid starter in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: The coaching staff has talked up Bernard netting increased work as a third-down threat this season. Before we get too excited about the Danny Woodhead vibes, it's best to remember he's still a change-of-pace back behind a top talent at the position. At best, Bernard is poised as a fringe flex in deep PPR formats given the Seahawks allowed the third-most receiving yards to backs last year.
outlooksByWeek.2: A strong pickup this week given Joe Mixon's ankle injury, Bernard was third on the Bengals in scrimmage yards and topped the team with nine touches in Week 1. If Mixon sits or proves limited in Week 2, Bernard could emerge as a worthy flex against the 49ers. Otherwise, he's a risky flex option given a minority share of touches and snaps.
outlooksByWeek.3: Bernard didn't cut into Joe Mixon's work in Week 2 despite playing just nine fewer snaps in the Bengals' loss. Bernard was held to fewer than two yards per touch against San Francisco and could again struggle to find room against the Bills, who have been solid against the run dating to the start of last season.
outlooksByWeek.4: Back to a complementary role with just five total touches in Week 3, Bernard isn't worth flexing for the Bengals' meeting with a shaky Steelers rush defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Bernard has been one of the league's best receiving backs since he entered the league in 2013, but his role has diminished in recent seasons as a result of injuries (10 missed games the past three seasons) and the emergence of workhorse Joe Mixon. Bernard posted career-low marks in both carries (56) and receptions (35) last season. His 4.7 YPT was second-worst at the position and marks the first time in six seasons that he didn't finish top-20 in the category. Undersized and uninvolved near the goal line, Bernard hasn't cleared four touchdowns in a season since 2014. He is no more than a backup who steals some passing-down work from Mixon. His primary value is as a handcuff.

outlooksByWeek.1: Due to split rushing work with Austin Ekeler with Melvin Gordon still out of the picture, Jackson's lack of work in the receiving phase limits the appeal of his fantasy profile. It also helps to consider the Colts allowed the sixth-fewest yards per carry to tailbacks last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Efficient as a rushing threat (9.5 yards per carry) in the opener, Jackson is a talented rushing complement to Austin Ekeler, but not nearly the receiving threat his peer has become. Without a strong stake in the passing game Jackson is tough to trust in fantasy lineups, although the Lions' soft rush defense (4.7 yards per carry to backs since the start of last season) at least offers some promise.
outlooksByWeek.3: Offseason talk of an even workload split between Jackson and Austin Ekeler has quickly shifted to Ekeler as the featured back and Jackson as an early-down reprieve. Without any really upside as a receiver, Jackson is outside the flex tier for this meeting with the Texans.
outlooksByWeek.4: The Dolphins are weak enough against the run to consider streaming Jackson in deeper leagues and for those with desperate running back depth charts. In a normal matchup, Jackson might see the ball for seven to 10 rushes, but in this contest as sizable road favorites, there is at least some appeal for rewarding closing duties.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gallman retains his role as the Giants' top backup behind Saquon Barkley, but that's not going to account for fantasy-relevant work most weeks. Leave him on waiver wires until alerted otherwise.
outlooksByWeek.2: Gallman found the end zone in Week 1. Saquon Barkley didn't. Gallman's score came in garbage time, though, and he unsurprisingly ran as the clear backup. Leave him on fantasy waiver wires for Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Gallman didn't record a touch in Week 2, reminding us that if the game is close, Saquon Barkley will consume all possible backfield work. No need to add him off the waiver wire for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Gallman is expected to step in as the top back in place of Saquon Barkley, who's out for at least a month with a high-ankle sprain. In Week 3, after stepping in when Barkley got hurt, Gallman had just 13 yards. He'll face a Washington defense that's given up only 19.9 RB fantasy points-per-game, ranking in the bottom half of the league. Volume alone should carry him to fantasy flex territory, regardless of matchup, though the Giants probably will bring in another body to take some of the work, so Gallman probably won't get a fantasy RB1 workload most weeks.

outlooksByWeek.1: The loss of an All-Pro caliber safety hurts the Chargers' D/ST in several ways, but this matchup with a defanged Colts offense could still prove quite rewarding. This proves additionally accurate if the Chargers' talented pass rush shows up early, adding to the sack and turnover upside we covet from this position.
outlooksByWeek.2: The run-heavy Lions present a mediocre matchup for the Chargers in that Detroit has done well protecting Matt Stafford over the past year and thus have limited turnovers during this stretch. The Chargers' talented pass rush presents some upside, however, as this group is in the streaming tier at the position ahead of this trip to Detroit.
outlooksByWeek.3: Facing Deshaun Watson is never a great matchup, but there are some reasons to think this Chargers D/ST could produce respectable results. Namely, the fact Houston has allowed Watson to be pressured on 40.7% of dropbacks, the highest rate in the league and far above league average.
outlooksByWeek.4: If there was ever a week to line up the Chargers' defense, this is it. Los Angeles enters Miami as massive road favorites and with their duo of defensive edge menaces in place this could be a fun outing for fantasy purposes.

player.seasonOutlook: The Chargers D/ST posted its worst fantasy finish in three seasons but finished 12th in 2018. The unit has ranked top-eight in points allowed each of the past two seasons but fell from sixth in both forced turnovers (27) and interceptions (18) in 2017 to 16th (20) and 15th (13), respectively, in 2018. Corey Liuget, Darius Philon and Jahleel Addae are notable offseason subtractions, but Thomas Davis and early-round picks Jerry Tillery and Nasir Adderley were huge additions at need spots. Additionally, edge rusher Joey Bosa will be healthy opposite Melvin Ingram this time around. Add that group to Casey Hayward, Derwin James (once back from IR) and Desmond King, and you have a strong unit on paper. Consider the Chargers' D/ST a top-10 unit.
